{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oxford}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid16269226\charrsid16072257 {\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid16269226 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Your name, as you said, is Elizabeth Eade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Your present address - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}23 Forest Road{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, Headington?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And you're a widow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Could you tell me the year of your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 1925.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the year of your birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 1895.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the birth place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Swerford in Oxfordshire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How many years did you live in the house you were born in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I suppose about eight years. When I was about eight years old. We had come to the village some years before a rector, a bachelor, and he had difficulty in running his house and he made rather a friend of my mother w
ho was a very nice and intelligent, helpful woman and he used to come round to our house and tell his troubles and ask advice and eventually we all went to live at the Rectory, which made a difference to my life in as much as though I was a country girl g
o
ing to the country school and having all the other country ways, I had the advantage of living in a very big house and meeting all sorts of people that I otherwise wouldn't and I was a voracious reader, so I read everything. Everything you see, and got in
terested in philosophy and all the things that the ordinary country girl doesn't, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 That was a very excellent, fortunate opportunity for a person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And how long did you continue to live then in the Rectory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Till the Rector then, he eventually married. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
He was getting on in life then. He eventually married a young woman and we then left and my parents then went to live at Great Tew. My father was Estate carpenter and so it was nearer to his work, you see. And then I just went 
out to earn my living. I went out to service, you see. 'Cos it was the only thing you see in those days there was no higher school than the village school, nearer than Chipping Norton or Banbury.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 And we were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  all too poor. There was no transport at a
ll, you know, only the carrier's cart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you moved to Great Tew, about how old would you have been then? You were about eight when you went to the vicarage I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. I think around eighteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 About eighteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well now, let me see, I must get this right. Well anyway the Rector was married in 1913.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And you moved about then did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. We left the Rectory then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And when you said your father was the estate carpenter, was that at the Mole House at Great Tew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Wel
l, you see, the whole village belonged to the Squire and everybody in the village more or less worked for the Squire and the houses all belonged to him. And we had quite a nice house there. It was a fairly big house though quite different from living in t
he Rectory. on \{BLANK\} Although we had always kept on our cottage in the village because when the Rector went on holiday he had to get a locum to do the job, you know. \{BLANK\}
 But from then I just went, you know, locally, not out of the county. I just went 
in doing jobs, you know. I wasn't trained for anything other than domestic and you see, we knew so many people who one would go to work for, people we'd met, visitors coming to the House "would you come and help us out?", you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 So that's how I started and I've never done very much other than domestic work.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well, of course, there were virtually no opportunities.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No opportunities, that was the only thing for girls, you know, in the village. No matter who in the village, apart from the parson an
d the Squire, even the very rich farmers, their daughters only went to the village school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. That was the way in Great Tew, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Swerford and Great Tew. You see, well one couldn't have the transport, and people couldn't really - well there
 was no other way. No way of getting there unless you went to a Boarding School which new people could afford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Whereabouts was it that you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well you know the pub, well there's a lane. Going down the lane our house was on the left going down a long path.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, we saw that path. I was interested to see it. Its an unusually pretty village. And did you miss Swerford at all when you left?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well it was so close we could either cycle or walk, you know. And my sister went on living there 
and so really it was only, as good as just being there. And I spent a good deal of my holidays, I'd just break it up between my home and my sister, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And which sister was that. Was that the older one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. I had got another one who lived there for a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And your brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 My brother went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 at the age of seventeen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 And he was 2 and a half years older or younger than you?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Older. I'm the middle one. There were seven of us. I was the middle one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh there were seven, so the family was only half way really when you showed me the photograph.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Just tell me now, in order, the eldest was - could you tell me the names too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Emily Louisa, then Mary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what was the gap between those two?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think there was somewhere around two and a half years between each of them. As far as I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And so after the second one, Mary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Then my younger sister lives at Banbury, she's 70. One died at the age of eighteen months, I did
n't know her very much, the one below me. And then the youngest one, she died on the Christmas Day after we were married. It was rather tragic thing, it rather broke my parents up you know. She was very much adored.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. How old was she then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Twenty-three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you were born have you any idea how old your father was, or any means of working out how old he would be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well let me see, now, I'm 75 in January. Well isn't it difficult I'm not awfully good at working out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You told me when he died.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He died at the age of 78 in 1937.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So if he were alive now he would be 110 and so he would have been about 35 when you were born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Around that I should think. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you know how much older or younger you mother was to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 My mother was a little younger I think but she died at the age of 90 in 1947.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
So she would have been 102, so she would have been about 8 years younger, than he was. Did you say she died at the age of 90. Now I've got that wrong, she was about 2 years older than he was then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Roughly the same age as he was then? That's enough to go on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Where did your father come from? Was he a Swerford man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He was a Swerford man. He was born at Swerford. No, no, I don't think he was bor
n at Swerford. I think his parents lived somewhere near Leadwell, in Oxfordshire then they went to live at Swerford, but of course I can't remember. But he grew up in Swerford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 My mother was actually born in the parish of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Westminster
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh was she.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. And her mother died when she was born and her father died when she was six years old. Her Grandmother, who lived at Bloxham brought her up and she had to go out to service at the age of, oh I suppose when she
 was almost a child because her father who was a comparatively well-off man, I think. He lost his money. I think he got in with not a very good crowd after his wife died and he lost his money with the result that my Grandmother, my mother's, my great gran
dmother, was a widow, she couldn't afford to do a great deal for my little mother so my mother had to go out to service, but she was a very clever cook. We all were very good cooks, you know, all our family. Her name before she married was Jelliman.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I can remember back. I can remember Queen {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Victoria
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s Jubilee, which was in 1897. I was born in 1895. I remember there was a sort of feasting in the village. In the village barn. I think I hadn't been well. I did at one time have a T.B. gland taken out and 
I think it must have been at that time. We didn't go - well my mother did perhaps take me to the feast. I remember seeing in the barn the people with meat on the plates, you know, feasting. And then going through the rectory, this was in the rectory yard,
 
and going through and up into some fields where they were having sports and I remember the scene. My mother carrying me to the sports. I remember the barn with the people feasting and then my mother carrying me through the fields to this. I remember all t
h
at. And I remember all the old people they had such small wages, such large families. Lots of them couldn't read or write. They suffered and they were so tolerant of suffering. They thought "yes, we're supposed to suffer, there's nothing we can do about i
t". And I've always had a great sort of feeling, can't God do something about it, why should they, why must they? And I wanted to give and I wanted to help and people used to ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Can you remember any particular family that you were involved with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well I was involved with, I had a sort of passion, for older people. I liked to listen to them talking. And there was one old lady, she was very deaf and she had a very luxurious thing, an ear trumpet, and as a little girl I thought I could then be able t
o talk to her. And I went down one afternoon to talk to her and I couldn't think of a word to say and there the poor old lady was listening with a trumpet. My mother was very deaf. All my family were deaf. They don't sort of speak plainly. A lot of people
 
in the village were deaf. Mostly, I should imagine from wax in the ears, which they didn't attend to in those days. You see they never could afford to have a doctor the ordinary village person. But they managed. And what they didn't hear they didn't hear.
 
They didn't talk a great deal. The ordinary village person doesn't talk you know. And they had to get up very early in the morning to go to work and then arrive home late at night and all hours they would be working and then it was just a supper and bed. 
N
o conversation, and this is what one lacked. Where I gained, and my family would gain, was being at the rectory where one would get a little different. We had conversation. We talked. I always wanted to talk and the rector would talk to me, people who cam
e would talk to me, you see, and I would read and then they would know I was interested.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was your mother in a housekeeping capacity, or was she a friend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Well it was this and that. He was a scholar and he wrote books and so though we were fri
ends and we met up at times for the odd meal, usually we went to school and his luncheon times was one o'clock and well we had ours at twelve, and so we didn't always, you see, not like that. But you see we were friends, but my mother just managed the hou
se. We had to have somebody to help because it was an enormous house and we had somebody to help and somebody to help in the garden and like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The person who helped in the house, did she live in, or come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No she didn't. We just got people
 from the village. The odd ones. Perhaps younger one would come and occasionally an older one and then we'd have somebody who'd come once a week to do the washing and they'd use the big wash house. In the yard there was a special place where they had a ta
p, which was a luxury. There were no bathrooms, you know, even in this large rectory. No bathroom. No bathroom and only one water closet. In the whole of the village they had the pit lavatories. Do you know the sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I know the type.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They clean them out once a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you were there though, in the rectory, did you have your own kind of sitting room and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh there was an enormous kitchen. We had an enormous kitchen and lots of bedrooms and play rooms and the house wa
s divided, you know. On the roof there were two roofs and then a lead passage like that between the roofs and we took our blankets and mattresses and slept out there all the summer. It was lovely and the swallows would come and sit along the roof and twit
ter to us, you know, just as we were waking up in the morning. That was lovely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
What I'm trying to get at, purely from the factual point of view, about the household was, I mean you had a free kind of easy relationship with the rector?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But did you to some extent keep to your own part of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. We had to because when he was in the house he was writing and reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that in the library?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He had a library, yes. And he wrote several books. He was quite a scholar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Had your father ever had another job besides being a carpenter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. He was a proper tradesman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He was, yes. And he always did that work all his life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Always did that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Do you know if he ever did any part-time jobs to sort of eke out his wages?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well no, he wasn't awfully strong, and for the last part of his life, for several years, well after my little sister died it was such a tragic thing, he never worked again. He was never awfully strong and he was never able
 to do another job. But my mother did you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What work did she do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
When I say she did, after we left the rectory, we had this fairly big house at Great Tew and she was a wonderful cook and full of energy at that moment and we took in paying guests.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. How many did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we could only have two at a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And she gave them full board did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Full board - yes everything. Nice people and we made great friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Very nice way of earning money that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And during the first war she had to take in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 evacuees}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 . You see we left Swerford and went to Great Tew just before the war started. Yes just before the war started, I can remember the day that the war started. And then we had to take in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 evacuees}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  and she h
ad, which was a great experience for the village a lot of Jewish children. I don't know how she managed to get them but they were rather darlings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were they from the East End of London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 East End of London, but their parents were very well off I 
think, because they'd come and visit the children when they could and of course they supplied a lot of things that were very much needed because the rationing was very, very poor. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Very harsh.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No \{BLANK\} for a while wasn't there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh it was awfull
y bad. And so by taking people, you see, you had extra rationing cards and my mother was a wonderful cook. One old man in our village used to say she could make a tasty meal out of an old boot, you know, if it was given to her. And it was like that. And s
o, you see, with the Jewish people she had to do their particular types of food. I mean they didn't eat pork or bacon or a lot of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were they very particular? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 
I mean were they very orthodox, that she had to not mix butter and meat and those sort of things like the very orthodox?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well I think they had to relax a tiny bit. But she did, she was quite conscientious, and she did as well as she could. But you know, if you're in a concentration camp starving you wouldn't bother whether it was pork 
or whatever, you'd eat it wouldn't you. I mean needs must when the devil drives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was this the second World War?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 That was the first World War.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. But you say they were actually quite well off, so I suppose they had come away from the bombing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. They had come away from the bombing. And we'd got a little - outside our house there was another cottage, which used to be a little cottage which mother used the upstairs for the store place for apples or vegetables and below she'd use f
or a wash house, or brewing or whatever. They'd brew their own beers and wines, you know, in the country. And so, when the war started, and we were short of room we used this little cottage - the bedroom made quite a nice bedroom so we would use that and 
the visitors could have our two rooms inside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I see, yes. So in the war she had the Jewish children and no other paying guests presumably, because there wouldn't have been any room for them would there really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I don't think she had other than }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 evacuees}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
 during the war and then afterwards she had, oh well, I can tell you one person who went was Basil Blackwell and his wife. They went for weekends and what not. And various well known people would go. You see, she had a vast connection with people beca
use people would come to the rectory, you see, visitors, or for a meal (oh wonderful meals because she was a wonderful cook) and so you see "oh, wonder if we could go there, wonder if she would have us?".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So she would put people up in those days. Do t
ell me more about her cooking, because I'm very interested in the style of cooking in the past.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
The only thing - she made such wonderful soup, and I can make wonderful soup. She'd buy bones, marrow bones, you know from the butcher. And in those days 
meat was so cheap, I mean when we were at the rectory. She used to buy bones and we had heaps of vegetables. A vast kitchen garden, so you see we had heaps of vegetables and she'd buy bones and make the most wonderful soups and I \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 would take it 
round to the old people in the village. And, of course, there wouldn't be meat, but they were all thick jelly, you know. After you'd stewed the bones and with plenty of vegetables. And I used to take to one old man in particular. He was rather a grumpy ol
d man and I took a large jug of soup it was all thick jelly and I said would he turn it out, I had to get him to turn it out into his own basin or saucepan. I wanted to take the jug back. And he turned it out and he said "not a bit }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 o'meat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  in it". Oh he wanted something he could get his teeth into.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So did you take it back again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no, I let him have it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 One hears such a lot about this sort of thing. Taking soup to people. How did most people receive these gifts of soup?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh they were glad.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 People were genuinely glad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 People were so hungry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was he exceptional then in complaining about the meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh well he was rather a grumpy old man anyway. But I mean that's how he would talk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But he'd eat it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, of course, he would but he would have been glad to have found a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 lump}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  of meat in it as well. That was it, you see. But it was so nourishing and good and it smelt so good. My mother made it taste so good, on wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Your mother, was she quite a lot better off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well, not better off, but in a way that, you see, one saved fuel. She had a very little wage. What I call a wage, but she had to have a certain amount. But he wasn't very well off. You see his income was only about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3676755 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 250 per year. And it was a tith
e. A rent you see, got it from the tithes. And the farmers who were supposed to pay the rent some of them were very bad about it and didn't pay. And he was awfully badly off. So to have mother there managing things he was able to live much better, you see
,
 and we had the advantages. Of course my father always had a good garden, he kept his garden well planted. He used to keep pigs too. We'd keep a pig which we could kill. We'd have our own Home-cured ham and bacon, you see, to go on, which was a great save
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did your father do the curing too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
My mother did the curing. Yes my mother did that. And everybody in the village who could afford it would keep a pig, that was their mainstay. And they would get from the brewer to help out, you know, the cheap
est thing before the pigs got to the stage where they had to be really fattened, they'd get stuff from the brewers. You know, the grain that had been used and it had a certain amount of nourishment in it, and somebody would go to Hook Norton where Harris'
s Brewery was and get sacks of this and that would help out and then ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Would somebody get it for other people too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes they would. They'd go with a cart, or donkey cart, or something and get it you see. And then they would - everybody planted e
very inch of their gardens. Every countryman was a good gardener.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was this both in Swerford and Great Tew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 All the country places, I think. And they had the potatoes. All the small potatoes and the farmers would have, and people who had them, wo
uld have large coppers in which they would boil up masses of, we used to call them 'pig' potatoes. All the tiny potatoes they'd boil up and mash them up with a little of the meal, you see, which saved. And then in the end you see they would have to buy wh
a
t they call barley meal which was more expensive to fatten the pig up, which would be killed. Usually they killed the pig up when it weighed about fourteen stone. I think that was usually about it. I think some people would go on if they liked meat very f
a
t they'd get them fatter. But people with very young children they didn't like the fact meat very much, but the old men would eat it, it didn't matter how fat the meat was, you know. And they had very little else. The people in the village were most frigh
t
fully poor. They'd have large families and do you know the man would only earn about fifteen shillings a week. And when you think - I know one family in particular they had fourteen children, I don't know how many miscarriages in between, because in those
 
days, you see, they hadn't got the pill and all that sort of knowledge, and they had to have what babies came along, and owing to the very poor diet they would lose (mercifully I think) they would lose quite a lot of babies. But several brought up quite l
a
rge families. And my Godmother now she's alive, she's 97, and she was one of fourteen. You see, the eldest of fourteen and she's still alive. But they lived so much on bread and potatoes, and if they had a pig they could have some bacon. But it was usuall
y
 bread, potatoes and vegetables that they could get in the garden, but in the winter it wouldn't be much. I mean you'd perhaps get swedes and turnips and so the living was very poor. Some of the men would go and try and snare a rabbit. But I think I had a
 
very poor opinion of what I call the employers, the ruling classes. They weren't awfully kind or knowledgeable about the sufferings of the people and when you think of the Tolpuddle Martyrs that story, of course, sends me up the wall, because I realize qu
i
te how the people in my village suffered. And with all these children to feed, or keep boots on their feet, you almost hated. You could feel the mothers would almost dread them putting their feet to the ground because of wearing the shoes out, you know, a
nd to get the shoes mended. And a lot of the girls at school, some of them didn't know what a nightdress was, or underclothes. And I remember at school the school was so cold in the winter, we had such very hard winters it seemed, and just a small round }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 bake}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  stove which the school master would stand in front.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 At Swerford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
At Swerford, yes. And the schoolmaster would stand in front and the poor little shivering beasts, you know, wouldn't find any benefit from the stove. And the chilblains. We all 
had chilblains. And you see there was not much in the way of hygiene taught, you know, not in schools. And all the coats and hats and things were hung up in one place. Well there were quite a good deal in those days, because nobody thought anything of it,
 
because they thought all classes would have to suffer from the same things - fleas and lice. You see that was the thing. It wasn't a thing that you could possibly avoid. Because my mother was clean and a lot of the other mothers in the village would be cl
ean. Well there were several very dirty families and as a punishment sometimes in school the clean ones were made to go and sit by the dirty smelly ones for punishment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What an awful thing to do. Awful to both sets of children. Cruel.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And y
ou see the clothes, the garments, all hung together in one lobby, and the lice would drop off. So there was always this sort of business, hunting, going on at night. You see, mothers would have to do hair and doctor up, wash the heads, and all the rest of
 it. Then hunting for fleas and all those things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they do it at school too - examine the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No, they didn't. In my day they didn't. But afterwards they did, you see, in my day none of that had started, and it was accepted. Well of course the school master had a daughter and she herself would have the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She was at the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She was at the school, yes. And the farmer's daughters too. All well off people, well known.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 This was at Swerford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Swerford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You were saying about your opinion, which I heartily agree, about the people who employed those hard up farm labourers. Who would }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 employ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  the bulk of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well you see there was what they called the Park. It was a large Mansion in which, in my day, it was wh
ere the Squire lived. And he owned quite a bit of property and he had a large lake and large grounds. But at the time, in my time, he'd already died and left behind a mad wife. She was quite mad and she lived at the park with a full staff of servants and 
a lady looked after. I think she had been, I don't know if she had been trained as a doctor or hospital matron or something, but she went there as a guardian for this old mad lady and she ran the house and she saw to things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Like in Jane Eyre?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yo
u know, I've been listening to Jane Eyre, and it so reminds me of this sort of mad thing. I had seen her at a distance. We used to get as near as we could to the House when we were playing, and I have seen this little old lady with her guardian, who was a
 
big woman, an imposing strong woman. But the Squire he was rather a bad man and the story went, of course I didn't hear it in my young days, but I heard it in after life. That the Squire was very unfaithful and he would you know, have affairs with the mai
d
s and get them into trouble and then they would have to leave. And it was supposed to be one family living in the village the man was the butler and the wife was either housemaid or lady's maid or something, and it was said in the village that the Squire 
had made it worth his while to marry this girl - the butler to marry this girl to take the baby, which he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you think it was true, this story?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I should imagine so because the eldest daughter (they had three children altogether) the eldest 
daughter was quite unlike the others and the people who knew would say "oh, that belonged to the Squire all right, you know". But they lived in such comfort and such a good house. A big house and a good house that I think that it was more than possible an
d they said that his treatment of his little wife sent her mad. This is, you see, of course, I can only say what I was told.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well that's what we want to hear. And while you were living there, what part of your childhood was the Squire still alive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh, he'd died and only this old lady. We used to think of the house and feel of it as though it was haunted because it had this sort of haunted feeling because of this little old lady who, I mean as far as we knew she might have been quite harmless, but 
that was just incapable of looking after herself. There was evidently quite a good deal of money, because the lady who looked after her, she was a big woman and she dressed very elaborately, and she had a very dignified look. She wore long silk dresses, y
ou know. She'd come to church and the servants would follow. She would come in the carriage and pair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But this was only a short distance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well about half a mile, three quarters, possibly, up long drives you see. And she'd always arrive just that 
bit late and the little servants following behind and they were little bonnets in those days you know, and they followed behind very neatly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Would that have been all the servants who would have come to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The indoor staff and I think most o
f the people who worked outside. I think it was more or less, it had to be a must. They must go to church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. The indoor staff, but not the outdoor staff?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well yes, I think they did. I think in those days people did go to church. For one thing
 there was nothing else much to do and one went to church. It was a social thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 To see people, I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I used to go to choir practice. The only time I ever got out in the evening was when I went to choir practice. Mother would never allow u
s out in the evening. We always had to be in before {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 8}}}8 o'clock{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Was that an accepted thing in the village?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well she was a little more strict. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 
Well some of the parents were strict, but I think she was especially strict and especially nervous and she demanded that we should be in. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I remember once I stayed out, I was going to be allowed to go to the May Day dance. It was my first, I was about fifteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The May Day dance, was that in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. In the village. The children would
 go round singing May songs and have dressed up and have the May Queen and singing May songs. Then in the afternoon they would have sports and a tea. And then in the evening the grown ups would have a dance. Well, the first dance that I was being allowed 
to go to for a short time, until {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 10}}}10 o'clock{\*\xmlclose}
. A woman, who'd come to live in the village, she was a Londoner, she said she'd teach me and two or three of my girl friends how to dance. So we went to her. I was terrifically pleased. And some man from the villa
ge was there playing a concertina and she was teaching us to dance. And I was frightened, you see, I was terrified of offending my mother as she was so very strict, and I kept saying "Oh, is it {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 8}}}8 o'clock{\*\xmlclose} yet?" "Oh, no." Well the next thing that happened my
 mother was there to see if I was there and she thrashed me. Yes, she thrashed me. I managed to beat her up the street. I could run faster but she chased me up to bed and she said of course she wouldn't let me go to the dance. And she wouldn't listen. She
 
was deaf, you see, and she wouldn't let me explain. And this woman was terribly upset, and my friends, because she wouldn't listen, because the deaf person can have it all their own way. With the result that she never heard, she wouldn't listen, and I was
 broken hearted. I was shattered to be beaten at that age. I was grown up. I looked - I was as big as you nearly. And just grown up and feeling grown up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the pleasure of the dancing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Being thrilled. And I was broken hearted but she didn't let me go. She didn't relent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was she always like that, if she said something did she stick to it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
She stuck to it. In one way its good but, you see, there the other way ... I had a feeling, you see, at the time that I was born everything happened.
 My father had an illness. We had pigs that died - in those days they hadn't people going round and getting you into trouble if you had pigs with swine fever, or foot and mouth disease, you see, none of those things. But one farmer he sold a set of pigs w
h
ich had fever and my father had bought two and they died. And 1895 was a terribly hard winter, snow and ice, snow on top of the hedges almost, for about six or seven weeks. Men couldn't work. There was a lot of sickness. And I think my mother said that sh
e spent the last of her own savings the year I was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Would that have been savings from when she was in service herself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And she said that she lived practically on oatmeal porridge because she was very proud and very poor, you see, and i
n those days they'd no dole only the parish. They'd say you must go on the parish. Well if you were very humble and very poor and really starving I think the parish fund, I don't know where if came from, they would allow people a few shillings, I - think,
 
or some coal, or a piece of meat, or I don't know what. But mother wouldn't, she was rather a proud woman, you know, and she wouldn't do that. So I was rather weakly as a child and I always rather felt that my mother was always a little more down on me th
a
n the others. I feel, well you can imagine, expecting, she had those three children, then another one coming and nothing to feed them on, you see. And I always felt, and I feel these days that I'm rather knowledgeable about women. I didn't have children o
f
 my own, I couldn't have them. Well I had two miscarriages, but I didn't have children. But I know that what a mother suffers, it must influence the child, and I was born with a responsible mind, a suffering mind, so aware of suffering, so aware of not be
ing wanted. My father adored me and I adored him. But I felt, when I was a child, my mother I seemed to irritate her. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 
And I was rather sweet, you know, I was rather religious, naturally religious, and I used to walk around the fields and pick violets and look for birds' nests and sing hymns and pray to God because I was unhappy. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And I used to do everything I could to try and help mother to make her love me. I felt she didn't. I expect she did really. But it seemed as how, you know how it comes, that there wo
uld be a sort of resentment - more children coming along and not being able to prevent it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Father go to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He lived at Swerford then, in the beginning, you see, and he used to go to Great Tew to work at the Estate as a carpenter. And he'd get
 up at 5 in the morning. When I was a little girl I would get up, I would hear him. And we used to lay the breakfast at night (this was when I was quite tiny) We would lay the breakfast at night and he would get up in the morning and he would have to ligh
t
 the fire with sticks and coal, to boil the kettle, there was no gas or electricity. And he would make the toast and not being well off he'd make what we called "tea kettle" broth, which was bread and you'd pour boiling water over and you'd put in a bit o
f
 either butter or dripping if you hadn't got butter, and some pepper and salt, and it was quite nice. And I would sit on his knee and help him have his breakfast and have a little with him, you see, and then he would go off to work. And I would wave him o
ff to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that when you were living in your own cottage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes in our own cottage. I think I was about eight years old when we went to live in the rectory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Your mother didn't mind you doing that, getting up early?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She didn't know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She didn't know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
She was asleep upstairs, you see. And this was our precious little time together. And then he'd come home at night and there were Chestnut trees and Walnut trees in the fields that he'd come through and he'd bring me a chestnut
 or a walnut, or something, in his pocket. And once he'd come home and he'd nearly cut his thumb off. I was a very good nurse, you know, I always wanted to be a doctor or a nurse, and my mother, I think she was expecting a baby at the time, anyway she fai
nted at the sight of it. But I took over and bandaged it although I was still tiny, it was before we went to the rectory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What sort of a man was he? Could you describe him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh he was very gentle. Rather, very refined looking. Well there he is, I don't know whether you can get anything from this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Quiet, gentle. My mother was vivacious, talk, talk, you know, and I think he irritated her a bit, being deaf he couldn't answer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He was deaf as well was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No he wasn't but she was you see. They couldn't converse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
My father was such a gentle person but I think his gentleness irritated her. She would have liked him to go and collect me from the dance, I think, and beaten me, but he wouldn't do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. What did she beat you with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 A stick.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 A stick, Did she do that often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well if we offended, she would rather have used the stick, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 On all of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, on all of us. And we were sent to bed very early at night and of course we didn't want to sleep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. What do you mean by very early?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well between 6 and 7.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Really! Well that was very early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And we wouldn't want to sleep.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Would that have been, at what age, that you didn't sleep? Up to when?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I'm talking now of before we went to the rectory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Up 'til about seven or eight years old, you would be sent to bed as early as that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And you see we'd all have to sleep, we had two large beds, in one room in our other house where we were. And we were playing 
one night and my old grandmother who lived in the village then, she'd gone down, and she was a very strict old lady, and we were having pillow fights or something. And they called up several times to tell us to go to sleep but we were quite oblivious, you
 
know. I was just in the act of jumping from one bed to the other and, you see, somebody was coming upstairs. And one of my sisters, who was a little quicker (they were older you see) she knelt down pretending to be saying her prayers, and I was caught in 
t
he act of leaping, you see, and the other one she started, she was doing something else, but we all had a bit of a smacking and had to be put to bed. And you see in the summer when of course when they were poor and we had the holidays, when you're out run
n
ing about in the fields, which we spent a lot of our time doing, we'd get very hungry, so mother would keep us in bed fairly late so as to shorten the day a bit, and then we'd have to go to bed early. For one thing it was less strain on the larder and les
s
 strain on the shoe leather. So she did that. It was a sort of economy thing. But we spent all our playtimes, I mean we had no toys, nothing bought, we made all our own, and do you know we could get a tremendous amount of happiness in our games. We'd go i
n
to the fields and climb trees and find birds nests and play games. You know, making houses with all bits of broken pottery and flowers and things we could find. And then there were Revival Meetings. I think it was at the time of Moody and Sankey. And they
 
would have prayer meetings on the village green and people would be asked to come and be saved, you know, and we got very worked up about this, and so we used to have our prayer meetings in the fields and sing hymns and pray. And I remember at one meeting
 
on the village green, I was quite small then although we were living at the rectory, I think we'd only just gone there, and they had one of the meetings on the Sunday afternoon. And they were quite illiterate the old men who would come to preach, they wer
e
 the old Wesleyan Chapel people. I heard in a programme last night, something to do with bringing the Churches together, an evangelical movement you know. We were the Church of England and we did look down on the Chapel people you know. There was a little
 
Chapel in the village. We never thought of them as, you know, even the poorest people were quite class conscious and you know had their own little sets and what not, and we looked down on the Chapel people. And these old parsons, they hadn't got; they'd c
o
me from different villages to preach, and then when they had these open air meetings in the summer, the camp meetings they'd pray in quite a stumbling, illiterate way and very emotional. They'd cry and sweat and carry on, you know, and ask people to come 
out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I was quite impressed because I was rather religious and I remember at this one particular meeting a young girl had got married and in those days they had very small waists, you know, and long skirts, and black picture hats and she'd come to the
 meeting in her wedding clothes and they were calling upon people to come out and be saved. To come to the Lord Jesus to be saved. And this girl, very dramatic, very emotional "Oh, God, I'll come", you know, she went out, and most dramatic and most impres
sive. My greatest ambition when I was a small child was to wear a dress and hat like that and be saved on the village green.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh I was tremendously impressed. And of course, when you think of it, in their stumbling way a lot of the vi
llagers they were very religious in their, very ignorant of course a lot of them couldn't read or write, and the parson the one that we had he was above their heads, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 This was the one you lived with at the rectory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. He would preach 
above their heads, because after all he was a scholar and he'd come down to the school to take the Friday morning scripture class and he would be teaching the categorical }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 imperative}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 , which I don't expect you know about, if you were a scholar you would know
. If you ask a great religious scholar the Archbishop of Canterbury or somebody like that they would know about it. Well of course we didn't know, we couldn't understand much what he was talking about but all I could remember was the hypothetical and the 
categorical, he used those two words. I never had a dictionary and we didn't use dictionaries and I didn't know what they meant. \{BLANK\}
 You see, with all these poor frozen people, and half starved and half asleep, a lot of them, he would be saying and of course as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Hegel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
 said, as Cant said, as so and so said, quoting from the great scholars. What did they know, they couldn't even read or write a lot of them and this, as I grew older I was irritated to think that people weren't more knowledgeable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mean that the village people weren't more knowledgeable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. No, the people who taught.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes that's what I would have thought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The teachers. You see, they didn't know the needs of the people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He, himself, though was a kindly man wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He was kind but rather had a great opinion of his own importance, you know. Of his family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mean his background and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, although he was very poor, his background. And he expected the village people, I mean, they had to rather bow the knee to him.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They did, did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. Oh everybody had to sort of, the men touch their hat and the girls had to curtsey. Oh he demanded all this you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did anybody not comply, I mean were there any rebels in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Only me in my heart, and I couldn't do it very much at that age. But I've rebelled since. I've had terrific battles with these types of people, saying what do you mean by behaving in this way. And he didn't understand the sufferings of t
he people. And he rather enjoyed a large social round, you know, all the villages around. He would get to know all of them and they entertained each other at their garden parties, their dinner parties, he'd only got a bicycle to get about on in those days
 but he'd go for miles to a dinner party or a garden party.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So though he was a scholar he had a taste for social life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, he loved it. And he loved food. And he loved the good things of life. Yes, oh indeed he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. So he would return these dinners would he? And your mother would cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, and my mother would cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She must have been a very clever manager then to do these big dinners on his income?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes indeed she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And wines did he serve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes wines, indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He must have bought those, did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well no, my mother made wines. She made the wine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And he served that at his dinners did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He would serve that. Sometimes she would have, for very special occasions, he might get a bottle of cl
aret just for the dinner. But he, himself, he couldn't normally afford to drink not every day. But all country people, you know, made wines and sort of beer and those sort of things. They made wine out of anything. Any type of vegetables or herbs or any o
f those sort of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was he particular about who he associated with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. Terribly class conscious.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I thought myself in a condescending way. He went to visit them as the great man, you know, I thought it was patronizing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you think they felt it like that too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well they accepted it, you see people accepted in those days that an educated person was someone to be looked up to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Would they have liked him to be different, or did they want him to be like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I th
ink they rather resented him if he went in when the men were home, or coming home, because the men very often had to go to work and they'd come home to their main meal at night, which would perhaps be a bit of a bacon and vegetables or something like that
. And if he called then I think that they rather resented it and I don't think that they enjoyed his visits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No they didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you think he did? Do you think that he thought he got on all right with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I think he thought i
t was a sort of duty visit. Well honestly I hope, well he's dead now, I hope he'll understand and realize that I'm saying what I felt. This is true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It was only typical of hundreds of others at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Typical. And this vast round of people, t
hey'd keep servants you see, I mean if you had a thousand a year you could keep several servants, in those days because they paid them so badly and fed them so badly that it cost nothing to keep them. They worked them every hour that they could get out of
 them from about five in the morning 'til, if they had their parties, 'til twelve o'clock at night you see. And there was nothing you could do about it, there was no union for domestics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, it was tough. And was it largely people with titles and those sort of people he would entertain?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Everybody, you see they accepted him. He came from a fairly good family, and he was accepted everywhere. Though he was a poor man. He found it difficult to get married because of course in those days mothers expected their daughters to be able to be kept.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well looked after, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
He happened to marry a girl who, she was related, distantly, to the people I was living with. I went to live with, you see, his friend, in Oxford, and he met her there. And he tri
ed to get married before but you see he couldn't get married because he hadn't enough money. If the girl hadn't money, but I think the girl he married she had a certain amount of money and her mother had and when she died she left her more, so they were a
ble to live and they had three sons. And they were more comfortable after he married because she was able to supply some of the money.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What about the school master? It was a school master, wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. A school master and a school mistress.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Just the two?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And a woman who lived with them, and his daughter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They all worked at the school, did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well three worked at the school and his daughter went to the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 His daughter was a pupil, of course, you mentioned that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And they came from Lancashire I believe. The wife died quite early on and he went on living there with the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did the wife teach you, or had she died before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, she taught me up to the time that she had cancer and died. 
She was very ill and of course in those days one didn't hear very much, you see, ailments weren't discussed very much. It was one thing or the other, you either had consumption or you had a stoppage. Usually it was cancer, I suppose, or appendicitis which
 
wasn't diagnosed; and people they said died of a stoppage, you see it was like that. And she died, but it was mentioned that she had cancer and I was awfully, well always wanted to know everything about illnesses, and I heard that the doctor had been and 
she was taken away and they'd operated. And I was so bothered about it, and I had this sort of urge to operate and get rid of things. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 
And I went, there was, through the park there was a lake and a waterfall, and under the waterfall there was stones and we used to go there and paddle and catch crayfish. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
And I went one afternoon, just after this school mistress had died, and I caught some crayfish and I just thought I'd operate to see if they'd got cancer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How old would you have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I was qui
te young, I suppose. It was before we went to the rectory. And I operated on them. I always had a pocket knife - we had a large bag for a pocket underneath our dresses so as not to wear our dresses out you see - and I was like a boy, I'd always got a knif
e
 and string and masses of things in my pocket. Marbles and all sorts of things. And I was on a slab by the side of the waterfall. I caught the crayfish and I operated, not thinking I was being cruel at all. No, I was just doing the job. I was experimentin
g, and they'd all got cancer as far as I could see, anyway it was an awful mess that I found inside them, which I racked out with my little knife, and bound them up and put them back into the water.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And they all died I suppose as the result of the operation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I didn't know that. There were no hearts to beat, you see, within those bosoms. No hearts to love or hearts to melt. No they were just - I was experimenting without any knowledge of crayfish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you tie them up with bandages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, string. I'd always got a piece of string in my pocket.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the school master himself, who did he associate with? I mean who was in his class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh you see the school master was a betwixt and betweener. He thought he was on a par with the farmers. 
And the farmers were just, well you see, there was the rector, the farmers and the schoolmaster. Well the rector was there and it was just sloping down you see. Well we were more or less, as we lived at the rectory, we always went to the Christmas parties
 of the farmer's daughter and the school master's daughter, whereas some of the other children in the village didn't you see. We had just that little bit of you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But I didn't like the school master. He was a sadist. He enjoyed beating. 
He would beat unmercifully for no reason. Girls, boys, whatever. And, funnily enough, only about three or four years ago I went back to the village for the flower show on the bank holiday, and I saw an old man there. He's a little older than I am but he l
o
oked old because he was a sick man. And of course I was delighted to talk to him, he was one of the old village men, and he'd gone to school at the same time as I did but he was a bit older And we talked about the school master. We was in the village scho
o
l and it all came back, you see. I said "Do you remember this?", and he said "Do you remember that?" And then he was saying about the old school master. He said "Ooh, he was a devil." He said "I remember him once" he said "Old Jack Kench (he was one of th
e
 boys a tall, scrawny, anaemic looking boy) he'd done something and the school master made him walk up some steps and he slashed him across the legs unmercifully". And, as I say, he used to stand in front of this potty little coke stove in the middle of t
h
e back of the school and we couldn't even feel it you know, we got none of the benefit. And there was one little boy in particular. I had chilblains not on my hands but on my feet. One boy, he was the most poor, miserable, boy and he had the most dreadful
 
chilblains, all cracks on his hands and they were all purple and bleeding and he had to go up to have slashes across his hands. The school master would beat him. All sadistic you know. I'm sick with it, I get almost into a frenzy with passion you know whe
n
 I think back on what one had to tolerate and one couldn't run from it, we might as well have been in a concentration camp. We couldn't escape the suffering. The village people couldn't escape the sufferings they had to endure by having to work when they 
w
ere sick because there was no alternative. They had to work every hour possible there was not the union, nothing to protect them. When they were ill and could no longer work in meant they had to go to the Work House, which they all dreaded. It was like go
ing to prison. They was dark and frightful places.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Where was the nearest Work House?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Chipping Norton, and they dreaded it. Now my parents, of course everybody would have it in their minds, "oh I wonder what would happen to us if we get older." N
ow my parents never had to go. We looked after them you see and they didn't have to go, which was a very great blessing. But I know some of the older people who went. The tragedy for them. The heartbreak. And I knew that when I'd go to see them when they 
w
ere sick, when I was a little girl. You know the poor old things, one sitting each side perhaps or sometimes they'd be in bed, or crying, "Ah, what's to become of us, I expect it'll mean the House." It was 'Ouse, they didn't put aitches in those days. And
 
oh the suffering. And I remember once I went home for a holiday and I sat on the village green talking to the father of this boy, this man I was talking to in the school, and his father lived to be quite old and his wife died earlier on, and he lived up t
h
ere quite close to the rectory. And this old chap he could think back further than my time. My greatest joy was to sit there for hours on end, sometimes talking to him, and hearing things further back than my time. But some of the things that I did rememb
e
r. There was one family they had fourteen and they were ever so poor. The man, I think he was a tradesman, but in those days they were only earning about fifteen shillings or one pound a week, and he had fourteen children. And this old chap was telling me
 one day, he said, you see the baker used to come round from the next village bringing bread two or three times a week, he'd come in the covered horse and cart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Which village was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Hook Norton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And a lot of people you see t
hey would live on bread and potatoes and that sort of thing and this old man was telling me, he said "Now there was old George Cowger", that was how he said it - it was Cowgere. "There was old George Cowger" he said "'E 'ad all them kids; couldn't afford 
to feed 'em. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 
Old Sammy Timms (that was the baker) Old Sammy Timms 'ed come round and old George's wife 'ud take great loaves o' bread, couldn't afford to pay for 'em, so old Sammy Timms the baker 'e county courted 'im." }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you understand what I mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He took him to the County Court?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes to try and get the money. And of course he said it all in his own language. "And so Old George, '}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  'ad to go to Chippy, and the Judge said to 'im, 'ow many children av '}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  got?' 'Fourteen, Sir.' ' 'Ow much money do ye earn?' (I don't know if he said a pound or fifteen shillings). 'Go on, 'tis no good trying to get anything out of '}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 .'"
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 A common thing!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What's the use.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And when do you think that would have been? If he told you that was it before your time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I knew these; I knew them all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You knew the families?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, but you see I was a child at the same time I was knowing all this, but you see I didn't know this particular story.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But you see I knew all thi
s. And you see, this man's family grew up and it was one of this man's daughters, the Cowgeres, who went out to be converted. And his grand-daughter, the daughter of his youngest daughter, she went as kitchen maid with her aunt who was a cook housekeeper.
 
She hated it, she was a rebel, she was rather like me in a way. She was a rebel, she hated it, she hated service, she loathed everything to do with it. Anyway she had to go, there was no alternative, but she stood it as long as she could and then she ran 
a
way. She ran up to London, and what she did in between I don't know, but eventually she got hold of a man, a very well-known man, a man of title and a multi-millionaire, and I don't know what story she told him but he married her. He educated her, changed
 her name and married her. And he died not so long ago and he had vast properties you know, Scotland, London, in the Bahamas, France, all over. And this girl she carried it off you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, and they entertained and he presented one 
of his big London houses to the nation for one of the political purposes and I saw in 'The Times', you know, all the guests that were there. One of the royalty and members of parliament and their wives. And how they were dressed. And there was this girl, 
this little kitchen maid that I knew who had gone to school, she was younger than I am, and she was this old George Cowgere's daughter, who was county courted because he couldn't afford to pay for his bread.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you ever meet her afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She
 wasn't allowed to come back to the village. But once a year, a lot of her relatives lived in the village, 'cos there were a lot of them went on living in the village and had their families, and once a year a large hamper of luxuries would come to be divi
ded among them. But she never come back to the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But I've seen her name in the paper, and when he died there was a big service in St. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Paul\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 , and some of the royalty were there and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14958908\charrsid2904646 M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 embers of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14958908\charrsid2904646 P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 arliament and all the rest of it, titled you see. She carried it off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh I can believe it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I saw her pictures in 'The Tatler' and so on, you know, and all the society papers. But you see they didn't know she changed her name.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you say she changed her name, she changed her first name too, did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I suppose so, yes, because I saw, oh it was in "Who's Who", and it was Eva, I forget what name it was, but I know it wasn't her name because her mother's married name was Messer, and it was Eva something but it wasn't Mess
er you see, and married to Sir Henry Price.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What a thought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But it's in "Who's Who".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
On that theme, when we were talking about the school master, you were saying there were the farmers. Were they, any of them, men of learning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. No they were quite illiterate, but very snobbish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And well off I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Very well off, but very snobbish. And they thought that they were very superior. Well this is a story, it'll show the parson, well he really thought he was above the lot and they all ought to cow tail to him and he expected them to call him "sir".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Really. What did he call them then, Mr.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He would call them Mr. So and so, yes. Yes but they would have to call him "sir". But I remember one woman, she was a farmer's dau
ghter, she wasn't all that young either but she belonged to the choir, everybody sang in the choir, and we had quite a good choir. And he used to take the choir practice, because he was quite musical and he would take the choir practice and it came to som
ething and she became quite excited and said "Oh, Mr. S \{BLANK\}". "Call me Sir when you're speaking to me."
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Really, how terrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And I remember, as a little girl, that was before we went to live at the rectory I was in the rectory, on the recto
ry premises, sitting on the top of the step playing with something on the top of the step on the outside yard. And the parson was going off on his bicycle, going off for the night somewhere. Well that was at the time when he kept maids, which of course wa
s a bit hopeless for him because he couldn't control the situation. And he'd forgotten something, and one of them came flying out of the door in her cap and apron, I remember this, I was a tiny girl sitting there playing, and she called "Mr. S \{BLANK\}
, you've forgotten this," and he said "Oh, how dare you speak to me." You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And would he expect the school master to call him "sir".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh well he did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did the school master comply with this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes he would do that. But they were
 more or less a little bit, you know. Oh you see the classes in a village. You see we were just that little bit, my father was a tradesman that's a big distinction in a village where its mostly farm labourers, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were there any other tradesmen in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes, masons, the building trade. It was usually farms and the building trade. Nothing else much in my very young days. And the young men they'd either be apprenticed to the building - and it was rather sad because one man who got marri
ed late in life married a younger woman and they had a son and, with great difficulty, because he was earning such a small wage, they apprenticed his son to a builder carpenter and he'd just finished his apprenticeship and then the war came and somehow he
 couldn't go on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He couldn't finish his time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He couldn't finish his time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How sad, because it was such a sacrifice for people to have a son apprenticed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And between the tradesmen and the labourers was there quite easy, social intercourse, sort of thing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes that was fairly easy. They would sit together. And, of course, the only recreation, I mean, for men when they could have any leisure at all, some men would go to the pub. Women never went to the pub. It would be a b
ad thing in those days for a woman to go inside a pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did some go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
One or two, but they'd be people who'd come from the town, you know. Perhaps a town woman would marry a country man and they wouldn't think much of it but they would be despised by the respectable villagers. It wasn't done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But the men would go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The men would go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And how was the pub divided?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They were mucky little places, then. I mean there was no division, just a tap room. They didn't have divisions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did your father go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 My father didn't go to the pub, no. Mother made our own drink, you know, so father didn't go to the pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You said she made wine - did she brew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Brewed all sorts of wine. Yes, and home made beer, which was, all it cost wa
s the sugar which was quite cheap in those days and a bit of yeast, which - we didn't get yeast in those days we got barm. Barm which you'd get from the brewers - you'd take a can, a covered can, and the brewer at Hook Norton (we'd walk to Hook Norton, yo
u know) there were more shops. Hook Norton was like a big village, they had a co-op and a chemist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I wanted to ask you if you ever had any other relatives living with you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 My old aunt, my father's sister, who was about my mother's age, lived with
 us for the last few years of her life. It was after we went to live at Great Tew.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 'Cos that was about 1913 you said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, but I think it was a little bit later than that that she came but she was there for, oh quite a few years, with my mother 
she died first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. 'Cos I have to know about the period up to 1918. That's why I wondered but you think probably not at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I should think not quite, I should think she went a little bit after that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 People came by the day to help your mother while she was at the vicarage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what did they call your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Mrs. Woodford. Well, just called her Mrs. Woodford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Mrs. Woodford. Yes, and what did she call them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well just their Christian names.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Their Christian names, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And sometimes it was the girls and sometimes an older woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. If it was an older woman would she also be called by her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Christian}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. Everybody, I think that was the thing in those days, you know. Everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mean who were doing domestic work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Anybody really. I mean few people, even when they got older. I think of the men in the village, quite old men, you'd call them by their Christian names or a nick name. So many people had nick names in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So why was your mother called Mrs. Woodford then, by them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well she was, you see, I mean after all she was running the household. She was never, it was like that in the village, two or three sort of people well she would be called... 
there wasn't as much familiarity with my mother and father as with some people. I mean the majority of what I call the village people, they were called by their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Christian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  names, but I think apart from relatives I never heard anybody call my mother anything
 but Mrs. Woodford, or my father, well just his friends or relatives would call him William, but the ordinary village people it was Mr. and Mrs. Woodford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You also said that somebody used to come in and do the washing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they do your mother's and father's and your own washing, the whole family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
All the washing. She had a whole day washing and in those days it was this always washing on Mondays, Ironing on Tuesdays. Women in the village who just dabbled out little things they wer
en't considered, you know, it wasn't the correct thing. They should do all their washing and it had to be done properly, boiled and hung out on the line. But of course a lot of people in the village were poor and they hadn't the amount of washing. They ha
d
 to wash their little garments quickly and put them on again. And I remember one woman telling me, this was in later years, her husband had a very dirty job, and he'd make the sheets dirty and she was rather particular and she said after he'd gone to work
 in the morning she'd wash the sheets and put them out and dry them and put them back on the bed. You see they hadn't quantities of clothes. But I suppose we had and then with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 rector
\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  clothes and a good many visitors, you know, and so the thing was we 
had the big wash house at the rectory, you see, a special place with water in the tap, which everybody hadn't got and very big boiler. Clothes were boiled and hung out on lines and then taken in, damped down, folded up, ironed the next day. The woman woul
d come in to iron the next day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And then when your mother left that and went to Great Tew what did she do about washing then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well there was somebody in the village, she did up to that time, I mean she was fairly active, she would do her own as 
long as she could but then she became rather arthritic and somebody in the village would do it for her
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see, yes. That would be after the first world war, though, wouldn't it? When she was older I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what about clothes? Could you tell me how your mother managed to clothe you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well of course we were many more garments in those days underneath than we wear now. There was always what was called a chemise - that's a little vest - and when we were younger a liberty bodice, k
nickers and petticoat, and then the dress, and going to school we had to wear a pinafore to keep our dresses clean, and we usually had, mother didn't let us have pockets in our dresses because of wearing them out and making the dress shabby so she made us
 a little pocket bag to put underneath our dress, you see. Well I used to have all sorts of things rather like a boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Like your pocket knife for the crayfish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I always had a pen knife and marbles, handkerchief and a few pins and things like that. Pencils.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did she make your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes she was very good making and making do, and you see the younger ones had to have cut down things, you know from the elder ones. And the material in those days was very much better than now. Very much 
more substantial and they'd go on for such a long time that they could be cut down from one generation to another, almost, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did she ever buy any garments that you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not very much I don't remember. But there was at one point you
 see when we got a little more grown up, a little bigger, requiring more, and being a little more vain possibly, there was a girl in the village who made clothes and she'd make things possibly a little smarter for the older children and we were always, yo
u
 know, very tidily dressed, but my mother had rather puritanical ideas, she didn't encourage us to be vain. We had to be neat, tidy, clean, but vanity was not allowed, you know. And I was rather inclined, I liked beauty and I liked pretty clothes and it r
a
ther hurt me a little bit to have to wear garments handed down from my sisters or some that weren't very attractive. But if they fitted, if they were decent, I mean mother didn't encourage me, I mean she was very strict, you weren't allowed to sort of com
plain or criticize. You were given these clothes you must wear them, and no nonsense, you know. You were sort of under the thumb.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you ever refuse to wear a garment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, only in my mind. I was very miserable sometimes, because some children th
ey may not have been cleaner or tidier, but they had a little more attractive clothes. Some of the village women, there were two or three who were not country people, they'd come down, married men, you see some men in the village, there were no industries
, you see, and the men used to go to London and places to get work and then several of them married women, wives, you know, and then would come to live in the village. But their habits were quite different from the ordinary village women.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were those the ones you mentioned who would sometimes go to the pub which was considered not the thing to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes, they would do that and they weren't awfully particular. There were one or two, I mean their morals were not quite as strict and they would get into 
debt, you know, they couldn't manage on the small wages and they weren't used to managing in the way that the old country people did - they had such ways of never washing anything and making such good use of every little thing, every bit of material and i
n
 the way of food, you know, there was nothing wasted. They had ways of making use of everything, so little money but rather independent in their minds that if they could make do with something they didn't have to buy, you see, so they didn't have to get i
nto debt.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what about your shoes, how were they cobbled would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well there was a man in the village who mended shoes. Well we never wore shoes, only for when we got a little older we were allowed to wear shoes, but they were always boots, buttoned boots.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 That's what I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 meant}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  really, of course. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And low heels of course, and it was only when we'd grown up a little bit that we were allowed shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did you have separate footwear for Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes always, and never
 allowed - and there was the difference I noticed and we all noticed. You see there came a point when people in the country, as I knew them, whereas in the old days there were clothes for Sundays and clothes for weekdays and what they called the second-be
s
t so if they went out in the evening or something like that they would put on the second-best, it wouldn't be the working clothes, you know. But always Sunday clothes, and it was not known, I mean it was the worst possible thing for people to have to wear
 
their Sunday clothes in the week, you know. And I remember having a very beautiful pinafore my aunt had given to me and it was fine lawn with embroidery on, but for the week my mother used to make sort of Holland, it was like, its rather a sort of linen, 
s
trong linen, and she'd put feather stitch on. She'd always put feather stitching and smocking, and very often our dresses she'd put on feather stitching and smocking, it made them a little more attractive. But I remember wearing my Sunday pinafore, I was 
a
 little bit naughty and I hoped off to school on the Monday morning in this best pinafore. I was very vain you know, I longed to have pretty things, and I wanted somebody else to see this pinafore. And there were little gangs, you see at school there were
 classes, always classes, classes, the poorer and then this and this, and they didn't play with each other you know. Little sets of girls and boys would play separately. Well I'd got what we used to call }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 French}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  knitting and we were playing with this, my lit
tle set a little more superior, and the others were a little spiteful, and a little jealous I suppose and spiteful, and they weren't allowed in with our little set and they got a little bit rough and tough and took the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 French}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  knitting and tried to run away
 and then there was a little battle about trying to get it back and it was a battlefield, you see, in less than no time. And we all had long hair in those days with hair ribbons. Well the thing was in a very few minutes this beautiful pinafore of mine was
 
torn, my hair was all pulled down, and it just looked a most terrible battle scene. This was during the playtime. And when we were called in, I remember now we were called into school after playtime, and I remember the school mistress was trying not to sm
i
le at these terrible little hooligans you know with torn pinafores and rough heads and bleeding faces, and she tried not, and wanted to know, and of course they took a very stern view, but I know now looking back, I can imagine you know, they thought it w
a
s a funny sight. But we were all in it, the whole school got involved, you see, because they took sides. And anyway our names were all put on the blackboard - list of fighters. And when the rector came down on the Friday morning to take the scripture clas
s he asked what the names were and I remember the school master turning his back, he didn't want us to see him laughing, I suppose, and telling him about these terrible fighters.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what did the rector say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Of course he tried not, he rather lik
ed children, you know, but he pretended to be a bit stern, but looking back I know he couldn't have felt it. But I know what I felt when I got home with this pinafore, because it was a very precious possession and I shouldn't have gone to school wearing i
t. That's one of the naughty things you see, and mother, well I got smacked. And of course then Sunday was a very dull day because the pinafore was rather ruined.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So you didn't have any Sunday clothes then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I didn't have a Sunday pinafore for quite a time. No. That was the punishment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
You mentioned your father making the fire, in the mornings, making his own toast and all that. Can you think back to whether he did any other household work or jobs of any other kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He could, he was a ve
ry good cook. He had a very strict and very wonderful mother, she was my grandmother who I remember and who was rather, she was one of these very strict and rather domineering, she rather bossed the village, and kept everybody in order. We all lived in fe
a
r of her, but she was rather a wonderful person. But very puritanical, very strict, which I think rather showed why my father was rather shy and hadn't got the same sort of bossiness that my mother had. But I think that if it hadn't been that he was rathe
r
 kept under when he was a boy my mother wouldn't have had it all her own way as she seemed to do. But he could cook very well and he there were times you see because mother always had children at home and a nurse would come, you see to deliver, and the nu
rse in those days it was called the Nursing Association where midwives were trained.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Queens Nurses, were those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, oh no. It was a very simple thing. A woman who lived at Hook Norton she started this thing and she gathered the girls together who
 were willing to be trained as midwives and then, it was a very marvellous thing really, for the village because they would go out when a baby was expected, and if they were known they would be fetched. The man would have to go, there were no telephones o
r
 anything in the village at that time. And the man would collect the nurse, she'd come and take over the house. She'd cook, do everything as the mother and wife would do, and look after the children and in the smaller houses of course had to sleep in the 
same room as the children. There wouldn't be a separate room. But they were very well trained in the way of domestic work as well as delivering and looking after the baby. And it was rather wonderful. Before that it used to be, rather like the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14958908\charrsid2904646 Sairy gamp}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  ty
pe, women out of the village who'd just go and deliver. Well I knew in my time it 'twas that some women in the village would have these women who'd go and just look after them, deliver the child and go in for a bit and in those days ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So when did the trained ones start?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well they came as soon as the baby was as near as they possibly know to be expected.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Sorry, I mean about what year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I couldn't tell you exactly that. My mind you see I haven't had to keep these dates and I'm not very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was it after the first World War would you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh before. Oh yes because I remember them coming. You see my sisters, the two that were after me, I remember the nurse sleeping in our room, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see and these were the properly trained ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
The properly trained ones, and my aunt was one of them, you see. She was one of them. And several of them married, you see, married men around. One of them married and went on living in the village up 'til about two or three years ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And how long did they stay with the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well you see it was the thing in those days, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 it\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  so different now as you would know if you've had a baby. A mother was never allowed to put her foot to the ground for ten days. And then in about a fo
rtnight, the nurse would be there up 'til about a fortnight, but if the mother wasn't very well and you know rather a difficult household, she would stay longer. I think that was left to the Nursing Association, they dealt with that. But on the whole it w
a
s a very wonderful arrangement because the mother could have her child and didn't have to bother about getting up and doing the chores and coping with husbands. I mean there were cases occasionally as you can imagine, where the husband or nurse would be a
 little bit flirty with the husband and there would be little sorts of affairs, little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 jealousies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
, that sort of thing, that's bound to happen, as you know, but on the whole it was very good and very satisfactory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And your mother, when she came, did the woman do everything for her then? I mean did your father cook later on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well my father, he would help you see. He usually had to go away, out of the village to work, you see, he wasn't working in the village and sometimes he would be away all the we
ek and only home for the weekends. Sometimes he would have to take a job further a field, always having to walk. No bicycles or means of transport. But he could cook, and I remember at times when my mother was not well, I wouldn't know what it would be, b
u
t possibly she would be expecting a baby. Because they came from 'under the gooseberry bush' in my young days, you see, we didn't know. We'd be sent out I suppose, and I remember arriving home one night and finding a nurse and a baby there, but I didn't k
n
ow, and mother was in bed. I couldn't think why she was 'swinging it', you know, because we'd got a new baby. I knew nothing about it, everything was so secretive. We were never told anything, we were kept so ignorant of all these things. I never saw a si
gn of anything in the way of what would happen, you know, when a baby was born. No, nothing was seen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that true of the older sisters as well. Were they kept right out of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, yes. It was not done, you know. They didn't allow these thi
ngs to be known. I don't know how they managed but we were brought up in complete ignorance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How old were you then when you realized they didn't come from 'under the gooseberry bush', do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I think after I went to school. There were
, as I say, a few girls who, there were two in particular. I don't know if there had been a divorce or if their father had died, but they were London girls and their mother had had to go out, take a job in service, and they'd come to live with an old aunt
 in the village. And they were very knowledgeable and they used to tell, you know, put girls wise about certain things. I think it was one of them who told me about you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I remember, you told me about it last week. Yes, that's interesting. And do y
ou know if your father, when a new baby came, if he did anything like bathing the other children, or putting them to bed or doing anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well he would always, you see, there was no bathrooms in those days and what happened, there was a big bath in
 front of the fire and all bathed together. This would happen, you see, you'd add a little drop of fresh hot water. All the water had to be heated on the stove, you see, and father would, I remember when I was quite small father would help if he was at ho
m
e, with the tiny ones you know, hold one while mother was dealing with the other. But he was very good, he could you know, but in those days women didn't impose on their husbands. I mean, it would appear to be a very poor wife who allowed her husband to d
o
 the work if it wasn't necessary. I think my father only did it when it was very necessary, you know, but he could do it. But a lot, I mean it was a thing a woman was really rather a chattel you know. She was supposed to manage and do these things and the
re was a bit of a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 fuss}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
 with a lot of people if the women were a bit feckless and careless and didn't do. They were looked down by the other women in the village.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So it wasn't at all a regular thing for your father to help with the bath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. W
ell he wasn't always at home and he wasn't awfully strong. He used to be very tired when he came in. And mother would always have his food exactly on time when he came in. She wouldn't keep him waiting. Although he said so little and wouldn't complain, sh
e
 felt it was the thing. He must never be kept waiting. And on Sundays, and at night you see we were sent to bed very early and we must be very quiet, as I told you, we mustn't make a noise, we must go to sleep. Then on Sundays it was really rather a very 
dull day. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 
Of course they would have a meal cooked on Sunday but apart from that work was not done, other work was not done, never allowed sewing or knitting on Sunday, if you had a button off your boot or anything you mustn't sew it on a Sunday. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And then a good deal of church going when we were big enough, you know. We went to Church and my father sang in the choir but he didn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 go to}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  Church in the morning he would go in the evening. And in the village, I think in a lot of the villages, there would be what they call a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 bake house}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
 oven which one of the men in the village, well there'd be two or three of these in the village, and they'd accommodate quite a few of the houses. It was before we went to live at the rectory when we lived in a smaller place they would
 do quite a lot of baking on Sundays, and the man, whichever man was entrusted would heat up, there was a very big oven like a baker's oven, and they would put in a big faggot of wood, it was usually thorn wood which would be cut out of the hedges, and st
a
cked in bundles, you'd put these into the oven and light it, let it burn out then sweep out the ashes and then all the people would come with their Sunday joints and perhaps a cake and a baked pudding and all those sort of things and put them in the oven,
 shut the door, and you'd have a gorgeous meal, it would be beautifully cooked and the right sort of colour all over, you know. And you didn't get burning in the wrong places, you know, it was all evenly cooked and tasting quite delicious.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did it cost anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Twopence. You paid twopence to the man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Whatever you put in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
You could put what you liked, for twopence. I don't know if the price ever went up, I can't remember that happening, but of course I wouldn't in as much as when we went
 to the rectory of course we'd got the big kitchen and the big kitchen range which made life quite a different thing you see it was a different story so then we ceased to be, until we left the rectory, we ceased to be like cottage people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see, but before you went to the rectory you used that sort of oven did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh yes, we had our own oven, two ovens, each side the fireplace, a small one and a big one in which you could cook quite a lot but you could do so very much more with this bigger oven 
and of course it saved us quite a certain amount of coal I suppose which was important, although coal in those days was very much cheaper than now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Very interesting. And I just wanted to ask you about the baths again. How frequently did you have baths all of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
We'd only have a bath once a week, everybody. I think this was the rule. But when we went to the rectory you see there was still no bathroom but we had the hip baths and the round baths you see which had to be filled and the rector he w
ould have his bath in his bedroom, but he always had a cold bath. My husband always had a cold bath you know right up 'till he was quite an old man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I know some people do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes he always had a cold bath. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Well at the beginning when you were used t
o it, it wasn't torture as much as your body became accustomed to it and it wasn't a shock. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
But we would have, when we were at the rectory, of course there was very much more going on, and there was a certain room which we used as a room for the bath and we'd all use that, you know, and all have a bath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that still at once a week intervals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Once a week, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was it always the same day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Saturday. Saturday nights. And then Saturday night all clothes were changed and put away. The dirt
y clothes were put away to be washed on Monday the clean clothes were put out to be worn on Sunday. Everything done was to present extra work on Sunday. The odd thing seemed to me was that although you weren't allowed to do other things on Sunday the men 
w
ould have been very upset if they hadn't had this very hot dinner on Sunday, cooked you know, they would have what they called butchers meat. You see usually in the week, country people they didn't have very much butchers meat, a lot didn't have meat at a
l
l, they couldn't afford it, but if they had a pig it would be bacon or ham in the week and then on Sunday they would have what you call butchers meat, either beef or mutton, they didn't have much lamb. I think to kill lambs would have been considered an e
x
travagance. I don't think they had much lamb. The sheep were allowed to, they had to grow up and become big joints. And I remember, now you see I can't have fat and I think it must have been a thing that, even as young as I was, that I was allergic to fat
 
and I remember once one lunch time we'd had mutton and I was hungry, I was usually hungry in those days. I was asked if I'd like a little more and I said 'yes please' and I was given another helping but there was some fat on it which I left. My father as 
I
 told you was a very gentle man, but he was also very strict and he said "eat up your dinner" and I said "I'm sorry I can't eat it, its fat." "You'll eat your dinner. You asked for more. You'll eat it." "I'm sorry, I can't." "Well you'll have nothing more
 
until you've finished." And I was not allowed anything more. It was brought out, I wasn't allowed any tea, or any supper. Mother by that time, although she wasn't the kinder of the two, she'd relented a little bit and she'd put it in the oven and roasted 
it up until there was very little fat left in it and I managed to roof down a few crumbly bits, but you see afterwards all my life I was allergic to fat.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 As a general rule were they particular about everything being finished on a plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. We 
must finish. And you see food was so scarce in those days. The really good type country woman they didn't buy cake, what they didn't make, if you couldn't afford to make you didn't have 'boughten' cake, what they called 'boughten' cake, and of course 'bou
ghten' cake was the thing one would long for because it was not the common thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Rather frivolous!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Rather frivolous, yes. We weren't allowed frivolous food. It was very good substantial food, you see, Mother would make her own bread usually and make her own cakes and pastries and her soups all those things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did she make them on regular days? Was it always baking on certain days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Baking, of course, when we were at the rectory any day would be baking day. I mean she had to be cooking wel
l every day, I mean did quite a lot of cooking but in the week. Sunday of course one could get in a cake and a tart and a Yorkshire pudding and the joint and baked potatoes we could get all that into the big oven for twopence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 That was before you went to the rectory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. But then of course at the rectory she did cook at any time then, she wasn't so limited. But I mean she did cook in the week at home, she could cook and she did, she had got quite a reasonably good oven, but had more of a splash 
on a Sunday because it was cheaper. Well a lot of people did do that. But the people who didn't and couldn't and weren't such good managers as my mother they were rather despised because their children were very badly fared.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you were at the recto
ry could you tell me, describe sort of, the breakfast in the mornings and did you all have it together all the children
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, we'd have our breakfast in the kitchen. It was a big kitchen with a long table.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Your father would have already gone, wouldn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
My father would have already gone. Yes he would go earlier and I was bigger then so I didn't come down to sit on his knee to share his breakfast then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So when you had your breakfast with your sisters what did you have to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 We
ll, you see, eggs were very cheap and in those days. We had plenty of eggs and, of course, we had bacon. And we would have oatmeal porridge and then usually plenty of jam or golden syrup. The jam would be home made because we had plenty of fruit and sugar
 was very cheap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And would you have bread or something, you know, like butter or margarine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh, I didn't know margarine until later on. I don't think margarine came on in my very early days. When we had a pig killed they would make lard from the 
fat part and a special part of the pig called the leaf, which is a large portion of pure fat, and they would render it down to make lard, which you could use for making cakes and pastry, but it was very nice and we liked it on our bread. And for fat that 
w
as used to put on the bread they would put in rosemary to flavour it and it was delicious with home baked bread. And then another thing which was so helpful and I'm very thankful for it, in our holidays in the summer evenings we played a lot in the fields
,
 you know, and we got such a lot of things to eat out of the fields, and I think that's how we managed to get our vitamins. Because, you see, vitamins weren't talked about in those days. They weren't known. You just had food, you didn't bother about those
 
sorts of silly things. But we had a sort of instinct that we needed fruit and green stuff and that sort of thing, and you see we all had wonderful skin and it was quite noted we all had. I remember when we went away from home they said "what a wonderful s
k
in you've got". Well I put it down, I thought, I earned this, apart from what mother would give, in the fields. We would eat things from the hedges and we would dig things up. Little plants that we knew had little bulbs underneath which were very much the
 size of a hazel nut and tasted rather like one. And with a pen knife, you see, I'd scrape them and I suppose wash them in some water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What were they called, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we called them pig nuts, but that wasn't the proper name. And another 
thing, you see, yew berries. Yew is very poisonous but the little pink sticky berries that grew on yew trees we used to eat them, you know. We didn't die. We didn't know they were poisonous. But we did know that yew tree was poison because it used to be r
a
ther a silly thing - oh, we used to say to each other "You killed the park donkey. No I didn't kill the park donkey. Yes you did." And it was the yew tree, you see, the park donkey had managed to get into the church yard or somewhere and eaten yew and die
d.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But other fresh fruit, I mean, did you have fruit trees and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Always in the country you had fruit trees in your garden and we grew currants, gooseberries, raspberries, sometimes strawberries, plums and apples. But at the rectory it was 
rather, it had been, it was a big house and in the old days they'd had gardeners and it was very well laid out. A large kitchen garden with a big fruit wall going round, and the most exceptional thing in those days, because living in the country you would
n't know about the foreign fruits, but in the rectory garden, you see, we had figs, nectarines, peaches, pears, all those things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did you all have them as well as the rector?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, we had, after we went to live there, we all had them. Of co
urse, he managed to get rid of quite a few of the more exclusive things. I mean we had the less perfect possibly, but it was a great thrill to eat something that one only read about in the old family bible, you know. Figs, I mean, figs in particular and t
h
ey are quite different from the little flat dried things we could buy. And that's another thing, you see, thinking of figs. We always called Palm Sunday, Fig Sunday. We always ate dried figs on Palm Sunday, that was one of the habits, but you see at the r
ectory we could eat the fresh figs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And how often did you have meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well of course, as I say, at the rectory we had meat every day, of some sort. It could be bacon or ham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Before you went to the rectory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we did have, because as I
 say, mother being a good cook she could buy the lesser expensive joints, less expensive joints, and make excellent stews and hot pots and pies and puddings and things like that. If you knew how to deal with these things, which of course the lesser traine
d women wouldn't know, and therefore their children were very badly fed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you always have cooked vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, always. And we would eat, you see we liked raw vegetables. Raw fruit. We would eat raw turnip, raw carrot.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But would that be served as part of the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Mother didn't give it to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You didn't have salads?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
We didn't have that, we could get that out of the garden ourselves, you see. We could eat, we ate quite a lot, I suppose we were rather greedy little pi
gs. We always seemed to be eating, you see, the bottomless pit it seemed to me. In those days you know you never seemed to be filled right up, although we had good meals, you see we would be racing about the fields and playing games. We would get hungry a
nd then we would find things to eat. Like nuts and these things we dug up. Crab apples and then certain leaves, like the hawthorns - the leaves of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 hawthorn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  we would eat those, we used to call that 'bread and cheese'. And then there would be the haws, the berries, you see, of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 hawthorn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
. Then the wild roses, you'd get hips and haws, you see the seeds, we would eat those. Yes all those things which these days you see they make the rose hips, rose hip syrup. Well in those days you see we ate the lot we di
dn't know about rose hip syrup, we would eat those things. We knew, you see, we knew what was good. We weren't told about vitamins.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you also have a pudding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that regular or was it occasional?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Well I think most days we had a pudding, but people in the village wouldn't, I'm sure of that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Some people they had very little. I remember an old man telling me, he came to help in the garden and they were very poor, and he had to go to work in the fields, he left school when he w
as about eleven and had to go to work in the fields and he only had a bit of bread and perhaps a little scraping of lard and go to work and he'd be there all day working for a farmer for about half a crown a week. And he used to eat swedes or turnips or a
nything in the fields and anything he could get from the hedges but he lived to be quite a good age. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 He died at the age of about 78, which I mean, very,very poor food, and working so hard.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What did you have for your evening meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we would ha
ve our main meal midday, but in the evening we would have, oh, perhaps some porridge or perhaps some cake, or anything, milk. We used to get milk from the farm. You see in those days the farmer's wife used to make the butter and so the milk would be skimm
e
d and they would sell that for about 2d per quart, you see, which was quite good, and then the butter would be separate. You could buy the butter which was about a shilling a pound, I think in those days. But we'd always buy, all the village people would 
g
o with their cans and fetch, I was always made use of, I think I was a very willing child running about collecting milk for the older people or the invalids, I'd have several cans of milk, and so we could have plenty of milk, or milk puddings. Sometimes m
o
ther would make an extra big bread pudding which we could eat cold in the evenings. But you see we'd have a sort of biggish tea. In the winter when we came home from school at tea time I used to rather like it because we'd have tea by lamp light and mothe
r would make either some dripping toast or butter toast. You could buy salt butter in those days which was rather good for toast, I think she kept it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 especially}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  for that. The butter was salted, I suppose they did that to preserve it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So when you were saying you had porridge or milk, you meant that really was for the last meal of the day? For the supper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. For the supper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, I see. So you'd have that at about what time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, about half past six or seven and then we had to go to bed, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. So your tea you had directly you came in from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
When we came in from school we had our tea. And as I say, in the winter it would be toast. Sometimes mother would make a scone and cakes sometimes, you know, make cake quite che
aply. And at times, if there was a pig killing the other little delicacies made from the pig. You know we'd have all sorts of things at the time the pig was killed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did your mother use the offal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Everything. Oh everything. She used what they cal
led the chitterlings, you know. They were cleaned. That was a great performance cleaning them, they had a lot of doings with them. To make them clean. Oh they were very delicious. I loved them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you cook the head?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The head was made into brawn
, but they always kept one part of the cheek which was cured and made into a, on a special day in the year which was around September or October and was called a Wake, they had Wakes in the country on a special day, and it was usually a little sort of fai
r
. And it was usually they would have this as a special thing, oh keep this for the Wake. And then I think people would come in for supper, or they'd go to each others houses or something like that. But this particular thing was the side of the head, the c
h
eek, you know, and it was cured, and I think it went down that you'd get quite a nice piece of the neck part because there seemed to be quite a fair amount of flesh on it and they would stuff it with a special stuffing of herbs and chives and that would b
e
 boiled. I was inquiring only the other day. Nobody does that now. You see all these things have gone and of course the hams would be cured and kept and in the country they used to hang the hams and the bacon in the chimney corner in a rack. In the house 
you see there would be wooden racks hanging from the ceiling where they could put the bacon or the hams after they'd been properly cured, you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In the kitchen, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did the cottages have those as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 All the houses had the racks. The bacon racks. It's called the bacon rack.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see. Not hooks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well you'd have the hooks, they were, the racks were hung on hooks from the ceiling, but fairly close to the ceiling because the ceilings weren't very high,
 but then in the chimney corner. There would always be a chimney corner you see, it would be like an open chimney and grate, and there would be the corner and you could hang some pieces of bacon down at the side. And you see, from the fire it would dry an
d there was a special way of curing them with salt and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 saltpetre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
, but for the hams they used different they put, I think, juniper berries and sugar, brown sugar, and salpetre and salt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did your mother salt any other meat? Did she ever salt beef?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Beef. Yes sometimes she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She salted it herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Oh yes. She would do that, she knew how to do everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the pigs cheek, when you said they were for the Wakes, were they preserved in some way then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, they were salted 
down. But you see sometimes a part of it, they would only use one part of it, and the other part they'd make brawn. Boil it, you know, until it was very well done, then cut off all...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You cut the thick skin off, don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Oh yes. You see, 
in those days the country people would; the pig would weigh (unless it was for a family, a rather big family with men and they would let the pig get older and fatter) but to have a pig with not too much fat and rather more delicate meat, they would let a 
p
ig go to about 12 or 14 score. But I know that some men would let the pig run on to about 20 score sometimes, but then it would be very fat. Of course, as you know, I was a little allergic to fat, so I wouldn't enjoy that. But the hams, oh I can't tell yo
u how wonderful the flavour of the really home cured hams were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They must have been. And on Saturdays, you didn't go to school. How did the pattern of the meals vary on Saturdays?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well my father, if he had been away you see, my father would come
 home at midday on Saturday. And then my mother would have, I remember this, that there would always be a very good meal on Saturday, because father would have gone to work at 5 o'clock possibly, in the morning, and then get home around 1 o'clock I suppos
e, or half past one. And he would be tired, and he would be hungry, so there would be exactly waiting for him to come in a good meal. Then it would be perhaps sometimes something with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 butcher
\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  meat, or it could be ham, or it could be bacon. Some days mothe
r would make what we call a bacon and onion pudding, which they liked, you know, and that would be boiled in a cloth. And all sorts of things. Sometimes one would get sausages, but they were something of a luxury if you had to buy them you know. But mothe
r would make them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She made sausages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
She could make sausages and make them with the liver. She could make faggots, if you know what faggots are, and they were delicious, beautifully flavoured.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Where had she learnt her cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well yo
u see her mother died when she was born, her father died when she was six years old, and where as he had been quite well off, she had to be brought up by her grandmother who was rather arthritic I think, which went down the family, from my mother and all 
my sisters and I have it. And then when her granny died she had to go into service, when she was about 13, I believe, or quite early, and she would be trained as a kitchen maid and properly taught in a big place you see by the cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was she in a big household?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She would be in a big household, yes. And she worked herself up until she herself became a first class cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And on the Saturday evenings, did you have the same tea, you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No there'd be a little luxury thing on a Saturday
 evening. It would be, well sometimes, of course, if a pig had been killed it would be one of the little luxury things from the offal, but otherwise sometimes it would be sausages, or mother would take a bit off the Sunday joint and make a little mixed gr
i
ll with some vegetables and little odds and ends, and make a very sort of attractive meal, which we liked. We weren't allowed to eat masses you know, it would be a small helping. We weren't allowed to be greedy and it was so much more discipline in those 
days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I'd like to know if you ever had any tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Very little, mother considered that an extravagant thing, but occasionally she would get a tin of salmon which she would get from the village shop. but that was considered an extravagance and a luxury.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Any other tinned food besides the salmon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Corned Beef, possibly, about once in a blue moon, would one get that but that would be you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But you would have some corned beef occasionally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes but not very often. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 I mean it was very, very seldom. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I mean something had gone wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what about tinned vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Never. We never knew them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Or tinned fruit, or anything else like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, not in our very young days. I never remember having any becau
se we had so much fruit, and we would bottle and jam and that sort of thing and raw, we never needed it. But of course there were dried fruit for cakes, currants, sultanas and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, but not tinned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what about hens or goats, did you keep any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Hens. We kept hens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. In all your homes up 'til 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Each time yes. Not many there was not much room you see. It was just to get the odd egg and then to eat the old girl you know when she'd finished but the
y went on living for so long and it needed an expert cook to get them tender enough to get your teeth into, because some of the hens I remember somebody who kept hens and was able to keep quite a lot because she had room to keep them and some of the old h
ens were years and years old. When they died it would be like eating an old leather strap, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And you mentioned that some men might go and snare a rabbit. Did you ever have any rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. We bought them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Your father didn't get them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh no, my father didn't. There was the difference. You see he was a tradesman and by the time he'd done his work, and sometimes he would be away from home, but when he did get home in the evenings his time was taken up in the garden. He was a g
reat gardener, I used to go and help him. He thought I was wonderful because my brother was lazy he didn't want to work he wanted to be away playing and I would go and my father would make the hole and I would put in the potatoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you remember seeing your mother have less food at any time so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
She ate very little, for what reason I don't know. It may have been, because one didn't ask these questions, one didn't notice in those days but my mother ate very little a
nd she was very busy, you know, would be busy about and waiting on us that sort of thing and she seemed to eat very little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What about your father, do you think she saw to it that he had more than the rest of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes my father always had the be
st of everything. Everything had to be perfect for him. Everything had to be served immediately. Although he didn't say anything you see, but it was so. My father had, we understood this without being told, because after all father had to work very hard a
nd he needs food. Not that we didn't get enough but that my father had more the best you see, perhaps a bigger quantity.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was he served first at the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, except on Sundays. And when we had really the joint and he was there. We were all there
 and he always sharpened the knife and carved the joint on Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And then he would have the last would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He would have the last, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But in the week when your mother served the meal were you all served in a particular order, which didn't vary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well, we had our special places at table and the eldest would be served first
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, and then the next?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Then it went on, round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And can you tell me more about her attitude to table manners. For example, were you allowed to talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You weren't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Could you ask, if say the salt was out of reach, could you ask for it to be passed to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we sort of had a little way of giving a little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 nudge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  to the one next door if it was out of our reach. But I
 don't think, apart from my father who always took quite a lot of salt, and mother liked a lot of pepper, but I don't think we took extra condiments ourselves, not the children. I don't think we needed it, it always seemed to be properly flavoured. It all
 tasted just right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But you had to sit really in silence, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In silence, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not even the most perfunctory sort of talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. But at times we would have a fit of the giggles, something we'd remembered, and then we were rather reprimanded.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did your parents not address remarks to you then that you could answer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They would perhaps ask, you know, but we could only answer. There was no chattering round the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And if they did ask you something, would it be only something to do with the food, I mean what was on hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
About that, yes. I don't think there was anything else discussed. No conversation, like, and you see mother being deaf usually it was just a silent meal. My father he would be getting on with his foo
d because he was hungry and tired, and she was deaf and perhaps she was tired too. And by the time she'd served the lot she would be eating hers so there wouldn't be conversation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And was she particular about how you held your knife and fork and spoon and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. You weren't allowed - you mustn't put your hand right up you know, you must get it there and hold it in the proper way. You weren't allowed to make a noise and when you'd got the food in, it had to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 chewed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  with your lips closed. Not to make noises like a pig, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What about leaving the table and that sort of thing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we were told when we could. You see they wanted to get rid of us, I suppose. But when we got older it always went from the eldest, or 
the two older ones, would have to clear the table and take them away and wash up. The younger ones were sent off, you see. And then father would have a little nap and sometimes mother would have a little nap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Now this would be weekends, would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 This would be weekends, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Of course your father didn't come home for dinner in the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Not in the week as a rule.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did the eldest two wash up and clear away every day? Or just at weekends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Every day. No this was the rule
, we all had to take on, as we grew up, and as the elder girls went away, they went to service you see, the other ones would have to take over certain duties. We had to clean the Sunday shoes, they had to be put away. We never had stainless steel knives, 
t
hey didn't come into fashion in our young days and we had to clean the knives, which were cleaned on a board, with stuff called 'bath brick', it was a brick with rather sandy sort of fine dust which you had to scrape, and the knives had to be rubbed on th
at. And then the cutlery had to be cleaned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you said you had to clean the shoes, was one child responsible for everyone's shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well if there were two around they had to help each other. But sometimes it meant that it would be the older one
 would do it, but I think that more or less the older ones would help each other. They had to clean the shoes, clean the knives, and on Saturday mornings we had to help with the housework. We had to do the dusting and certain things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What was your particular job that you had to do, or did you vary it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I had to do the same as the others when the time came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mean it was a question of the age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It followed up. The age. It followed on, it was the rule, we didn't quibble you see, one went off and the other had to take on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What about, were there two boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 One boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Only one boy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But he was rather lazy and he was rather naughty and he would scrape out of any jobs if he could. He was rather more - he wasn'
t very popular with my father. My father thought he was lazy, he thought he was naughty. And the only time, I mean, I saw my father give him a smacking, you know, he was rather naughty and rather disobedient. I think he rather rebelled against, you know, 
being with girls. But I didn't understand this part. And, of course, he emigrated to America in his teens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, I remember you told me. Was there one of your sisters that you felt closer to than the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 My eldest sister. But you see she went 
away. I missed her, quite a lot of her, because she would be away, you see, in my young days. But we were very close friends right up to the end of her days. She loved me more than any. We were closer, you know. And I was more understanding of people than
 
the others, I think, though I say it who shouldn't possibly. But I understood older people and I understood suffering. I understood and so I was rather popular with both my parents as I got older, with my father always, but my mother too as I got older, b
ut I think she rather resented me as a child because I came at a bad time when they could ill afford another mouth to feed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You told me about the wonderful games you used to have, I remember. Did you play with your sisters and your brother, or with oth
er children or both?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well we didn't play with my brother much. He always seemed to be away somewhere with other children. He didn't care much about us. But it would be more with my other sisters who were there, the younger ones mostly, and the other 
children in the village. And we always had games which didn't cost anything. Our toys - we didn't have toys that had to be bought, but we would make things. We made our own games, our own amusements. The one thing which we had to buy, which they weren't v
e
ry expensive, and went on from one generation to another, was marbles. And there were the seasons for games, you see. It would come, there would be marbles. In the winter we had skipping, that was to make us warm, and playing hunting, you know, chasing ea
c
h other. Then in the summer there would be tip tap, marbles and all those sort of things. But then we'd play in the fields, and we'd have swings, and oh, searching for mushrooms, and picking blackberries and nuts when the season came that they were ripe, 
and as I say, all these things, and getting a meal out of the fields in the evening, you know, in the summer evenings, as well as our holiday times. We'd go off hunting in the fields for all sorts of things.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you told me that your mother was very 
particular about your coming in by about eight, did she allow you though to wander fairly freely in the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh yes. They never had to worry about us in the day. In those days they never worried. You see these days I would go crazy if I had a child a
nd he was missing for a few minutes or if he wasn't in sight, you know, because things happen. But in those days, and I think back on those days, how we would when we were quite sort of young, we would go to Hook Norton which was about three miles away, b
ut they had bigger shops there. They had a Co-op shop and a chemist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How old would you be? For example when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh in my early, I suppose I would be, I should think 9, 10, 11, 12. They thought nothing of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Would they want to know that you were going there though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well, of course, they would send us. We would be sent on errands. We were quite free, I mean, and I think the parents were quite glad to get rid of us children. To get them out of the house, you see, and so w
e would go into the fields or we'd, on Saturdays mostly, in the week we wouldn't have time, only in holiday times, would we go to Hook Norton, but we could go to Hook Norton on a Saturday and do some shopping and I remember at the election time we were aw
fully, tremendously, thrilled at election time and members would come to the village to give meetings. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 We were very thrilled and in those days it was only the Liberals and the Tories. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They didn't have the other party and it was rather a snob thing I think that the ... I don't think many of the villagers understood very much what it was about. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 But like the farmers, or the other class, was able to call themselves 'Tories' and the village people would have to be 'Liberals', you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
They would be and I remember the children at school they'd be sort of having little squabbles about you know their party.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What was your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well my father, well oddly enough, although the rector was a great, I always thought he was a great snob and class conscious, he 
was a liberal, which was a very odd thing and he was a great friend of the member that we had at that time, the Hon. Eustace Heinz, who was afterwards Lord S and S \{BLANK\} from B \{BLANK\} Castle, you know. They were great friends and Mr. S \{BLANK\}
, our rector, used to go and speak for him at meetings but not in our own village. And the meetings used to be very stormy when the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Tories}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  came because there were a rough crowd of young men who'd come from Hook Norton and they'd go to all the, follow around these me
n for the meetings, and give a sort of rough house, and I remember when I was quite young I went to a meeting or a beginning of a meeting, to watch it, and these men arrived and they were sort of hustling the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Tory}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  member and made such a hullabaloo. They go
t at the back of the school room where the meeting was held and you couldn't hear him speak. But that wouldn't happen to the liberal member you see. I mean it was taken for granted, you see. You see, the class again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And your father was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well, 
I think my father, I don't think he talked politics very much but I think my mother always rather made a little show that she was more }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Tory}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 . But I think she always had a few of these ideas, I don't know how it was, she had these ideas and she could never h
ave been taught, because she rather favoured High Church. She had an Irish mother but you see she didn't know her mother and she wasn't brought up in that, but our Church was very Low Church but mother had these ideas. She did go to our Church, but she al
ways had this idea. And then she always had was very puritanical and she wasn't a bit snobbish but she always rather gave the impression that she was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Tory}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what do you think your father would be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He didn't say much about it. But I think he was a liberal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He voted though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. And I think at the time that I remember most, I think I was a biggish school girl, and it was the free trade and protection, and I wanted to know what it was all about and some girl at school said she was rather down on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Tories}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  because they could afford food, you see, good food. Well she said for us poor people, she said, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 it\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  too expensive, and if we have free trade we shall get our currants and sultanas cheaper. That's all I knew about it. And so whe
n the election came and I remember another girl and I. She was a bigger girl, we had to race all the way, we ran all the way to Hook Norton to get the election result, we couldn't get it in any other way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Imagine children doing that now!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. An
d I remember when we got to the top of the village, we shouted as loud as we could. When we got that we were nearing the village, "so and so's got in". I forget who it was now, I think it was Eustace Heins, and we shouted, there was such excitement. But w
e didn't know it was all plain ignorance we didn't know what it was all about. But we did our shouting, you know, took sides.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How interesting. And you don't actually remember your father going to vote. I mean actually casting his vote or talking about it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I don't remember him doing it. He didn't talk much you know. After all he wasn't at home much and the talking he did would be when we were in bed. You see, you've got to realise in the villages, men hadn't time to talk, and therefore I think you
 would find doing the thing that you are doing now, the great thing, the people that I knew, the older people they didn't talk to each other. They would go to work early in the morning, they would take something with them, they would come home latish at n
i
ght. They were tired, they were hungry. They would eat their meal, they would go to bed. There was no time to talk. Did your parents take part in any political activity at all. No, but you see, when we were at the rectory, we entertained the member, the H
o
n. Eustace Heinz, he came and I remember this very well because the night that he came to speak in our village - he was liberal you see - he came to have a meal at the rectory and mother had to look after him because while he was speaking there our rector
 
had gone to another village to speak. He would never speak in his own village. And Eustace Heinz was rather a nervous speaker and he always got a tummy upset when he had to come and deliver his, you know, speech. And I remember mother fussing over him and
 
giving him little things, you know, before he went to the meeting. And then afterwards he'd come back to dinner and she'd give him a little something and she'd have some hot soup and make a fuss of him you see to make him feel, you know, fit again. And li
ke that, you see, we went on knowing all these sort of people and.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 While you were at school did you earn any money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No I didn't earn any money. I was promised, somebody used to make use of me running errands. It was one woman in particular who wa
s always sending me "would you do this and would you do that" and I was always very anxious to help everybody and she was a cockney woman. "Would you go to the shop and fetch me so and so." This was when I was a little girl. "And I'll give }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 yer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  an 'alfpenny
 another day." Well she promised me an 'alfpenny another day - she must have owed me hundreds of pounds, which I never got. Well I was paid 2d a week by some old lady to fetch her milk but I always gave my mother the 2d.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that every day? Once a day you fetched it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Once a week I had the 2d. but I fetched the milk every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
But a lot I did for love, because people were very poor. But I was given this 2d, but until I was quite a big girl I always gave my mother the 2d. I didn
't keep it. And then once I fell and I bought some sweets. Mother never mentioned it and from then on I never gave her the 2d.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Before, when you'd started, had it been her idea or yours that you should give her the 2d?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It was my idea I suppose it never occurred to me that I ought to keep money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And when you bought the sweets did you feel terribly guilty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Terribly guilty. But she never mentioned it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. And when you actually left school, how old were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Thirteen. But then y
ou see we were at the rectory and I went on helping mother at the rectory. And then I was about I suppose, fifteen, I think mother possibly wanted, I don't know if she wanted to get rid of me, or whether she for some reason that I don't know what she sent
 me out into service. And it was in London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, and you were only fifteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Dreadful. I cried every night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It would have been possible, I suppose, for you to have been much nearer home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And this was your first place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. Well no, wait a minute, I'm very sorry, not my first place. I did go for a short time to a vicarage where my other sister had been and she wanted to leave and I took her place for a little time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that living in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Living in, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 That was your first job was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. I went there. I cooked, because I could cook from, mother always let us cook you see. So I knew how to cook even at that age I could always cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what age do you think you were when you took that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I suppose, I was only there a very short time,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 For less than a year?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think so. I can't quite remember that. And then I went to London, Phillimore Gardens to the Lord Justice Kennedy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well how interesting, and how long were you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think about two, or two and half, three years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So you would have been there during the war? The first war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Before the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Before the war, because I was at Swerford when the war broke out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Of course you were, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. I was around eighteen then. Yes and I'd come back to the village because I was very unhappy at this place. There were servants and I didn't like servants. I don't know why, I always feel superior 
you know. I felt superior. I didn't like servants and I was very critical of servants. And one saw very little of the employers, and I was worked very hard and only had very little money. I had very little money, I think about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3676755 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 8 a year. And worked very ha
rd and at the beck and call of servants who I didn't like very much and I think they thought they could do as they liked with nobody to protect me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Who was actually over you? Who supervised you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well the cook. I think I was a 'between' maid. And
 I was at the mercy of - well in the morning I had to get up very early and get the large kitchen range alight and cleaned, and it was very hard work. And get the servants breakfast. Lay it in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 servants\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  hall. And clean steps and clean front brasses, al
l those terrible jobs which I hadn't been used to and then I would be, after breakfast I had to clear away the breakfast and wash up. Then I would have to go upstairs and help the housemaid until eleven o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you said that you had to clear away the breakfast, was that the servants breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Servants breakfast, yeas. Oh yes, because there was a parlour maid and house maid, you see, for the other people. Oh and they had prayers, of course, before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They had family prayers did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Always family prayers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did you go?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, everybody had to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well of course I was always a little bit religious when I was a child you know. Yes, I think it was just there, I mean without being 
taught, and I picked up the bits, you know, of learning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But the idea of family prayers in your employment like that, it didn't worry you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no, not a bit, I rather liked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You liked that? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It was the best anyway while I was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So carry on telling me, because this is most interesting. At eleven o'clock you said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
We came down and the servants would then have a morning snack, which was cake or something, bread and cheese, and tea. And then I'd have to do the 
vegetables and help the cook and lay the servants meal. They would have their meal before the employers. And then I had to do the washing up. And they used copper cooking utensils, which had to be kept very clean and bright, which had to be cleaned with v
i
negar and silver sand and something which was awfully bad on my hands, you see. And it was terrible hard work. And I left there, and I only got away through my own cunning. I went on hunger strike and they didn't know it. And then I got, you know, rather 
ill, and I was sent home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mean you did it on purpose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh yes, I deliberately did it. I deliberately wouldn't eat although I was so hungry, I wouldn't eat, I wanted to get away. You see I could never complain to my mother. You see she wouldn't take any notice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you correspond?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes I would write to my mother, but I could never make a complaint. No it wasn't done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How often did you see her during those two years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well once the family took a house for the summer holiday
s in Wootton in Oxfordshire, and I went down with the family, and so then I was able to cycle home once a week on my day out. But otherwise...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How long was that then, how long a period in Wootton?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 For seven weeks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Only seven weeks, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. But once my father and mother and aunt and a sister came up to London. I don't know how, and the cook was rather nice about it, and I expect she knew I was unhappy, and she got them lodgings with a cousin of hers who lived at Notting Hill Gate and
 they stayed there and they would come and take me out and for the first time I went to see a film. It was a Charlie Chaplin, in 'The Kid'. And it was the first time my father had ever seen a film and my mother and we laughed so much. A silent film of cou
rse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. How long did they stay in London, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think they stayed about a week. But that was wonderful. But of course I was broken hearted when they had to go back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Was that the only visit they made?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The only visit. Of course 
you see my father and mother they never had, they never went for holidays. They didn't go away for holidays. My father had to go away, that was not long after I was born, he was very ill. He had a very bad illness and after he got better I think he was se
nt, I think he belonged to what they called a 'club' or some such thing that they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 paid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
 into, and I think he went to Southsea to recuperate and that was the only holiday he had all his life, up 'til the time he came to London at this time, to me. But my moth
er once went to the seaside with an aunt and some friends and I had to look after the family while she had gone, you know. We didn't have holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But what time off did you have while you were in service in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well you see I was never allowed to go out alone, it was in London, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Whose orders was that were those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well of course, I should have been frightened. I was a very frightened little girl. I should have been frightened and so I had to go out with the house maid or the parlour maid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So where did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well once I remember they took me to the zoo, but oh my feet were so painful and I was so tired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that from all the standing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Standing and I'd had to work very hard all the morning, you see,
 and by the time I'd got finished and went out I was so terribly tired.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What time off did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 None apart from this half day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 One half day a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 That's all. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Goodness!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well that was
 the thing, you know, right up until this war. It was the thing that (this last war) where servants were so scarce, I mean, it was only half day a week that servants were allowed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You never got a whole Sunday off, for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no, never. Never. Never. No. Servants never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What if you wanted to go to Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well one was taken to Church, but that was very early in the morning, to Communion. The staff went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You all went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, most of the staff went. That was very early in t
he morning. We went to the very early service. When I was in London we went to St. Mary Abbots. But we went to the very early service, I think around six or seven o'clock in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were they all church goers, the staff?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 All, yes. You see, 
I think they used to say when they were asked. You took a job, what were you, and it was Church of England or whatever, you know, and you wouldn't be admitted if
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 If somebody had said you were an atheist you wouldn't be admitted would you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You w
ouldn't. But well one wouldn't say that. You were something you know. I think one got away with Church of England. I was intensely interested in Church. And I remember I went once afterwards. Oh this was on holiday time, when the people were away and the 
s
ervants were left on board wages, and we used to go to Church then. Didn't get up so early and then went to the morning service. And I was so tremendously interested in the sermons that I heard then because I could understand them, because, as I said, the
 rector in our village he couldn't...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He was way above?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
He was way above, yes. But I remember this sermon and I wrote it to mother in my letter. And I remember the one thing. I won't take up too much of your time by telling you. The one thing I r
emember to this day, the parson said (we'd always been used to saying the Lord's prayer and knowing it so well and not knowing the meaning entirely) and to hear him say, "To me the Lord's prayer was the hardest thing I ever had to say." And when you think
 of it and separating it up, it is the hardest thing if you say it with sincerity.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. That was what he said that you wrote to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He said that and I carried on and told her all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did she comment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes she liked that. She li
ked that part about me you see. When I was away, I think I got on her nerves, I reminded her of her days when she didn't want me. And it seemed as though, although I think I tried too hard to be loved. I think perhaps I may have fussed around her too much
 to try and get a bit of affection and I think I got on her nerves. But when I was away, you see, I wrote her all those things and I wanted letters from her and I wrote her all these things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And she replied and answered you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And she replied, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you have your older sisters in London in service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Where were they then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well they went more to country places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Nearer home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Nearer home. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But you must have been terribly lonely?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Lonely! I cried every night. And every time I had a letter I had to run to the lavatory and cry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How terrible!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It was terrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 For two whole years you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the other servants can you describe, you know, what the servants consisted of, and who they were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well there was a cook, and I was the between maid, the house maid, the parlour maid. And then a man who used to come in and do some sort of, to do a lot of silver cleaning once a week. You know they had a mass of silver. And do 
clean boots and do up the men's clothes and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No living in men servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. No living in men servants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that rather unusual for a household?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Rather unusual for those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what did the family consist of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well there was Lord Justice Kennedy and his wife, and at that time, he had a family but only living at home was one daughter. And I remember the occasion when she was presented at Court and I was allowed to go and look at her. And she was in her Cou
rt dress with her ostrich feathers and her dress, and I thought of course that it was heaven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you say, you were allowed, was it very ceremonial?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well it was a ceremonial thing. You see the servants were allowed to go and see this grand thing happening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You would have been used to meeting educated and sort of, you know, people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. I was cut off. You see the only time that I ever had any sort of contact. When I arrived, the day I arrived, I was met at the station and taken, you kn
ow, I think one of the staff met me. And brought back. And it was one of those horse-drawn vehicles, it looked rather grand. And then I had to put on my uniform. Cap, apron and what, and be taken to old Lady Kennedy to be presented. And she had a very sor
t
 of cackly sort of voice. The servants used to call her 'the old dutch'. And she asked me all sorts of questions and I stood to attention and then she got up and she was rather like old Queen Victoria, this rather starchy little lady and then she got up a
nd she was going to leave the drawing room, and I quickly went and opened the door to let her go by and she told the cook, "nice mannered, nice mannered, little girl". You see all those sort of things, I remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But did you ever have any sort of personal friendly contact of any kind? With the employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 None at all. None at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They didn't take any interest in you as a human being? You mean, at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. No, nothing. They didn't know anything that went on below stairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well what was their contact then. I mean what was the bridge between themselves and the servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well the cook. The only thing is the cook would go up for orders in the morning for the meals you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. There was no housekeeper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. She was the 
cook/housekeeper, but she would go up and if there was a party it had to be planned, and the menu, well they always had a menu made out you see, written menu made. Every meal was a grand occasion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 With just the three of them sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, well 
it was always a grand occasion. I mean they didn't live in the slap dash way that we know of these days. You see there was a maid to wait at table always. And the table beautifully laid, always with silver cleaned, and the parlour maid would be wearing a 
crimped frock and apron in the morning, but she had to be changed into a black dress and white apron and a different sort of cap for the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 luncheon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  in the afternoon. And then in the afternoon, what was left of it, I had to go up and change into a different thing and I had very little rest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What sort of time would that have been? That you went up to change?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I wouldn't get up there before about half past two or three o'clock by the time I'd finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Because you had to wash up the things.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Wash up, yes, and clean these wretched copper pans. Then I would go up and change. Wash and put on different things. And then I would have to get down in time to get the servants tea in the servants hall and then after tea clear away and then do veget
ables and all the little ugly jobs that the cook didn't want to do. But the only interesting thing was that I preferred to be in the kitchen to the other things. I was never very crazy on the rest of the housework but I was keen on cooking. And I'd got my
 eyes open, I wasn't taught anything but you see I watched how things were done and I knew quite a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She was a good cook, was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She was a very good cook. But you seeing having my own mother I wasn't such a nit that I would have been if I ha
d gone straight from a cottage. And so I knew a lot of things, I mean, all the things which would have been 'dutch' to an ordinary little girl, I knew.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What about your relationships with the servants, how did they treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well this is what I 
didn't like. You see I was rather religious and rather honest, brought up to be rather religious and rather honest. And I found that there was so much back biting. While I was up with the housemaid she would be running down (oh, there was a lady's maid to
o, I'd forgotten that, I couldn't fix her in) and they were always rather at loggerheads.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The house maid and the lady's maid, you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The house maid and the lady's maid, the house maid and the cook, the parlour maid and the cook, and they were 
all you know. And when I was with one they would be running down or talking about the others. And I was not allowed to say anything, I was not allowed to have an opinion. But I had heard all these things one against the other and I rather resented all thi
s
 but could do nothing about it. And then they would try to say, and what did she say, did she say something. And then I would have this terrible feeling of wanting to be loyal and a bit afraid of what the other one would do if I split, you know. It was a 
frightful position for a child. I was a child, you see, because they were all old, well quite old to me. Cook was about 35, the lady's maid was around 50, the parlour maid was in the 30s, the house maid was 28. 'Twas like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Nobody in their teens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. I was a child, and I didn't have any young company at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you get to know anybody else at all? Any friends, make any friends?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No except my aunt had two friends, but of course to me they were quite old people, but I suppose they we
re only in their 30s or 40s, I can't remember. They lived some distance out. They were dressmakers and I can't remember exactly how it happened and how I got there. I can't remember, I suppose I would have gone alone. I would have been afraid and I wouldn
't have been allowed to. But I did see them, and I remember seeing them, but I can't remember much what they were like, but I do remember seeing a lot of cottons on the floor which I would have liked to pick up, you know, where they had been dressmaking.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How often did you go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I only remember going there once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. Was there a garden at the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, but I didn't see, it wasn't not like the big gardens like we had at the rectory. But it was just the ordinary London garden, you
 know, at the back. But I can't remember anything about it. I don't think I ever went into it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So on your half day were there some occasions when you didn't go out? at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 If there was nobody to take me I couldn't go out, and so I would go up t
o my room. Occasionally it couldn't be so then I would go up to my room and I was glad enough to get on to my bed and go to sleep, or read a book. I was a great reader and I was quite glad to get a chance to read a book.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What time did your half days start then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well that wouldn't start until all the work was done, around half past two or three o'clock. Or when the housemaid or whoever could take me, could go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did you have to be back at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Always back, well we had to be in at ten o'clock. Half past nine or ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they take you to their homes or friends any of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No. They hadn't any. None of them were London people. The cook I remember came from Epsom. And I remember this so well, 13 Adelphi Road, Epsom. N
ow fancy me remembering that, but I can't remember my own telephone number sometimes. And the house maid came from Newbury. The lady's maid, I can't remember where she came from, but she had a brother who lived in London - oh she took me there once, yes I
 remember that. You see memories are coming back. And he was a detective.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But was there none of them to whom you felt closeness and affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not very. I suppose I was closer to the cook than any because I was with her more. But she used to have
 violent tempers and she used to get very tired. I don't think she was awfully strong. She was a very bad colour. On looking back I feel she couldn't have been very fit. And of course I would come in, if she got irritated or if one of the other servants h
a
d upset her, I was in for some of her temper which I didn't quite understand and I'm sure I didn't deserve. And they were always rather afraid, you know, it was rather a difficult time in those days the white slave traffic was very much in evidence and I 
t
hink at that time when I heard about it but didn't understand very much what it meant. Because I didn't understand those things. But I remember they were always afraid for me, you know, that I shouldn't go out. I suppose I was quite a fresh looking countr
y
 girl and might have been attractive and there was an occasion when I quite believe I could have been taken. I used to have to clean the front brasses quite a lot, and there were a long flight of steps going up to the house which you would know if you kne
w Phillimore Gardens. A man used to come down every morning, and of course to me he was rather like the Kaiser, he had the sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 moustache}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  that Kaiser Bill had, and I think he was a German too because I could tell you an incident, and he wore a silk hat, 
and a frock coat and striped trousers and his brief case and every morning he would go down at a certain time. I don't know if he went to his business or what not, and one morning, there was the long flight of steps and then there was a little paying goin
g
 along and then there was the gate which was on to the pavement. And I had to clean the knob of the gate. And I was there and this fine gentleman that was supposed to be, I'd seen him, a lot of times and I suppose he'd noticed me, came down and as he got 
t
o the gate, I suppose thinking back on it, he said to me "Would you come out with me one evening" and he spoke, and he reminded me, he looked so much like the Kaiser, so I think he must have been a German. And he spoke what I recognised was not an English
 
accent. "Would you come out with me one evening, I would give you a good time?" And I was flattered beyond words and I hadn't got to the point of saying yes or no when out came a furious cook, she, you see it was a half-basement and she had seen from the 
w
indow at the gate she'd seen this man, she flew out and of course he went off, and she said "What did that man say to you?" And I was all sort of blushing and thrilled. You see how easy. "Oh," she said "Never speak to a man, never speak to a man." I said 
w
ell this is what he said to me. I hadn't had time to do anything else. But I just wonder what would have happened. And of course I've been horrified since, because I grew older and heard about the terrible things that happened and could read the papers. I
 
think what would have been my fate I quite believe this could have happened because he was an oldish man. I suppose he was a man, thinking back on it, and I can see the picture of him now in my mind, I suppose he was a man of around 60 or something like t
hat, but very stately you know and very elegant.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It shows that the cook took some interested in your welfare.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, and then I remember another time. It was a London fog and there was a post box over the road and I don't know if you've ever be
en in a London fog. Well I'd been over the road, they sent me over to post a letter. Perhaps they hadn't realized how bad the fog was and I just went over the road, and as I came back I almost sort of lost my direction, you know, it was so difficult. And 
s
ome man he came down and he saw it could be a girl you see, and as I was going in the gate, he followed me and came down the basement steps. I was going down the basement, you see, and I suppose one of them heard, perhaps the door was left a little open f
o
r me, heard voices and they came out. And this had happened. And I suppose this man had had evil intentions. So it was so necessary to guard me that I felt such a prisoner after being so free, you know, running the fields and knowing everybody and speakin
g to everybody, because we knew everybody for miles around. And all the village people knew nearly all the village people in the next village, you know, that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It must have been terribly hard to get used to. You must have been very depressed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I never did. I never did, get used to it. And you see then, the only way, I couldn't complain to mother and say oh can I come home I'm so unhappy and I didn't want to complain to the servants because they would perhaps have treated me badly, so 
I just, I must have been very crafty, you know, I just went without food as much as I possibly could and was still working very hard, having to work and then I would faint, you see. And I became very anaemic and in those days one wore corsets, you know, I
 
became very anaemic and so they sent me home. They wrote to mother and said I wasn't well and they thought perhaps I should come back to the country. And I remember the rector when he saw me, "Oh," he said "You've got quite a London complexion". Which of 
course I had because I'd become very anaemic and very white. This little country girl, you know, I'd missed my vitamins, you see, out of the fields. Although I must say we had very good food at that place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes the cook she did give very good food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But you weren't overseen at all by the mistress of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No. I never saw them. Only one would see them from the basement, getting into the carriage. They had a carriage. A coachman and a carriage and pair. And I would see the Lord Justice Kennedy. I could see from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 basement}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
 when they went out, you see, when they went out in the mornings. But I had no contact, I could never remember since the first conversation I had with old Lady Kennedy, I don't remember having any conversation at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And there was just the one daughter living there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
One daughter living there but there were sons who would come from time to time. And I'd read of them and seen their names in the newspapers, you know, afterwards of later year. And realized, oh they must have been the sons of Lord Justice Kennedy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How did you get the place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh from the rector I suppose. I mean he had contacts and he would know. It was like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. When you heard you were going there, what did you say to your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I couldn't say anything but I was terrified.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You didn't try to talk them out of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I couldn't. Never allowed to. No, one didn't have, was not allowed to have an opinion as to what
 one should eat, or wear, or do. One was never consulted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But did you confide in anybody about how you didn't want to go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You kept it all to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I kept it all to myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 And while you were there, there was nobody you could unburden yourself to?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Never, never, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How terrible. Not even that elder sister. Did you see her at all during that period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. And when you went to Wootton, it was a holiday for the family, but presumably, not for you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well, I had a little more freedom, in as much as the village boys did, you know, rather chased the other servants. And there was one little boy who rather, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 they teased}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  me about him. But I wasn't allowed to go out with him. But I would see
 him. But in the mornings we would get up very early and go out for a walk, you know, to get the country air. We did that, but we had to do our work the same. So it was very much more tiring because one would have to do a certain amount of work before goi
ng out and then work very hard when we came back, but the walk was so lovely. To be in the country again, and the smell of the country, and the birds, it was all so gorgeous to me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Was that the first time you'd been home since you'd gone away? In your home area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You never went back any other time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No. I didn't. You see when they came up, when my parents came up to London, I didn't then go home for a holiday, I was allowed a bit of extra time off while they were up there, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And that was how long? I think you've told me but I've forgotten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It was around two years, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. I mean that they were in London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I can't quite remember, but it was a week, more possibly, but I can't really remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not much more than a week, would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not a great deal more, I don't think they could have afforded it and my father wouldn't have been away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So that was, say, one year's holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what about the next year? Did you have a break?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I never went home from London until I left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you left where did you go after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I went back to the rectory, you see, and then I continued there helping mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. You didn't go out to a paid job after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Not until after we left the rectory. And I did stay on at the rectory for a short time after the rector got married, to sort of you know, help, because his wife was very young. She was about 26, well, she was 22 years younger than he. She's still alive. S
he lives up the Banbury Road. And I stayed on for a time until she was expecting her first baby, which she had quite quickly and then I went and got another job as cook.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In Great Tew was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. My parents went to live at Great Tew, and I went
 to Kingham. I believe it was Kingham first. I had two jobs. No, I went to Little Tew first. There was Little Tew and Great Tew. No I went to Little Tew first and it was after that I went to Kingham but as cook, you see, because I could cook although I wa
s very young I could cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How long were you in Little Tew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The job there? Oh, two or three years, I should think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. What sort of household was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well they were very mean. The food was very bad and I spent most of my wages on food. The food was so scarce.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was their own food poor, or just the servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well they lived very well but the servants were kept very poor. There were three of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What was the profession of the man of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I think he was re
tired of some sort. I don't know whether he was retired. They weren't very young. There was father and mother and a daughter living at home, and everything was locked up and the ingredients for the food. The lady would come out and make up the menu for th
e
 day and look at the recipes, you see, to see what would be needed. Take them from the cupboard and the cupboard locked. So we could never get. And the servants had, oh very poor food. We didn't have the same. And all for breakfast was cold bacon. We didn
'
t have fried rashers or eggs or that kind of thing. Always cold bacon which, as you know, I didn't like very much, so I used to spend my money at the village shop and I would go home you know, and get a meal on my day out, and bring food back, which I wou
ld smuggle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You did have a day out there, a day off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
A day off, yes. Well not a day. It was a half day. Always a half day. A half day a week as cook, and half a day on Sunday. But the house maid and parlour maid would only get once a fortnight - a half day once a fortnight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Goodness. And the employers there, did you have much contact with them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Now this is rather, I, you know, I've done a lot of despising in my life and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 it\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  sort of from one to the other. I despised servants, but 
I despised employers more. Some that I've known, because, you see, I was in this position of knowing all the local gentry and they all knew each other, they all entertained each other. They would go to each others parties. A great social life, even for ou
r rector who was so poor, he had a great social round, you know, dinner parties and what not. And d'you know the gentry they were such }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 scandal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  mongers among themselves and what I thought was frightfully mean what I'd suffered from servants in this big house
, I suffered from gentry. In the other house. You see my sister was living at Duns Tew, my eldest sister. She was cook housekeeper. There were terrific prejudices coming mostly from jealousy or this class thing that I told you about, where domestic servan
t
s were despised by such people as the farmers and this particular thing which everybody in the village who's alive now would remember, one girl she's an awfully nice girl and she's still alive now, and I'm still calling her a girl although she's over 90, 
a
nd she's crippled and lives alone in the village, she's now a widow. But everybody liked her so much she was so charming and so splendid in every way but she did the unforgivable thing she married a young farmer, and the rest of the farmers of the rest of
 
the family in that farmer's family were so terribly disgusted that he should marry just a domestic servant, you see, that they couldn't show their hatred enough, you know. They did everything to show their hatred, and it split up so many families in as mu
c
h as they would have friends in various parts of the village and this girl would have friends because everybody else loved her and it meant that they always had to be careful about visiting at the same time. And they had to be careful when they were invit
e
d to the same things, and the social things like in the village, if there would be a little concert or something, this girl, you know the others would turn their backs on her. And on her wedding day, which was a thing that I thought so very terrible, was 
t
hey drew down their blinds as she went through the village to her wedding at the Church. And you see in those days, they don't do it so much now, when there was a funeral, when the body was being taken through the village to the Church yard all the people
 
showing respect drew their blinds, well to them this was really a very, a sign of an outcast, I mean she was just condemned. But nobody else, I mean everybody else went on loving her, they do 'til this day, she's such a splendid person, she writes wonderf
ul letters to all the old people and the sick people and she keeps up with everybody. She was very much more loved than anybody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you said the farmers, do you mean all the farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. That particular family. There were several sons, but
 they you see, they did the conventional thing they married farmer's daughters, and she of course being just a domestic servant, she went into domestic service because as I say in the village you had no chance, you had to go to the village school. Well th
e farmer's wives went to the village school too. But you see they happened to marry like this and her parents weren't farmers but they were very respectable people, but she'd had no training and she chose, I mean, after all it\rquote 
s a much better life than, well there were no shops, anyway for her to work in, and no factories.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
But I mean, it was supposed to be by some people a very much more refined thing to go into good service than to go into a factory or a shop, and you wouldn't be trained for office w
ork you see. You would have to have special training, which you couldn't get because you couldn't get, well there was no transport from the village to go to a higher school or for training and therefore you didn't get it. And then you found that you were 
made to feel that if the sons in other families, if they married somebody from a town or somebody, they weren't really accepted by the mothers-in-law, you know, and they were given a very bad time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 This was in the farmers' families was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. In
 everyone's families this was. They were awfully stodgy, you know, you mustn't do anything different from what had always been done and you mustn't speak, I mean you mustn't become refined in any way. I mean some girls would, I mean, they'd become a littl
e more refined and try to speak more grammatically and a little more refined after they'd been away but to come back this was absolute, ooh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you suffer from this yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I tried not to. I was a little clever about this thing. I mean wh
en you're in Rome, ooh yes, I had to. I can always do this you see. When I'm with Americans I'm almost as American as the rest, you know. It's like that I'm a bit of a copy cat. But no, I learned this thing and I think I had a very knowing little brain, I
 
learned quite a lot of the things what to do and what not to do to offend. And I remember two old village women had been picking up wood from out of the woods, you know, for fire lighting, and they'd got a big heavy burden to carry, and I was coming along
.
 This was after I'd been away from home quite a long time, but I happened to be back, and I said could I help to carry, they were so surprised for one thing that I would speak, and another thing they were so surprised to think that I, I don't know why the
y should think that I was so superior, should offer to carry firewood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, I suppose about eighteen, nineteen, or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 "Oh well, you're quite different from the other lot, those are stuck up,
 they wouldn't do this, they wouldn't do that." This was the attitude, and so I was clever enough sort of to, well wanting everybody I suppose to be friendly. It didn't occur to me, you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Now had you been a girl from say, you know, a family of the
ir own type, would they have also been surprised that you stopped, or was it that you were the housekeeper's daughter at the rectory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no, no. 'Twas just that I think that girls after they'd been away from home and came back, a few of them I must s
ay, they did put on airs and graces, you know and dressed differently. And then, of course, the ordinary village people who perhaps had never been out of the village, had got no way of getting out of the village only on their own two feet and they hadn't 
t
he time, couldn't afford to wear their shoes out, also, possibly. But they would be, oh the girls wanted to be a little more superior, when you see you look back, when you're with your family, you don't notice but then when you come back you think well th
e
y're a little rough, a little raw, their manners aren't quite so refined, you know, and try to imitate. And this is what I find, and I would know 'til this day, with the older people, the ones that had been into good domestic service and the ones that had
 perhaps worked in shops, or something like that, the ones that had been in good domestic service was much more superior in their homes and their way of life than the other people. I find that. I know 'til this day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I wanted to ask you to tell me a lit
tle bit more about when you worked at Little Tew. Now you were very interesting in your conversation with her about how she would come and pump you. Do tell me about that again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. In those days, all the villagers around, all the local gentry, all 
knew each other. If a newcomer came to the village they all came, they left cards and then it meant a sign that you'd been called on and you could return the call and then you were one of them. Mind you they would sort you out before they left the card, t
o
 know whether you were in the 'top drawer' and fit to be called on. I mean they were so terribly stiff about this thing that they would find out whether you were, you know, their particular set, and if you weren't you weren't called on. Then they'd call a
n
d then there'd be this round of things, you were invited to a party and then the party you had to return the thing and this goes on and on with the result with our rector, every day of the week nearly he was invited to something or other, and he went on h
is bicycle mostly, to the various places, and he'd get to know all sorts of things. And then you see my sister she was cook/housekeeper in one place, I believe I told you, and there was a little bit of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 scandal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  going on there, they were very rich people. But this woman coming to pump me, you know, to know, I thought that was awfully bad form, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Did she try and get you when the other servants weren't present to talk to you about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh they wouldn't be present, oh no. As I was cook, I
 was cook you see. After I left the other places, you see I always could cook, and I wouldn't go as cook was a more superior person you see and you had a little better time than the others.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What were you called? What did she address you as?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think she called me cook. Oh yes, she called me cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She called you cook, not Miss Woodford, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. I was called Miss Woodford before I was married, when I went to Doctor Webbs, I was called Miss Woodford then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But she didn't call you that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh no. I was very young then and I wouldn't have expected it. No. I expect, I think I was called cook there. And the others, I was called Cook, and the parlour maid was called by her surname, she was Berry."Berry", Berry is the Cook down?" you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And were there other servants at that particular house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes well there was a parlour maid and a cook, and they kept a coach man, they had horses then, a coachman, and gardener. But they were frightfully mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What did you call her? When you had to address her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I tried not to call her anything. She expected me to call her 'Madam' I think, but I avoided it if I could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you dislike calling people 'Madam'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Somehow I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And what about her husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I didn't see much of him I think he was rather just the husband of, I mean she was the..
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. But had you had to address him, I mean, suppose you had to call after him for help or anything, what would you have said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I don't remember ev
er having to have done. I don't know what I would have said. I believe, perhaps I would have attempted, I may have said 'Sir'. But I avoided if I could. That's a fault on my side I think I don't think there's any virtue in my behaviour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It showed an independence of spirit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
An independence of spirit but I don't see why I shouldn't have been willing to, but I never wanted to, I avoided it if I could, because I found what I did to these people, it gave them, they were so terribly important in their 
own eyes and it irritated me, because I knew they were such small beer. And I couldn't bear to think that because they had had the advantage of education and money and what not that they could behave in this way, and be such superior persons, well this ir
r
itated me so I didn't want to make them feel any more important. In my own little way I was trying to put them straight. I don't know if I ever did very much, you know, I didn't succeed very well. But I did more towards the end of life, I managed to do it
 better towards the end, but when you're a child you can't do it as much.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no, and you really weren't much more than a child when you went to that particular place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. A child in the mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they have children of their own in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well yes. It was a second marriage and they had three children. And one, I think she was the daughter of the first marriage and she was always at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 About how old was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 About thirty I should think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, not a child, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
And then there was school girl who was the daughter of the pair of them and she had a school room and a governess. Oh, I'd forgotten the governess.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh did she, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, and the schoolroom was over the kitchen quarters, you see, and she could lo
ok out on to the court yard where the stables and things were round and, you see, the servants were not allowed out only, well being cook I was allowed out half day in the week and every Sunday, but the parlour maid and housemaid were only allowed out a h
a
lf day once a fortnight and on a Sunday and half day during the week but they weren't supposed to go out in between. Well they were courting someone out of the village, and they knew, I think, that of course these people would know, that the courting was 
g
oing on, and this wretched little girl in the school room she used to spy, and she'd got a cat called Tiger and if she thought she heard a sound of a footstep in the yard at night, which meant that the parlour maid was running along to meet her love, she'
d
 come down to call the cat and to find out, you know, where she was. So it was a very nerve racking business. They managed to get married, funnily enough, and he became a very important person in the village and he only died a few months ago at the age of
 88 I believe, and she's still alive.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But when this girl came down to spy was it just for her own usefulness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 To be able to tell her mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, she told her mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She told her mother because that wasn't allowed you see. That just shows how the mean brutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How old was this child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 About twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And was there another younger child? There was an older one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Two older ones but, a man. The girl was at home but the man was away. I didn't see much of him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the governess, what was her social position in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh well, she was as family, you see. But I suppose she was one of these poor, come from a poor genteel family, who had to do something, rather like Jane }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 Eyre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 , you know that type. But she was an oldish woman and she was German. But she was very much, you know, she wasn't really, I shouldn't imagine that she'd have much free speech. She was very much under the thumb of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did she take part in their social occasions? If there was a dinner party would she be present?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No, I don't think so. As far as I remember I don't think so. I think for a dinner party she would be in her room. I don't think she was included.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Ordinary meals, though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Ordinary meals, yes. With family, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did the twelve year old always eat with her parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, except of course, for dinner parties, she wouldn't then, and then I think the governess and she would have their meals upstairs.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What was the job of your employer there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Nothing. He was retired, and I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh what was he? You don't know?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I don't know what he did, he was retired before I knew him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you think they had social ambitions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, I think they were the old type gentry, you know. She was a
 Scot. And I think they were the old type gentry. Well, you know, our rector from the village he was very, you know, very, very, although he was poor, and his family were poor and his sisters, but they were so terribly class conscious and he said this qui
t
e openly that, he was always rather relieved that there were no doctors or solicitors in his family as they were rather low fellows, you know, that type expression. You can't believe it can you? He didn't even consider them. Well now his son is a solicito
r.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 That reminds me, another thing I was going to ask you, in Swerford was there a doctor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No. He had to come from, at one time there was one at Hook Norton which was three, or three and a half miles away. The other was at Bloxham, and the other a
t Chipping Norton. So it was always rather a, I mean you didn't have to be too, well we didn't bother about Doctors much in those days. We managed without.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And you were telling me that there were some women who used to induce abortions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, the
y grew herbs in the gardens, but of course I didn't learn about that until later in life. I only knew that the respectable women in the village didn't have anything to do with them, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, Penny Royal I think you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Penny Royal, that was it yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the instance, just for the record, you were telling me of the farmer's marriage to the domestic servant; what sort of date was that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Now let me see, I would have been at school and I left school at 13.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, well in the period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, well in the period.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I was wondering, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 it\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  an interesting story in any case but I was wondering because of this boundary. Now, on the question of that job with those particular people, where did you eat your meals at that place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In the kitchen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you have a servants hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, not at this place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You had one in London, didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9330829\charrsid2904646 In London there was a servants' hall and I mean that was a little community on its own. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I mean, apart from prayers in the morning, 
I wouldn't see the other people, you see, the employers, you wouldn't see them. I was invited to see the young lady when she was presented at court, you know, I was invited up to see her in her court dress, but one didn't meet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. But at, that was at Little Tew, wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, Little Tew.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was there any room where the servants could sit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. No room, only the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Only the kitchen. And of course at any time you could be interrupted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And we were, because they were spy
ing the whole time. And I'll tell you this, about the food. You see, I was so hungry, being young I was so hungry, and I used to spend such a lot of money at the village shop to get the biscuits or anything to fill up, because they'd lock everything away.
 
She would come out in the morning to do the menu for the day and dole out the things, look up the recipes, you see, to see what was needed, dole them out and lock up the thing. And we were allowed so much tea a week and it was very little, and we were ver
y
 glad to drink tea, you know, for a little stimulation, and it wasn't enough. And of course, I rejoice over this and I don't think I'll miss a place in heaven because of it, I was an accessory. The parlour-maid gor to know where the keys were kept and one
 
afternoon, I remember, when the family had gone out for a walk, she got the keys and she raided the store cupboard and she managed to get some tea and a few extra things. She had to be very careful because it was so noted, you know, everything, every ounc
e
 almost, was counted. But I had no conscience about sharing in the loot, you know, and another thing they were so afraid we should have something that they didn't want us to have, I wasn't allowed to make the cake, although I could make cakes beautifully,
 
I wasn't allowed to make the cakes in case I made a little one which we would have. We weren't allowed cake you see. So my mother, when I went home, I used to go home on my day out, half day out, my mother gave me some materials to make a cake. And so I w
a
tched the opportunity. I thought they were going off for a long walk in the afternoon so I got busy and made my cake and I'd just got it in the oven, it was smelling beautifully, they came back and do you know they could smell it. This woman came straight
 
out. I had a little bit of warning, I think the parlour maid had seen them - "Ooh" she said, "They're coming back!" So I whipped the cake out of the oven and I put it into one of the cupboards - some old boot cupboard or something. "Ooh, do I smell cake?"
 
I don't know how I said, or what I said, but she looked in the oven, there was no cake in the oven. In those days, you see, it wasn't like an electric stove, or gas, it was one of those big kitchen ranges, you see, and so the oven anyway would have been h
o
t. But my poor cake was ruined. We ate it somehow, I think. But they were so mean. That's why I despise, you know. I couldn't help despising people who should have known better. I found people in that position, who, they had all the advantages of educatio
n, upbringing, money, culture, everything, and they behaved worse than little people in my village who had had nothing of that. I could not have behaved, my mother could not have behaved, as those people behaved.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well there is education of the heart as well, isn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes indeed. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you got this job, how did you realise that, I mean, did she sort of say to you, "you will not have cake cook", or did it come up.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, it was like this, you see. When I went, of course, the parlour
 maid and the house maid they were still there, and I was always rather a joker and rather full of wanting to make a joke out of things. And of course this position, but of course in so many places it was the same, you seldom got a place where servants ha
d a free hand. And so I didn't think it was very exceptional for a place like this but of course it was one of the worst places one could imagine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 By a free hand did you...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 'Twas usually the thing that the lady of the house would dole out the rat
ions and such things as tea and sugar. The servants would only have so much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see, was it like that in London, too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I wouldn't be so conscious of it because you see the cook she had the managing, but when the family went away and the serva
nts were left there they had what was called 'board wages'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What exactly was board wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Board wages. The cook was given, well we were given, I don't know in those days don't forget this would be about...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 About 1911 you were there weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Something like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Before war broke out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh yes, before the war. Much before I think. Anyway they would have 'board wages' and the cook she was rather good about that, you see, we lived, we had awfully good food there and so I was 
used to having very good food but the sort of food you wouldn't get in working class families you see. Well I suppose all the other servants had come from working class families. They were rather superior in their way but had come from working class famil
i
es so when the employers went away and they were given 'board wages' what they had, I went with either the housemaid or the parlour maid or somebody, go to the shop where they would sell those things like saveloys and black puddings and little pies, thing
s
 like that, you know, they were quite cheap, but rather the sort of things that working class town people would have, and which I thought were really, because I hadn't been used to them, you see, being in a village and only used to my mother's cooking, an
d
 so I thought that was wonderful and 'til this day I still have a fancy "now I would like to have a meal" one thing was saveloy with pease pudding, and it was wonderful, gorgeous flavour, you know, and so cheap. And the cook was awfully good about this sh
e
 would be as economical as possible and then any money left over at the end of the week she'd make up the account and then hand over the money left over. But I think we were only allowed about, I don't know if it was 7/6 or 10/- a week for our food you se
e
. But I think, I don't like, this is what I feel a little bit guilty in saying, I mean, and it wouldn't do and I wouldn't like the whole of this thing ever to be sort of broadcast to hurt anybody but you see, naturally the cook wouldn't be completely with
o
ut certain things and if she knew the people were going away of course she would have certain things she could fall back on, so we weren't pinned down to spending every penny I suppose. But she did buy these things. Like the saveloys and pease puddings wh
ich I would long to have, you know. Even in the height of luxury I would choose this. It had a.. I enjoyed it so much, possibly it wouldn't taste so good these days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, I think pease pudding is very nice. Were there any of these jobs though where you 
had the same, absolutely the same food as the family. Well not absolutely the same, but I mean in Kingham for example, what sort of food did you have there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In Kingham that was an awfully good job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How long were you at Kingham?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I was at Kingham, oh about three years I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 After Little Tew that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes but that was the fact that, that was because that family going away or something happened in that family. I can't remember at the moment. It would take too long for me to round 
up but that was a wonderful job, no doling out and you could have, you know, just a free hand. Ooh we used to be able to say that we lived like 'fighting cocks', you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Because I had a free hand and I loved cooking. We had wonderful food. That's 
where I could experiment, you see, and I managed to do all the things that I longed to do, you know, where I hadn't the facilities before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mean making certain dishes, do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Making things, yes, and I loved to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Would these dishes be for her and her family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no, we all shared.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Everything was shared?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Everything was shared.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What was the occupation of this family then, the husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well he was, I don't know really, he was retired. They were fairly old peop
le. And the war started, oh yes, just before I went there you see, and they had two sons and a daughter, and this was another thing you see, I'm always critical of these people who should know better. The eldest son he was rather a drip, he was up at the 
university and he was rather a drip, rather a mother's boy you know and she rather spoilt him and she was terrified when the war started because she didn't want him to go into the army. And she made an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 invalid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  of him deliberately.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. How?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She h
ad him home, and she had the doctor, and I really feel this, I might be sort of, I really feel the doctor was in league, I'm sure, because I saw things you see. I saw what happened. I knew how this man could behave, you know, what he could be like, but he
 just drooped about and was pampered to death and went on certain diets and always a great display at certain times. But that was another thing. And then the other son, who was supposed to be diabetic, he was at home, so neither of them went to fight.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Both of the age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Both of the age, but it seemed afterwards, I didn't get to know very much about them afterwards. I saw the daughter afterwards, after she was married and I'd gone to live in Oxford she came with her aunt who was a friend of Mrs. 
Webbs, so I did see her. She was rather a nice girl. But these boys were spoilt terribly. But you see they lived normal lives afterwards, so they weren't invalids.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What about the daughter, what age was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The daughter, she was in her twenties
, rather a beautiful girl. And I could tell you something, rather a thing that, at that time, I was rather horrified about. Because, of course, I didn't know \{BLANK\}
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 On p. 77 the 'thing' that 'rather horrified' Mrs. Eade was that Kitty had been sleep
ing with one of her brothers (having intercourse). The Governess had told her that this was wrong and that she ought not to do it. Kitty had replied 'what a pity. It's so nice.' I think Mrs. Eade had learned of this from one of the fellow servants who had
 heard it from the Governess.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Mrs. Eade left the house because of the violent tempers of the French servant. This girl was in a position to blackmail the family because she had had a child by one of the sons of the house and the employers felt respons
ible for her. Mrs. Eade told me this off the record.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 \{BLANK\} could have got rid of her, she wasn't a child, she was in her thirties.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What was her official position?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Parlour maid and ladies maid, sort of, more or less.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see, I didn't quite realise that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So did you just go without giving notice or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No I went and the lady came to see me and she said she understood, she'd had this thing before and it had been, I mean the house maid had left because of her an
d the chauffeur left because of her, and it was always her violent temper and she knew she had the whip hand because they couldn't sack her, because or else, you see, sort of blackmail. And so I didn't go back because of her. But that was a wonderful job 
I could have stayed there 'til the end of my time as regards my feelings.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Was the woman, I mean the employer, she was nice, was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She was nice, yes. She was nice and her husband. Very nice. And they liked me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were you cook there too? Did they call you Cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. I think so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And they liked you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes, they liked me. Yes, oh they liked me. I was nice to look at and I was a good cook, which they appreciated. You know everybody, that was the great thing, to be able to cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I suppose it made much of their social prestige for entertaining.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Of course it did. Oh it put them oh on to a much higher plain, you know, to have a jolly good cook who could turn out a smart dinner, you know. Ooh, they were the popu
lar people. Good heavens I got my employers very many more friends, I think, by the way they were fed. They were glad to come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they entertain much that family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They didn't entertain a great deal because, you see, I went there the war had jus
t started and there was this situation and the boys couldn't take part. I mean they had to be sort of kept sort of under cover and under diet and what not, so they didn't do much but they had wonderful food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Could you tell me something that you might cook for dinner? Would they have dinner at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Always dinner at night. And they'd have a jolly good, they'd have a cooked breakfast, jolly good lunch, then tea with you know scones, tea cakes and lots of sandwiches, cakes and things, and then dinner a big dinner at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Three courses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
At least three or four courses every night, but for a dinner, you see if anybody came, if they had a dinner party, it was around seven courses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And when you cooked this dinner did any of the servants
 help you with preparing the food? Or did you do all the cooking work yourself? No I did the cooking, I think if they wanted a chatter they'd come and give a hand with something, you know, peeling something or doing something, and a woman used to come in 
from the village to help, you know, help with the washing up. Oh yes, that would be, she would come and help with more of the little jobs that I wouldn't have time to do, If I was doing a proper party.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. She would be got in for party occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. For party occasions and for odd cleaning and that sort of thing. Washing up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And when you said a cooked breakfast, did they have sort of different things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well they'd have porridge and the usual things; kidneys, bacon, sausages, eggs, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 omelettes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 , fruit, that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Would you have eaten first before they had had their meal? Would you have got up earlier and had your own breakfast or did you have it afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think we had it about the same time. No, I think we had
 ours first. I can't quite remember. But they weren't very late getting up. And these wretched boys who were supposed to be ill, you know, they had to have their breakfasts in their rooms. The parlour maid would take that up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How long did that go on, this illness so called, go on for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 'Til the end of the war, then they left the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And there was your off time the same as it had been at Little Tew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. As Cook I was free and I had a sort of you know, well I went out when I liked as long as the work was done I didn't have to bother.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She was quite happy about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh very, very happy, they just didn't bother. Invite your friends in, and I could go out and visit my friends, I just free, you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When you invited friends in, where could you sit and talk with them, in your room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In my room, yes. Yes. In my room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Otherwise where was your place that you ate, in the kitchen? In the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In the kitchen, it was quite a comfortable kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were their family prayers in any of the other houses that you lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They all had family prayers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, that was the thing in those days. I think it was to, you know, they had this superior thing and there was again, I was a little b
it in conflict, it seemed as though with the catechism that you learnt, with the catechism it was a sort of thing to be drummed into you to be humble, you know, how to treat your betters. And it didn't seem as though it was preaching to them. Now you woul
d
 think I'm a rebel you see, but you see now, my duty towards God and my duty towards my neighbour, I learned to say that by heart before I was confirmed you had to learn your catechism which I could say, I found I hadn't said it since I learned it before 
I was confirmed which was at the age of 13 or 14, and one night, not long before Dr. Webb died, we were sitting talking and I said do you know it\rquote 
s a very odd thing but I remember things in my very young days which I can't remember now, I've a bad memory fo
r memorizing things, for quotations and that sort of thing. And I said I wonder if I could say my catechism and he said could you say it off by heart now. I started and I said it right through. My duty towards God is to believe in Him, to fear Him and to 
l
ove Him, with all my heart, with all my mind, with all my soul and with all my strength to worship Him to give Him thanks to put my whole trust in Him, to call upon Him, to honour His holy name and His word and to serve Him truly all the days of my life. 
I
 said that d'you see. Then my duty towards my neighbour is to do to all men as I would they should do unto me. To love, honour and succour my father and mother, to honour and obey the king, and all that are put in authority under him. To submit myself to 
all my governors, teachers, spiritual preachers and masters. To order myself lowly and reverently to all my betters. To hurt nobody by word or deed. To be true and just in all my dealings. To bear no }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 malice nor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  hatred in my heart. To keep my hands from pick
ing and stealing and my tongue from evil speaking, lying, slandering. To keep my body in temperance, soberness and chastity and. No I stopped just at that. It just went. I started to think of something else. But there's only just one more sentence. Well i
t's no good it's gone. I've said most of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I'm very interested because when I was confirmed. So you were saying, about the catechism?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, I thought it all sounded to me as if it was a put up job. I thought it was a little bit spiteful of God t
o have put so much burden on the humble, you see, the poor, where they had to be lowly and reverent to all their betters and submit themselves, and you know, then to be true and just in all their dealings. They must be, you see, but it seemed as though th
e
 others weren't. That's why you see I had one in for them the whole time. We must be but they needn't be and I had this awful little critical mind. A devilish mind and I looked so innocent with it all, you know, because I was rather a quiet looking little
 thing, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Can you describe, can you remember, at any of these houses, what form the family prayers took?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well they would, a chapter of the Bible, in the Bible.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well lets think, for the sake of a particular case, which would you be talking about now, for they weren't all exactly the same, were they?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well mostly. You see they took the Old Testament a good deal in those days, very much more the Old Testament than the New. And I believe I've seen through that little wheeze, you know
, in as much as in the New Testament, if they'd had to say too much, you know, read out the New Testament with anybody with my sort of mind, I would have thought now how are you going to make out with that one, because our Lord was very just and He would 
h
ave been on my side in a lot of these things and I felt, you know, that now I couldn't understand, but you see we got so much of the Old Testament. Both in school I knew all the Old Testament stories almost by heart through hearing them in school. Every m
o
rning there was a scripture lesson, it was a reading mostly from the Old Testament, you see, and prayers. And then on the Friday morning the rector would come down to give us a little talk, sermon, and keep us all up together, you see, to keep us lowly an
d humble and bowing the knee.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But with this Old Testament, would that be the beginning of morning prayers. I mean, say at the house with the small gardens, who was it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The Judge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Lord Justice himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Lord Justice he would read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He would start with that would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He would read a chapter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How would you all sit or would you stand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The chairs were arranged and then we would have to kneel down for the prayers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Which room was it in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In the dining room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In the dining room. Yes. Was this the usual thing in all the houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
In all houses, the dining room. And a little job that I went to first, it was only a little job, my sister wanted to get away and I took her place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I remember, your first job wasn't it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. And there were four in family. The two girls living at home and the two boys at the University and they'd got two dogs and one dog was very old and very smelly and I used to, you know, giggle a lot in those days. When I was young I did
 giggle a lot and also the youngest daughter she was also about my age and she giggled too. And I remember one morning we were saying prayers and the awful dog came into the room, the smelly one and we were sort of kneeling there saying our prayers and th
i
s dog came and put his nasty smelly face through the bar of the chair, you see, and I started to laugh knowing what the suffering would be, you see. Having all this smell and couldn't get away from it. I started to laugh and the other one started to laugh
, this young girl, the other ones were trying not, they were older you see. We were sent out of the room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And after the chapter from the Bible, was it the lesson for the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, the lesson for the day, but they didn't 
do as they do these days. I mean, you would have, you know, the specially arranged lessons which seem to have a bit of the old and a bit of the new, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So you were saying, after the lesson what would be the next thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well prayers and then we'd all say the Lord's Prayer at the end, and then go back and they would have their breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And was this every day of the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not Sunday though, presumably?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Sunday as well, as well as going to Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. Yes. But I couldn't go to Church much at some of the places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was it before or after the Service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What place was it you found it difficult to go to Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I seldom went to Church at Little Tew, there wasn't time and when I went on
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did that worry you because you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well at that period, I think I said to you there was a period where I put it aside and, you know, I felt a little bewildered by it all and I didn't see much sense in it. So no, I wasn't too distressed about it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. But had you been keen to go would it have been difficult for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It would have been impossible. Too much to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It seems very strange there you were having these compulsory family prayers and yet your employers didn't let 
you have the time on a Sunday to go to Church if you wanted to. They didn't consider that. You could have gone on your own time, I mean, suppose the housemaid and parlour maid, they only had one half day once every other Sunday and of course they didn't w
a
nt to go to Church then. They could have gone to Church then if they'd liked but I don't suppose they'd care to. They did their bit of courting or whatever. You see on that time was so precious and the time you got off you didn't want to be in Church. And
 Church in those days wasn't terribly these village Churches they weren't terribly thrilling as you would know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Could you tell me about the seating in the Swerford Church, because these are interesting things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well you see people had their ow
n pews. This very grand dame who looked after the poor mad lady at the park, she sailed into Church and sat up in the front with her own seat you see, which had cushions on. And then the servants came just behind and they sat just behind her. Then the far
mers they sat in the front, you see, and gradually came the riff raff \{BLANK\}
 you see, you sort of sort them out the classes they went back and back, our seat was next to the farmers you see. My mother and father our seat was there. Nobody, I mean it would 
have been a terrific crime if somebody had been cheeky enough to go and sit, 'cos there was nothing you see, you didn't pay for your seat, you had no hold, but it\rquote 
s a very odd thing how they got it their own way. Nobody would dare to have gone to sit in the seat of these people. It was like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were their names there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Their names weren't even up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Their names weren't even up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. In some Churches they are you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But it wasn't in Swerford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But they to
ok it for granted that was their seat there, and there the farmers and there the school master and there Mrs. Woodford and her family and there came, there, there, there, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What about Great Tew was it a similar set up there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Same thing, same thing. The Squire and his family and they went in, you see the Squire }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 it\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  a very big house there and they had a private entrance into the Church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did they alone use it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. But in my, I wasn't at Great Tew, I
 was grown up you see, when my family went to live at Great Tew, so by that time the Squire had died and they weren't living there very much. The house was ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Who did live in the house then at Great Tew when you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well during the war they let it to a school I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 During the First World War?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think so. Well something happened then, I can't remember very much about it. I wasn't there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Could you tell me, I feel I've got a quite a good picture of the social strategy, so
cial classification of Swerford. Were there any differences between Swerford and Great Tew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well the only differences in Great Tew and Swerford, you see the Squire owned the whole of the village at Great Tew, most of the men worked on the Estate in s
ome way and a lot of the women were employed, you see, because it was a very big house, but afterwards although the place still does belong to the Squire very few people do work on the Estate now. It isn't kept up like it used to be in the old days, and t
he old people have the tied cottages you know, very small rent they still go on living.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What sort of house did you have in Great Tew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Very nice. Oh, lovely house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Could you describe it to me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well it was diamond paned windows, you know
, with lead, and 'twas quite old down a path, lovely garden each side and nice porch, it looked an old house, well I think all the houses were very old. And there was the living room and then a sitting room and then very big larder at the back where mothe
r
 could cook as well as prepare her cooking and do everything in there in the way of food, so it didn't interrupt any of the things going on in the living room. And then we had a cellar with out own well of water, spring of water, oh the most wonderful wat
e
r. And mother was able to keep everything cool down there she kept the wines and beer and the things she'd make. And then she'd be able to have a big thing where she could cure the bacon and hams, we killed our own pigs you see, and then there were three 
b
edrooms, an attic and then there was a cottage outside, which had been used as a cottage which was no longer used, which we had and there was a bedroom above that which we used sometimes, because mother took in paying guests and as I told you during the f
irst war she took in children, refugee children from London and so we made this into a bedroom, over this old cottage and it was rather nice. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 
But we used the bottom part of the cottage for the, you know, wash house and the rougher things, we had plenty of room in that place, it was lovely. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Lovely garden.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you, in any of the jobs you were in, did you bake bread as Cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you bake all the bread or did you have it delivered as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we had some delivered in some places I think, but I made the bread mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It's much nicer, much more substantial you know. You can't eat as much home made bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I know, I used to bake it, but I only had a Rayburn. And in the places at Little Tew did they have, did they 
grow their own vegetables and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, and they had a gardener. Oh yes, masses of it, we weren't allowed to go into the garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You weren't, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Not allowed to share anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did all the vegetables come from the house's gardens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, because they were good gardeners, all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What about Kingham, was it the same there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh yes. They had a gardener there and they did, I think he rather used to speculate in property and he'd take a place, a furnished place in al
l lovely parts of the country which was rather a thrill in a way because we all went there you see. We went to St. George's Hill, near Weybridge, wasn't it. And then we went to Walton on Thames. And we lived in three different places in the village. Then 
he'd live in the place, have them done up and sell them. I think he rather speculated in property.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I'm not quite with you here, when you say you were in these places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well you see, I went, the staff went with them. They'd take these places furnished first, and then afterwards...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, I see, this was for the holidays was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, for holidays, well it was like a holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Their holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Their holiday, and then he'd buy them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see, yes. And while you were doing for those h
olidays, I mean, did you have any more time off, or was it simply a change of scene as it were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
It was a change of scene, but we had free time and of course the war was on then, the first war, and of course lots of soldiers and you see we had boy friends and really had quite a jolly time. We could entertain our boyfriends to meals and what not.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And she didn't watch what time you came or went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. They didn't care. They didn't bother. They didn't bother at all, never inquired about anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
One of the questions that is on the schedule, which I can't see now, but I can remember is: Did your employer give the servants any moral instruction because in the old magazines of the time there were often lots of bits of advice about certain things.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh well, they weren't supposed to do this or that, I mean, you weren't supposed to. Well this particular one I don't suppose she would have minded very much about boy friends, but the other you weren't really supposed, you weren't supposed real
ly to know the difference between the sexes!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you ever have an employer who thought she had a duty to enlighten her servants to the good life and all this kind of thing, preaching.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. They all rather would preach, you know. Oh yes, if th
ere was any little occasion. And I remember Mrs. Webb, I'm having to say this now, this was my last thing where I was there 34 years. She, I remember her telling me, and she had a bit of a conscience about it afterwards when she had to come up to against 
m
y way of thinking, you see, and my way of rather sort of inquiring about the rightness of this or that. And she said "Oh well, of course, we were brought up to thinking this or that way, and things were very different in my day and I realise that I have m
a
de mistakes." And she had had, that was sometime before my time, when they were first married, a very wonderful parlour maid but she'd left. And she'd confessed to me afterwards. She said, "I did the wrong thing," she said, "I somehow discovered that her 
m
other had had her before she was married and they hadn't told me this when I engaged her. But they were such a respectable - the mother had married, you see - they were such a very refined family and this girl was so refined, and so good looking, such a s
m
art parlour maid and such a good one in every way." And you see, Mrs. Webb was very stupid when she discovered this in some way, and I don't know how, she said to the girl she should have been told. Now I, of course for me, that was, I think that was drea
dful. And she regretted that afterwards, because of course the mother would have none of that and so the girl left.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see. Quite right too. Do you remember instances of that in your own jobs? Interfering in your background?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, you see, well
 you weren't supposed to have young men and you weren't supposed to be attracted to young men and they weren't supposed to look at you, which of course they'd want to and.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you think there was ever an element of jealousy in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh well, maybe,
 yes. Yes. And, you see, I was supposed to be good looking and I knew how to dress after I got away from home. Mother, of course, made me dress in a very puritanical way, but I dressed in a better way, more attractive way, when I got away from home. But, 
of course, when I went out I dressed as I liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What was your mother's attitude to your having boy friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, very strict about it, and you weren't supposed to be out late at night, you know, and she tried to keep a very strict control.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Even while you were in service she tried to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh yes. Well even up to the time I was married. And after I was married I mean there were certain things she didn't approve, you know, she was, she never sort of got terribly modern in her thinking. She did
 relax a bit, well of course she had to but she went on thinking, you know, that certain behaviour was right and other wrong.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 If you were going out with a young man would she expect to meet him, to know who he was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, she'd want to know if.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did you comply with this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I did when it became I couldn't hide it. I had to, you see, and she'd look him over and approve or disapprove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Would you bring boy friends to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I did when I found, you know, there was no a
lternative, but it was rather a dull time for them, I mean, sort of sitting around with family and not allowed only, it wouldn't be allowed to show any sign of affection in front of other people, we weren't supposed to show any sort of affection in front 
of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you mean by touching, or even looking affectionate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No touching, or kissing, or anything in front of the other people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Were your family themselves, and your mother, were they not the sort of people who embraced or kissed goodbye 
and that sort of thing very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well they did, but they thought young people should not be encouraged to show their feelings. You were supposed to hide your feelings. You mustn't show that you loved somebody, well if it happened to be of the other sex, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And do you remember her actually forbidding you to see anybody or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh yes. Yes. And that's why you see, she wouldn't let me go out. I wasn't supposed to go out at night and this time when she fetched me from the 
dance, when I was a little bit late and I was supposed to be in by eight o'clock, and it was in the summer you see, in the May, and she found out that I was there, this woman had tried to teach me with other girls to dance, and she thrashed me you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Just to get back on to the school. Just a few questions on that. Do you remember at school any children, who were, as it were, outcasts. Who had no friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well there were two or three families who were rather outcasts because they were very dirty
 and very smelly and they would use bad language, which in those days was very, very low. Only I think I told you, if my mother had to, would have had to have said, in any way, devil it would be spelt. She couldn't say the word, you know. But some of thes
e families would be a little bit rough. They weren't very clean, you know, and they brought the little insects to school and we all had to be, sort of, you know, so difficult not to catch them, which one did, then they had to be caught.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were those children to some extent on their own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They had a bad time, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they keep together or did they
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well poor little things, on looking back, I think they had a very miserable time. And I remember one in particular, there was a family the moth
er was not of very high intelligence and she had had a child before she was married and her husband he was rather a drunkard and she had a very bad time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Going back to the pre-war period, when you were at school, of girls or boys being discriminated a
gainst by the teachers where others would be favoured.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. All along the line. All along the line.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well as a matter of fact, not last Saturday, the Saturday before, a friend, one of my school friends, came to see me and, she and h
er husband came to see me. I was bridesmaid at her wedding. And I told her, you know, that I was doing this. I thought she'd be interested. I said I'd talked to you about the old village, and I said, as you would know what a lot there is to tell. And she 
s
aid "Oh good heavens above, I'd like to be there." And then she went on talking about the school teachers. She said "Do you remember old Miss Williams?" I said "I remember her but she wasn't in my day, she was after my day. You must remember you were youn
g
er than me." She's about, she's 69 and I'm nearly 75, so there's that difference. She said "You know that old Miss Williams she hated me," and she said "She always took the opportunity of punishing me" and she was one of her school teachers who was very h
andy with the cane and she would thrash the children. Some of the mothers went up, you know, went to her and complained.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did your mother ever go up to the school about anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 My mother went once. I can't remember what for. I think she went once but I can't remember what.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was it to complain do you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 There was something that had happened but I can't remember so I'd better not waste time over it but.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And your father, do you ever remember him going up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, he never would
've. No, father never did. He was one of these quiet reserved types. If any talking or complaining had to be done in any way mother was the one who did it. Father never. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they take an interest in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well there was not much 
interest to take. I mean, there was so little, just reading, writing. I was awfully bad at arithmetic. And you see, in those days, one was punished me the worse my brain sort of closed up. I just couldn't do certain things in arithmetic and so I remember 
b
eing thrashed. A farmer's daughter who sat next to me, she was good at arithmetic. I was good at everything else, especially spelling. And we were sitting together one afternoon and she said under her breath, "How do you spell so and so?" And I was just t
e
lling her. And the school master with his eagle eye watching, he chose not to have seen possibly her lips moving, but he saw mine. He didn't say anything, he just came across with his cane, slashed me across the shoulders. Now this was, this to me makes m
e even now I feel sick, now I'm so crippled with this wretched arthritis, I think perhaps on some of these things that happened in childhood could be responsible. 'Cos one sort of closed that, you know, all your.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Attention? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And yet to see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What did you do when he did that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, cried.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Just cried?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Just cried miserably.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were girls treated as roughly as boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You wouldn't say they received gentler treatment?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It was worse in a way, becau
se you see, where a girl would be either hit on the hands which was dreadful, or slapped across the shoulders, a boy would be put over the desk and his behind which really was less painful in a way I should imagine than his hands and shoulders.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. C
an you remember whether the teachers felt it their duty to go on about punctuality, manners, all that sort of thing, or didn't they care much about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, you had to be, you had to be perfect, you see. Mmm. You were expected to do everything, 
you see. You were punished if you weren't. No excuses to be made you see. You were not excused if you did not know a thing or if you were felling ill one day and a little bit dopey and not very bright. You were perhaps punished for not paying attention or
 some-thing, your mind wasn't allowed to wander. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 
And I remember in the summer it would be not and the birds would be singing and the bees would be buzzing and in those days you see the haymaking and harvest were done in rather a primitive way and just the l
atter part of my school days they'd got a machine with a horse, a pulling machine to cut the grass and there was a little field, a meadow, just next to the school, just next to the play - ground and you can't imagine how sleep, how soothing it was. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 This th
ing going along, the noise of this thing cutting the grass and it was hot the bees would be humming and the birds singing and I used to get so sleepy, you know, want to go to sleep, and then of course, one would be woken up with a smart smack or something
 and punished in some way. This was to me so terrible to be punished for not knowing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. That must have been awful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Even to this day I'm not awfully bright on arithmetic and I just don't bother. I get a little bit sort of, well I'm not going to
, I take advantage now, you can do that, you can add that up I'm no good, you know, I possibly could if I wanted to, but oh I'm not going to be bothered I've had enough of that, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you tell your parents how much you hated it about the arithmetic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Neither of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. You see this was it, we, one could never go and complain.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Neither to your father or your mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. One didn't do that. Even when I was away I told you, when I went to London I cried I was so hom
esick and I was so lonely taken away from all my you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Associations?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Associations. You see, having the run of the fields and, you see, then to be with all these older people, to me they were old women, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Cruel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And not to think that a child, that that wasn't enough for a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No, that was very hard. Would you say, I mean in the first domestic job you had, the place that your sister had wanted to leave, what did you think about that? Your first taste of domestic service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well that was a very odd place. He was a parson in the village. They were frightfully poor. He and the parson in the next village had both married }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 Germans}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 . German governesses I think they must have been. And they were both alcoholics. This is the oddest thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How very odd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Of course they were well educated women, but the one that I went to she didn't seem to get much social life, she didn't have much social life because they had to hide this thing and they were afraid to leave he
r very much but I thought a thing which was so stupid, how I do criticize these people! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 I thought it was so stupid I would say for an alcoholic 'why have drink in the house'. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well the parson himself, he had whisky or cider and he would have the thing in th
e house, well you see soon as the back was turned anybody you see that she could get the place to herself for a bit. If they would be out, if the family would be out, if her husband would be out and perhaps the children would go off to play tennis or some
t
hing, and she would be very kindly and come and say "Now would you like to go into the garden, or would you like to go somewhere, or would you like to go for a walk?" And then by the time I got back you see she'd be rolling drunk and sick all over the pla
c
e. This happened continually and so she didn't have much social life, but the other old lady, well she wasn't old in those days, she'd three or four daughters and they did they entertained and she was a very domineering woman and they were better off than
 
the other people, they had money I suppose, because they entertained and the daughters were well educated, though they never left home. I don't think they ever did much, but they had a good education and they entertained in spite of this thing. I think sh
e
 did it in a different way. I think they managed it in a different way. She drank a lot but didn't get to this state I think. Because I never, but of course we knew about them, and I remember our rector he was very anxious to get married but of course he 
h
adn't much money and in those days people wanted their daughters to marry somebody who could keep them as they had been kept, you know, with their luxuries and he asked one of these girls to marry him, but her mother was quite indignant, although she like
d him you see as a guest at her dinner table, but as one of her daughters' husbands, no. No, she wouldn't have that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Which of the women was this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 One of the, this was at the next village one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I mean was it the next village one, not where you worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think perhaps this one was not a governess. The one I was with, she had been a governess, she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 German}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  and very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 German}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
, very gutteral with her talk, you know. Very good looking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they have any children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They all had children. They were four lovely, oh, so good looking, such handsome children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The drunken mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The drunken mother. Oh they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How old were they when you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well the men, the two young men, they were in University and the girls were at home but they'd
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What sort of age were they, the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 One was 15 and one was 19.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were they having any education, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Well she would be able to teach them you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She taught them herself, did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
She taught them a lot and I think they had classes somewhere. I think they joined up with another family. I can't remember all the details of it, but they were, you know, quite well educated. In spite of, because of course I t
hink they spent, a good deal of money went on drink, and. But you see my sister left because she would never pay the wages. Like me, but of course I never realized that my sister left hoping that she could get it because they hadn't paid her for sometime.
 They were only paid once a month. Then I went, when I found the difficulty in getting my wages, because you see the poor old lady she preferred to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Use it on something else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. Yes of course, I could understand that. But of course I wanted 
my wages and so did my sister. I don't know if my sister ever got hers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you get yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I think I possibly did, but it's so vague and I've never been, and it was so very little, I don't think it made very much difference to my life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you happen to remember, not that this thing is terribly important, what you did get paid at that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I can't remember quite, but I remember at, in the London job I was paid }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3676755 \'a3}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 8 a year, which I sent home to my mother. I kept 6d. a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes I kept 6d. It was only paid monthly, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes because I remember now that was one of the things I wanted to ask you. What did you do with the 6d? Stamps I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I, stamps for my letters I wished to write home. Mmm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Anything else? Can you remember? If you'd gone out with say the parlour maid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 If I'd gone out with those I would have bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Paid your fares?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Sweets. I think perhaps. I think perhaps as I only had 6d, they'd pay the fare, but I couldn't
, I wouldn't like to say that I would be expected to pay a fare but in those days you see you would get a halfpenny or penny bus fare. It wouldn't be very much so I can't remember exactly that. I mean it wasn't terribly important.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And when you went back to the village, the first place you had there when you went back, can you remember if you got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I stayed at home. No I stayed at home for quite a time and then I went as cook. I think I got
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You stayed on 'til after the rector married didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, then I went to Little Tew and there I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 One point, when you were staying on there with the rector and his new wife you know, while she was getting used to things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I only stayed there a short time you see to get her into.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were you actually paid any wages?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. Oh yes. I had to be paid. It was very little I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Can you remember what it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 These questions aren't very important.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not terribly important. But in those da
ys the wages were so terribly small, I think that at Little Tew, I think I had, I don't know if it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3676755 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 18. or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3676755 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 20. a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Because it was quite a jump up because you were cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, I was cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And then at Kingham what did you have there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think I had, I think I had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3676755 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 30. Mmm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And you told me why you left the Kingham job, why did you leave the, now it was Great Tew first, wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No we went there, it was Little Tew I went into service as cook, but my mo
ther lived at Great Tew afterwards, you see, sometime afterwards. But she was living at the rectory while I was at Little Tew, you see. I could have gone on living at the rectory, but you see she couldn't afford to pay me, and so she got a girl out of the
 village who'd go, sort of you know somebody out of the village to help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Why did you leave the Little Tew job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh I think it was so unpleasant and so hard and so badly fared like, I can't remember exactly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mentioned your father being a good cook? And helping with the cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 other work}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  did he do in the house? Decorating or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. He never did that. But any decorating, when we lived in our own house, mother was quite good and when my married sisters w
ere at home they' help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And did he do anything like repairs or mending?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well, I mean, if it happened to be in the way of woodwork he could do that but mother never let him do anything apart from his work if she could help because he wasn't 
a very strong man, he was very tired when he finished his job so she never imposed on him. But of course he did his garden. I helped him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I remember you saying that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When I was young. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what about cleaning? You don't remember him doing any cleaning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 There wouldn't have been the need for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 There wouldn't have been the need. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And you mentioned he could give a hand to your mother, and did on occasion in bathing you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Because you see all
 the children were bathed on a Saturday night and he would sort of I suppose take charge of the little ones, you know, and pass them on, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what about things like reading to you, or telling you stories, did he ever do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh he was 
too. Yes he'd read and we'd always, we had the family Bible which had pictures in and we were never tired of looking, you know and remembering the stories, that\rquote 
s how we got most of our religious stories, they got going like that, because, and usually on a
 Sunday night, well I suppose it was when mother was perhaps expecting a baby or something like that, we were never told the reason that we didn't go to church but we would be some of the tiny ones, but father would go to church and we would always have t
he family Bible out and we went through it. We were never tired you see and then we'd hear the stories and we knew them off by heart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It was, that was a Sunday night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 That was a Sunday night. But you see there wasn't much time during the week bec
ause you see father didn't get home and we were sent to bed early so he didn't have any time in the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did he take you out without your mother, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. We all went together. We used to go, you see like on Bank Holidays and someti
mes on a Sunday evening in the Summer we'd all go for a walk but we were all in order we weren't allowed to scamper about on Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. No. But it was with your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Always with my mother.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And do you remember her ever going out and his being in charge of you and your younger brother and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well, you see, I was the middle one. I had two older sisters and a brother and if father didn't happen to be there, sometimes he'd be away working and he wouldn't be able to get home excep
t on the weekends, and then my sister would be in charge of the smaller ones and sometimes mother would go, you know, either to see her friends or to help anybody in distress, and we would be quite safe with the sisters. You see, we didn't do, such, we we
r
en't quite so recklessly naughty as the children today. We were rather more afraid of offending our parents. I mean afraid of offending mother because we should have been smacked and father would have been very stern. He didn't smack like mother. But we l
ived more in fear, you know, in those days of, well as I told you, our parents, our teachers, and 'um the policeman, you know threatened by that. We really feared.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You were threatened by the policeman. What sort of things for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh well, it was not so much the girls as the boys. They were threatened, you know, we shall send for the policeman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In your family was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not so much in my family but the people in the village if the boys were naughty, would send for the policeman, whi
ch I don't think they ever did, but it was always a threat that it might happen one day. I mean, it happened like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was the policeman much in evidence?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Seldom saw him, and I think he. I don't think he took much notice of what was going on. It was rather a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 dullish}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
 life for a policeman in those days, there wasn't much happening, and people were too busy to be wicked. The young men in the village when they started growing up a bit and there was this bad element of a gang of youths who came f
rom Hook Norton at odd times and they would be a little bit reckless. And the younger men, I mean, after they left school, they used to get up to mischief a little bit, rather play up the old people in the village. Play tricks on them, because they'd go t
o
 bed early for one thing because they were tired and I suppose to save fuel. They would tie the doors together. And there was this one, the old man I told you about who didn't appreciate the soup so much because there was nar a bit o' meat in it, you know
.
 Well he lived in a cottage and he worked on the farm, and the bedroom windows weren't too high, and the faggots that were stored outside which they used to light the big ovens to cook the Sunday dinners, they were piled up outside and these young men one
 
night they piled all the faggots outside, which came above his bedroom window and he and his wife would be asleep, I suppose, and the old man who depended on the morning daylight to get up, they hadn't got any other way of knowing in those days, and of co
u
rse it was so dark in the morning he didn't get up in time. So that was rather a cruel trick. They were a little bit naughty at one time, the bigger boys, but they grew up most of them, to be rather, rather, the heavy father, the sanctimonious strict fath
er, you know, I knew them growing up with their own children and you know you would really, you couldn't imagine them being anything but very, very strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But incidents like that, presumably the police weren't involved with those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They didn't ge
t to know. No the police wouldn't. We hadn't a policeman in the village at this time I'm talking about. No he would come from the next village and, you see, no other means or getting except on foot or a bicycle and I don't know who.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 From Hook Norton, would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 From Hook Norton. I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what about in Great Tew, was there a policeman there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I don't think there was one actually in the village at that time. I think one policeman had to do for several villages.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And i
n your family, you mentioned the older girls helping, you know, look after the little ones. Did the younger children, there were two girls younger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Below me
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did they help the older ones. Were there any sort of things they had to do for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well I suppose the elder ones would make use of them, but you see they were very tiny because you see by the time when they were about 13, they would leave school at 12 or 13 and then they would go out to service you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Mmm. So they would be away and then I would be the one left and then my brother went to America when he was about seventeen, I think. Mmm.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The younger ones didn't do anything for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No not very much. I think perhaps there was just a chance one woul
d make use of them. But they all were, they had to follow on as they grew up a bit, you know, and take on little duties but, you know, little errands or do the little things that they were able.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But that was more for your mother's scheme of running things than your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I remember. Things like dressing them though, or helping them to eat their food, you know, when children are at the stage when they can't manage a spoon? Did your mother do that, or did the older girls do that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Do you know, I can never remember not being able to feed myself. I can never remember the time when I couldn't read. No I don't know how it came. But I seemed to know so early these things and we were made to be as independent as pos
sible, but I think that somebody had to be, when we were quite small, had to be responsible for the many hooks and eyes and buttons and the backs of our dresses. And we wore quite a number of garments, I mean in these days children wear
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Just nothing really in comparison to what it used to be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Some quite nothing at all, you know, but we had the regulation things and it would have been quite dangerous or indecent if we didn't wear the whole lot of garments underneath. Yes and there were all those hooks and eyes. Hooks and eyes and buttons.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And tapes too in those days, weren't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Tapes, yes, yes indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So when you said somebody was responsible for seeing how it was done up, '
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I suppose if mother wasn't around this woul
d only be in the morning when we were dressing, when the sisters that were there they would have to help. When they were away mother would have to be responsible and I suppose then I took on because I could quite early, I mean, I learned to do things and 
I could quite well when I was quite a child, long before I left school I could cook little things, mother let us do this you know. Mm. We were interested.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Can you remember at what age you put yourself to bed, or do you never remember at all when
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we were sent to bed quite early. We all had to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But when you say you were sent, do you mean you were responsible for getting into your own night attire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. Oh yes. I think when the elder ones were there they would have to help the y
ounger ones undo the back buttons and hooks or whatever, but the we had to go and wash, you see, wash and our hair would be brushed and you know, see if they was clean, because as I told you at school there were families who weren't clean, which then was 
p
assed on, the little the insects were passed on, you know, so we had to be sent - Oh mother did to do that if there wasn't an older one, to make sure that our hair was clear and we always had our hair plaited up for the week and then on Sunday it was you 
k
now, masses of hair, long waves of hair and sometimes curls, you know. In curls, put into rags or papers, and we would have ringlets, imitate, you know. Oh, one of the children, my youngest sister she had curly hair, but the rest of us were quite straight
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And did you say that that was done on, you know, not every night, though, the putting into the curling things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Only on Saturday night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Only on Saturdays, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 We'd have our bath and the hair done up for Sunday, because all 
the week our hair was plaited up so as not to encourage the dirt or insects more than necessary, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. I'd never thought of that use of plaits. And then you'd presumably go to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 We'd go to bed and we were supposed to go straight to sl
eep which I told you on one occasion we failed. My grandmother had gone down, I think people used to, you know, neighbours or my old grandmother and relatives would go down at night after we'd gone to bed and they didn't want us, well they wanted us out o
f
 the road so that they could talk easily and we weren't supposed to be making a noise so to interrupt their flow. So we were sent to bed and we were supposed to go to sleep which didn't please us very much because we weren't tired at that time it was so e
arly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did your mother come up every night to say goodnight or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well she'd come through, oh yes, she'd had to come through one particular place when we were a child. She'd have to come through out bedroom to get to her own, but we'd be as
leep by the time she came, because you see we weren't allowed to talk or romp about. It was a bit boring and we just dropped asleep from boredom I suppose. Mmm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But she didn't come up before you...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 If we did make a
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 To say goodnight, I mean, did she say goodnight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well, she said, we kissed them both goodnight before coming up, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, I see, and then came up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And you mentioned two large beds when you were in that room when you were romping about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were you all in there then? Your brother too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes my brother when he was a little boy, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But did you ever have a bed to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not when we were quite small. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No but when we went to the rectory, of course, we did. We were able to spread out. Mmm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what were your sleeping arrangements there for your own family, at the rectory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we'd got. Mother had quite a biggish room and if there happened to be a smaller child, much smaller child, that would
 be in a smaller bed in her room. And then there were some marvellous attics. Oh much better than my rooms here - marvellous attics and there was, the house was, you know, there was a division between and lead about that wide and we used to, when the weat
her was at all decent, we would throw our mattresses out and sleep on the outside. It was gorgeous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I remember you telling me, yes. But you were all out there, were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 We were all up there yes, except perhaps the tiny one, would be down in mother's room. They were very big rooms you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Yes I know what those old houses are like. And so there did you all have a bed of your own then? When you were in the rectory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes I think we had small, you know, very quite small ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Now at the rectory you mentioned that there was a large kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you all eat in there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. It was very large and it was, oh it was so attractive. With the good smells, you know, and you see, the rooms were so far apart, the dining room, you know, right along the passage, and so we all ate in the kitchen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Always. Were there any occasions when you used the dining room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well no, occasionally we'd join the rector, you know, our family. And on Sundays he would join us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh would he? In the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes, because he'd been used to always come to us for Sunday tea, you see, so he joined us. And he was very musical. My father was very fond of classical music, you know, which he didn't get the chance to hear, and they'd go
t what they called the music room. It was formerly a breakfast room and he'd got a piano there and we'd go in there on Sunday nights as we had always done since I was a baby, and the rector would play the piano and talk, you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 He liked out company, he 
would say, and I was the baby, you see at one point, I sat on his lap before we went to live and he would do this two little dicky birds sat upon a wall, this little game, you know, which I could never understand, it was always a mystery. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And then of course, we were all thrilled to hear the piano being played, this marvellous music, which we wouldn't hear otherwise. No wireless in those days, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did your mother or any of you play at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. Um, we would, you know, play by ear, on the pi
ano, but no we never learned. No it would have been an extra thing, you know, to pay for tuition. I suppose rector would have taught us if we had shown any great }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 keenness}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  for it. But by the time I was growing up, I mean, I was busy, made use of in some way. You know, I was always anxious to please. And I would be running around, and I didn't have much time for this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And you mentioned how wonderful it was at the rectory that there were so many books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. And I could read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did he encourage you in that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And there was a point just when I was growing up, you know, how one gets...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 After you left school, do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 After I left school, well even perhaps a little bit before, when you know you get little ideas of romance, a
nd I started wanting to read perhaps you know little love stories and that sort of thing, and I would, father and mother if they'd gone to bed. And I would stop downstairs, if I could, they wouldn't know, and be reading downstairs. And I remember always t
he rector would come out at night and he would go to the larder to forage for something because he would sit up late and he'd get a biscuit or something before going to bed, and he'd find me there and he'd look to see what I was reading. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 "Oh you shouldn't b
e reading this rubbish" and I got these little sort of love stories from, there were two women in the village, they used to take in these little paper back things just with little romantic love stories and it was so, mother was always rather disgusted bec
a
use they were content, women with children, you know, their literature consisted just of these little truepenny love stories, then their children would get hold of them and then I would get hold of them, you see, but the rector didn't like me reading thos
e things and then he would suggest, you know, other little books that would be a little more profitable for the mind I suppose. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
But he didn't which I rather regretted, afterwards, which I rather wanted, and I don't think I had the courage to ask, that he wo
uld enlarge on some of the religious problems that I had, because I always had problems. When I was a child I used to think too much about life and the teaching and what I knew of the scriptures and I wanted to know things, but he didn't get down to that.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you ask him questions about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Not very much because he seemed to be, he hadn't got quite the mind to come down to a child, in the way of, as I told you at school, the categorical imperative. If you asked some of your university scholars that well you'd find it ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So there was not much contact?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No, not in that way. He liked to talk about things that, he was very interested in all social things, you know, he was rather um, he liked society and he liked to rather talk about the di
nners he'd been to and the food he'd had. He liked his food and I got to know quite a lot of things that possibly I wouldn't have known in the way of food. He'd come up to Oxford for the Maudling Gaudy, or some of the Gaudies and then we'd always wanted t
o
 know what he'd had and he'd bring home the menu and then he'd explain, you know, some of the things he'd had. One thing in particular that I used to like to do afterwards for a savoury. They always had a lot of courses for dinner in those days. And there
'd be the soup, the entr\'e9
e, the soup, the fish, the meat, the 'um all these sort and then a savoury at the end. Well one of the savouries we had at Maudling, was croutons of bread, you know, fried, and chopped, made very pretty, chopped olives green, choppe
d lean ham green, then the chopped yolk of egg and white of egg put through a sieve, you know, and done in little rows, you know, or little rings whatever, it was rather delicious to eat as well as looking very pretty. I always remembered that and I did i
t many times in after life, you know,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mean, it wasn't done straight away after he'd been to the Gaudy, you remembered it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I remembered it. Oh I remembered lots of things. You know, that he told me
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And tried it out yourself did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How interesting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And of course Mother knew, she would know masses of things. How it was done. It was no problem to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the people who used to come in and help your mother with the housework when you were at the rectory, did they
 eat with you or did they go home for their meals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well they went home, well they would go home except sometimes they would stay for a meal, if there was something, you know, particularly attractive, that they might be tempted to like, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Your mother would invite them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But it wasn't part of their wages, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And can you remember when your, say your youngest sister was a child, or the second youngest one, how they ate before they could 
feed themselves? Did they sit at the table, or what did they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
They sat at the table, or high chair, you know, in those days they had the high chair which came up level you see with the table and that would be beside mother. And they would have a spoon or a cup or a little, but I suppose mother did, did you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Feed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Feed them, I suppose, buy I can't remember her. I think that by the time that they sat up to the table they would be able to cope. We always wore a bib, you know, in front, to prevent the, you know, the drops, to keep clean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But before they could feed themselves, do you remember, where or how she fed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It would be with a spoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 At the table or after your meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 At the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It was always altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Little for her. As I say, I never saw her eating a hearty meal. I think she spent a good deal of the time sort of coping.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Looking after all of you, I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You told me quite a lot about your parents' attitudes
, you know, in some ways, but you haven't told me whether they told you much about how they wanted you to behave towards each other, their children. How they wanted you to behave.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we weren't allowed to quarrel. We weren't encouraged to quarrel. 
If we got a little spiteful with each other, you see, we were smacked or punished. We weren't allowed to quarrel. And we had to be very strictly truthful and honest, d'you know. It was a very strict business. And woe betide if we were found out. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 'Cos naturally children do little things and hoping they won\rquote t be. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
But on the whole we were rather afraid. I think it was from fear, possibly, that we would be afraid to do anything. We were encouraged to be very honest. And I think my parents were very honest people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Can you remember what they thought about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Ooh, now that was so interesting, because in these days, to hear on the radio and ordinary people and cultured people using bad language because that was the thing that was absolutely terribl
e. My parents would think. And there was never, I never heard a swear word in our house, and if mother had to quote like, or read or quote devil or hell she would spell it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How interesting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Yes. But this is an extraordinary thing, they were rather sort of strict and rather sort of puritanical.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 When grown ups were talking and you were around, what was thought about you joining in, I mean, would you chip in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 We were not allowed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And I remember when I was a tiny child 
before I went to school, mother had an old friend, who would, she was rather lonely and she would come up in the afternoons this was before we went to the rectory. She'd come and sit and they'd be sewing or knitting and I would be sitting and in those day
s I was very keen on millinery, making hats, and I would sit there never saying a word the whole of the afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What sort of age would that have been?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well it would be before I was five years old because we went to school }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 at}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  five years old, y
ou see, and I would be very busy making hats, and trying on and looking, but never speaking. And they expect would be looking and sort of smiling about me, but I would be listening to their conversation, taking in some of it, storing up some of it, but ap
p
arently not supposed to be listening and they never addressed me at all. I just went on, and they used to be sewing or knitting and you see as the needle struck the thimble it would make a little click, so when I was attempting to sew my hat or whatever I
 
was doing, I couldn't make, I don't think I had a thimble so I used to say 't' to make the little noise that their needles were making. I wanted to be like them, and so it was 't', 't', you see with my, every time I struck the needles because mine didn't 
make a noise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. But you never joined in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Never joined in. No we were never allowed to interrupt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And I suppose a lot of adult conversation wouldn't have taken place when you were around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. No. No grown up. In our day I never hea
rd anything that I could ever remember of a sort of conversation that one would have, I mean, as I would know as a grown up person, that I would have with my friends, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Now I don't think I heard you say anything about birthdays. How, if at all, they were different from other days? Were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we would have, when we could afford it, you see, as I told you we were invited to the birthdays and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 Christmas}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  parties of the farmers' and the school master's daughters and so we would have a
 party for, it would be, not a very expensive one, because mother would be able to make quite an attractive little table, you know, little jellies and things that she could make and so we would have little parties for birthdays. And we'd have little games
,
 but the party didn't last too long. Everybody would leave I suppose about seven or eight o'clock and the parents would come and collect the children, which happened with us when we went to parties. The parties we went to the grown ups and people, somebod
y, would bring us home, because we were children, then you see,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 About eight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
About eight, yes. Sometimes one of the parties I remember at one of the farmers they would keep it on longer because they had some grown up relatives would be there and 
so the party would go on longer and the daughter could play the piano and sing, and we all had to do something. Either sing or recite or do something at the party. I was rather nervous and I would do what I could but I didn't enjoy doing very much, I was 
a little bit nervous and self conscious, but we all had to do our stuff.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And at your parties, besides the farmers and school masters daughters, who else did you invite to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well it was only the children we would have. Then their parents would fetch them, at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, but you had the village children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 We had, yes, some of the village children. Not many, it wouldn't be a very big party. No. Just our immediate friends, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And there wasn't any problem about the school master and the farmers' daughters mixing with the village children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. No. We mixed you know more than them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Because you were at the same school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, the same school. Oh yes, no problem at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But I wondered perhaps if you would have children to your parties that they might not have invited to their house, because you were a ...

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well they didn't invite some of the children we had, one little family we had, which they didn't, they weren't always invited.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But there wasn't much fuss about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. And do you remember your parents playing any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 They didn't play games, but we had Ludo and Snakes and Ladders and little things you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But they didn't join in? They didn't play with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well no. I don't remember them playing. Well they were usually rather occupied I believe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But we'd, some people, before we went to live at the rectory there were some children living quite close and they would come in and p
lay with us, all these little games, all very quiet and you know nothing too rowdy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what about outdoor games? Were there things like that your parents played with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did your mother and father themselves read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. 
My father read more than my mother, because when he was at home he spent, apart from sleeping or resting, he spent his time reading. In later years he had his little crystal set wireless and then eventually the other, which he enjoyed. Mother couldn't bec
a
use she couldn't hear and she rather used to get a bit rather fed up when he was listening at his crystal set and she couldn't hear you see. And there wouldn't be anything happening. But mother used to read, but she never read anything but rather, well on
 
Sundays it was always, you know, rather religious literature and, but if she read any other time she was very keen on Tolstoy and I remember that the rector used to give her for a present, you know, Christmas present, it was usually a Tolstoy or one of th
ose, types
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And do you ever remember her or your father ever reading aloud to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. No. No. You see, mother being deaf that made such a difference, I think its such a tragedy and
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 While you were a child and up to 1918, concentrating on that period, was their a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh yes. You see my grandmother died when I was about eight years old, and she had living with her my grandfather I never knew and my grandmother had her brother and sister living with her. They'd nev
er married. Her sister had been a school teacher and the brother had been a landscape gardener and when he retired and became too old to work, he had been, you know, he had been to America, he had been all over the place with his job, they settled down wi
t
h my grandmother and money was not very plentiful in those days so with the three little sort of things they were able to live reasonably comfortable but no luxuries much. My grandmother was a very sort of stern, managing person you know, the whole villag
e
 under her thumb, we were all terrified of her, but she was really a very good and a very kind woman. But we always if we wanted to play with our friends she didn't approve of too much time wasted in play. We were, if she caught us, we were scooped in to 
them a duster or pull a few weeds out of the garden, or do something like that, never allowed to waste time. And I think that's what made my father, he's rather a shy man, and my aunt was this type of person, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you go to the funeral or didn't children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well I was rather keen on funerals and in the villages in those days, it was only stopped when the war came, and they didn't want bells used. It was only stopped, but you see when a person died in the village, for a man you tolled the be
ll, I think it was 50 times for a man, or 100 for a man, I'm a little bit vague about it at the moment, and then a little less for a woman and little less for a child. And the village, the sexton, it used to be a waste of time for him, he wasn't paid very
 much and I was quite a small girl, I remember tolling the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 bell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
, doing it for him, sitting on a stool and just tolling with a watch, you know, and pulling the bell every minute, you see, just a little tug, and I would sit in the belfry alone in the church. 
I did this for him and I was, on I was very interested in funerals. And if anybody I knew, I would go to the house and ask if I could see the body, I was awfully, you'd think it was morbid, but I liked to take part in everything. The joys and the sorrows.
 I'd go and weep, you see, over the body, as I..
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were you allowed ever to see a body?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes, I saw them all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 People didn't refuse you when you came to the door?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Nobody refused me, no. Oh no, it was the thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And with your grandmother, did you attend the funeral right through, you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I suppose I did, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you remember it actually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And we had to wear, well mother wouldn't be able to afford black clothes for all of us but we'd have a black band on our sleeve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, and she herself, did she change her clothing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She wore black mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mean in any case?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In any case.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see, so after she died your mother didn't wear a different sort of ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No, I think she usually, as far as 
I can remember, I remember seeing mother, apart from when she wore her working clothes, you know, which would be perhaps cottons or prints or something, she would be always wearing black clothes and you see she used to wear a bonnet and mantle not hats li
ke the women of today wear. To me she was an old lady, you know, I mean when I was a child, I thought of mother as a very grown up person.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And your father did he after, it was his mother, wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 His mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 After her death did he change or wear an arm band for several days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well he would wear a black coat and he wore, oh I think for about a year the would keep to their mourning, what they called their mourning wear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He would?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes they would. They didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But then it wouldn't be his working clothes, would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mean when he went out anywhere - his best or second best coat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 His best clothes, yes, they would be the dark clothes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I see. And it would make a difference then with your father's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well, it's the same I think he always had dark clothes, I don't remember him having the light, they were very puritanical in their dress as well as their behaviour. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Now when you say people wore mourning for a year, I mean how would you know this with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I think they put a bit of crepe on somewhere, on their bonnets or hats or something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 On their Sunday clothes was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. But you see clothes lasted so long, one never wore Sunday clothes in the week, there was the...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I remember you telling me the best, second best and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Mmm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 At the rectory did you see a newspaper or any magazines as well as having books?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not much, but the rector would take The Times. And, no
, I never remember, I don't remember reading The Times, and I don't remember, I suppose my father and mother would look at it, and I don't suppose we would have read the paper. I don't remember ever having the chance to read newspapers when we were quite 
young. And they didn't take them themselves. They didn't take any papers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. And magazines? Periodicals, do you remember any of those?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well there was a little thing called 'Home Chat' which was a useful little thing, you had domestic sort of hi
nts, cookery and dressmaking, and that. That was 'Home Chat' and I think the women would pass from one to the other. And then there was rather a religious paper called, oh, now it's gone from me, which they took, and you'd get a sermon and a sort of evang
elical type of paper, and I think various people would share that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Do you remember if your mother herself subscribed to those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think she would've to that one. Yes. I think she would've.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 To 'Home Chat' as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 'Home Chat' I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She actually subscribed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Anyway, I should imagine she would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And then did she pass it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well she would pass it on, yes. I mean things, well you see money was so scarce in those days that even a penny would be an important coin, and to pay a penny for a paper that was a penny's worth of food missing, you know. So they passed them on. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well people still pass magazine on, of course. It's very sensible really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You mentioned going visiting with your parents, you know, both your mother and your father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Who did you visit in the village, could you tell me some of the people you visited with your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well friends, we had friends, sort of contemporaries of my father and mother and they had children abo
ut the same ages and didn't visit very much but just occasionally you know, they would go, but I never remember my father and mother going for a meal, or for them coming to us for a meal. They would have a glass of wine. What would happen if they'd come t
o
 visit when we were in bed, they'd always get home-made wine you see, and they'd come and they'd have a glass of wine and possibly cake or a biscuit if it was going, but we weren't in on that we would be in bed, but I think mother had always got wine to o
ffer to people coming.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes and you said they never had a meal. Not even tea or anything like that? A cup of tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I don't remember that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did visits between friends take place in the day at all, or was it mostly after...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well, 
I think mostly after we were gone to bed, except when we were at the rectory, that's when I was quite a school girl, some old people, mother used to invite them up, it was a treat to them to come and she would give them a very good tea and she'd give them
 
little things to take home, perhaps a bit of bacon or a bit of pudding or something to take home because they were poor and I suppose they didn't get many luxuries. And I remember an old lady and an old man, in particular, they used to make a habit of com
ing well, for many years it seemed to me, when we were at the rectory, and coming in the afternoon and have tea and then go home after tea with their little scrap of something whatever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. That sort of thing, did she pay for that herself, I mean, out of her own idea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh yes, that's her own, you see, oh my mother and the things that she gave in the village it would be her own you know, she didn't give, I mean, the, she didn't give what belonged to the rector, I mean what she gave was hers. It wouldn't be his.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. I wondered how they, you know...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh, she managed, you see, because you see while we were at the rectory my father was still working, and so we were independent you see, in that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, of course. And have you any idea what he paid her while she was there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well it was very little. I think it was something around }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3676755 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 20 a year. Very little, but you see there were certain advantages as I say, with fuel and the wear and tear of the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Exactly. You mentioned you u
sed to go to Hook Norton shopping, do you remember ever actually being taken on a shopping expedition with your mother to buy anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I suppose when we were quite tiny where we could be pushed in the pram we would have to be taken but then aft
erwards, well we weren't too old then, we went to Hook Norton on our own shopping.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You went on your own shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Or with some perhaps bigger friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. You mentioned your father used to go to Church in the evening. When did your mother attend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
She used to go in the evening unless it was, you know, either illness or perhaps a baby was on the way, I suppose that would have been it, but we weren't told. But father always went in the evening and he sand in the choir. He had a nice base voice.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did he? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
They had a very good choir, the rector was very keen on music and he got a very good choir and the one event in the villages they would have festivals, choir festivals, and they would compete and they'd go to some part
icular place on the day of the competition and there was, and they'd win a banner, you see. Yes, for the best choir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Did you ever go and watch the competition?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I wasn't old enough then. I belonged to the choir afterwards but I don't th
ink that, I don't think at that time that I managed, I don't think I was old enough to ever go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But I remember we were full of excitement when the choir arrived back home and they'd won the banner. Great event.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And can you remember whether the Church ran any temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No, the church didn't. But I told you the old lady who lived at the park, the squire's widow, who was mad, she had this very important looking person who looked after her and ran the estate and that sort o
f thing and she was rather an odd sort of mixture, she used to, at the lodge, the gate you see which was the entrance to the park, there was a very big building and the coachman used to live in one part of it and she had two rooms in it which she kept for
 herself and she had it was furnished with a lot of chairs and people who could and \{ILLEGIBLE\} did and a lot of people did choose to do that, whether they belonged to Church or Chapel she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 
would hold}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  prayer meetings, but they sang mostly the Moody and Sanke
y type hymns, you know, although she was a Church person. She came to church you see, she didn't go to Church in the evening but she arrived at Church in the morning with the carriage and pair and her long black train and rustling silk, you know, and the 
s
ervants following meekly behind and, but she would have these prayer meetings on Sunday afternoons and the grown ups would go then, the ones who went. My parents didn't go, I think they were a little more, you know, Church and, but we used to go. She woul
d
 have children's services on Saturdays and temperance classes, and we all signed the pledge. I don't think that we were too strict ourselves about it. I don't think we considered home-made wine as being intoxicating. But you see a lot of people, the men i
n
 the village, a lot of men, well several men would be working there and it was, and it was a terrible thing you see if they'd signed the pledge to be known to go to pub, which a lot of them did, but it mustn't be known by this lady that they went to pub a
n
d they also would get quite drunk with their home-made wine. And so it had to be kept from her otherwise there would've been trouble because she rather bossed them about, you know, and she had the whip hand, because you see it meant they would lose the jo
b
 and all sorts of things like that and she would get up a large supper once a year at Christmas and have a musical evening where people, all the village, did their stuff, you know, singing, reciting and what not. And I remember as I told you I was awfully
,
 rather self conscious and rather shy, and I was asked to sing and so I chose to sing, but I don't think anybody much could have heard me, I had a very small voice and was a very small child and I sang 'Jesu lover of my soul'. Well in the hymn book it's i
n
 two parts, and there are masses of verses and I was so shy and the little man who was playing the harmonium accompanying me. I was so shy that I went on and dived into the second half and they must have been all bored stiff listening to this little squea
k coming from me, you know. And then they had the big supper afterwards, and rabbit pie and all those sort of things, they could catch the rabbits on the Estate you see, and rook pie, shoot the rooks from the trees. It was quite a big thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 At this Christmas party you say all the village was invited?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that really all the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Really all the village, yes. The schoolmaster I remember once, I think they'd had rabbit pie which, you see rabbits really are rather poisonous if th
ey're not cooked, you know, properly. Or if you, you know, they can give you poison, some people are allergic and I remember masses of people were ill after one of the parties, the school master among them. I remember that quite well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And so nobody was considered too kind of working class there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Everybody went to that. Everybody was invited.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Did everyone accept?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Most people. There seemed to be a great many people there, but you see in those days there were such masses of child
ren in the village 'cos people had large families and you see the latter part of my time there they got less and less and the children would grow up and go away and the last part of the time. No school. Not enough children to use the village school.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Really about what time was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Scarcely any children in the village. Well I suppose in my, this would happen in perhaps about my, can't exactly to be accurate, I should imagine around my twenties or possibly a little later.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Yes, what a change. Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. But also we said grace at school before going home to lunch we said grace and then when we came back we had to sing "We thank thee Lord for this our food, but more than all for Jesu's blood, let mann
a to our souls be given and bread of life sent down from Heaven." We had to do that, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And what meals did you have grace in your own home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Only dinner, I think, as far as I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And who said it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think we had to do it, just say it to, you know, just mutter to ourselves. We all said it. We bowed our heads, shut our eyes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Said it all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And said "Thank you God for my good dinner", or something like this, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 We said our prayers. We had to kneel down before going to bed at night and say our prayers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And did you ever have them, sort of family prayers all together out loud, you know, like you described at the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 Phillimore}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  Gardens job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Not exactly that. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Just, you know, praying on your own? That sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Praying on our own, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did your mother have any interests outside her house and family? And the help that she gave to other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well you know in those days there weren't such things as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 Women\rquote s}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  Institutes and Mothers' Union and those things and of course she had a very busy life and there wouldn't be really the time, you see, and she'd get very tired and in the afternoon she used to g
o upstairs and have a rest and I'd be left downstairs, you know, when, after I'd left school and went on there, and the girl who was helping us we'd be together, of course we'd have fun when mother was out of the way and, um, but I don't remember mother e
ver, well in those days there weren't the things, nothing to do. There'd be a school concert once a year, which everybody would go, the children would take part and of course the parents would go to hear the children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. But did she ever go out just to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. And how often did your father go out in the evening or was he always at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Never. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. And you said he used to come in after you'd gone to bed. About what sort of time was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well, when he 
was working near he would come home before we went to bed and then he'd have like a high tea, he would've taken sandwiches with him and then he'd have a cooked meal. And then we would go to bed after that. But we would have a cooked meal at night with him
, you see, we would have had our tea and then we would have a little drink or a scrap of something, possibly just before going to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. How often, I mean, what proportion of the time, would he work so that he'd come home around that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Wel
l you see he'd have to, if he was walking about 3 or 4 miles to his work, he'd start about six o'clock in the morning to get there and then he'd get home at night, I suppose he'd leave work about five or six and get home, he was a very slow walker because
 his feet and legs were rather painful always, and they wouldn't come very quickly. He never had a bicycle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 He never had a bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Never had a bicycle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. And your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Never had a bicycle. They never knew how to ride. They never had one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. And did you have one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not until I was quite grown up, and I bought my own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not before the First World War?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. But I learned to ride on one of my friends in the village she had a bicycle and then her father had one and w
hen it became dilapidated, and it was one with the solid tyres, you know, and the bar, and I learned to ride on that. Go to the top of a hill, get over the handle bar, couldn't reach the pedals of course, but I just learned to steer it and just fly down t
he hill and take a chance how I got off. It was usually got on to the side and fell, but I was quite agile, you know. We would ride anything that would go. Or get on to a horse or a donkey or an old pig if it was big enough in the orchard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you ride horses much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes. Well we didn't actually what you call ride, they were mostly the farm horses. We didn't get the chance much. The school master had one and when I was quite a little girl he used to take his horse into the rectory orchard and I woul
d collect him half way and he would put me on the horse and I'd go up to the orchard with him and then he'd let the horse loose and, but afterwards I learned to ride. I was very keen, the one thing I wanted to do very much was to be able to ride a lot, ri
de a horse. I liked, I loved, horses. I longed to do that more than anything else, but I...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You didn't have the chance or the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not to do very much. I remember in the First War I'd been ill and I went down to the Doone Valley and I rode a hor
se there. You know, you could hire. I could ride, you know. I could stick on anything. I'd got a good balance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Did your father take part in any sport or...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no, he was never fit enough, when I knew him. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did he ever attend races, or bet, or was that out of character?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh. Oh, my dear! That would be a terrible thing! Betting! Oh! To hear, and people didn't bet in those days like they do now, you know, there would be, of course, they'd have a village cricket match. I don'
t, but they never had a football match but they'd have the village cricket match. And it was a very poor little sort of cricket pitch, I mean, it'd be in an ordinary field and the animals would be rolling about it all the week. And then the night before t
h
e match the men would go up and roll it with the roller and, you know, make it a little decent. But I used to like to go up and, you know, play cricket. They'd make use of me to run and get the ball, you know, long field. I could throw in a ball from long
 
field when I was quite young. I could do all those things. I think I was rather keen on all those things, you know, using my body. I tried to. I wasn't awfully strong when I was young, but I was very keen to train my body to get strong. I had this sort of
 
thing inside me that I wanted to be strong and do things. And I remember at King George's coronation, King George V took his coronation, I was just a young teenage girl then, I forget what age that would be, but I was quite young, and they had sports, rac
e
s, and jumping and all sorts of competitions. I won everything you know. I could always run. Oh, I could run. And I remember in later years when I'd go back to the village and the men who'd been young men when I was a child and then they'd be older men so
rt of sitting on the village green, and I remember one man said "My, couldn't you run!" Oh and I loved it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Any other sport at all, I mean, were there any actual organised games or sports that a girl in the village would take part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. We made
 our own. We made jumps, you know, and keep making it higher and higher and I could always jump, you know. And apart from jumping and playing cricket...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you learn to swim?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I could never swim.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did your father or mother belong to any savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Not exactly, but, except my father paid into this club. What they called the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 Oddfellows}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  Club, or something like that. Whereas when, if they died there would be enough money to bury or if there was very bad illness I think perhaps there
'd be a little benefit. It was a benefit club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I know the kind of thing. Yes. But actual clubs for specific articles of clothing? Or Christmas clubs anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Nothing like that. No. What we couldn't pay for we didn't have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And did your mother allow you to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well they were mostly the ones we played with, I mean, they were, I didn't No I don't think she stopped us playing, about our own ages you know, we wouldn't have been encouraged to play with
 big rough boys, you know, but I think our own ages. We were just all the same together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And what was her attitude to your getting dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well we had, we weren't allowed to wear, I mean when in the holiday times we had less good 
clothes and we would wear pinafores, to protect us a bit you see and well if, mostly the things would be washable, we weren't encouraged to get ourselves dirty. I don't think we did very much and even to this day everybody is so amazed that in the old day
s
 perhaps if I was dressed to go out to a dinner or dance or something, you know, in my beautiful clothes I could cook a meal, you know, without getting a spot and I never needed to wear an apron. I never now you know, I could cook a meal do anything witho
ut getting messed up. And I don't think we ever did get very dirty.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 So that wasn't a problem really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Not really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. And you mentioned that you used to do gardening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Helped my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Did you ever go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh we
ll, not fishing, but only, we'd paddle you see to catch crayfish as I told you, under the stones and we would catch minnows and tiddlers and put in a jam jar. But we could paddle, you know. There was a river, a little river running by and there was a wate
rfall, so we had plenty of water, but I remember once, one story, it was some girls older than I, I was only tiny and one was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 cousin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646  but she was quite in her teens, they were both in their teens and you see the elder girls had to take the younger ones out
 and let the mother be free. And these girls had taken this baby down to the river, where they wanted to play and they wanted to get over the other side, and they didn't know, they didn't want to have to go along way where there was a little foot-bridge s
o
 they had the bright idea that one should paddle across, or get across in some way and then the other should throw the baby to her and she'd catch it, which she didn't and it went into the river, then of course was a great to do because they knew they'd b
e thrashed if they took the baby home with all its little flannel garments and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 woollen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
 garments underneath and so one girl fled back home, and got in the back way and found some matches and some paper and some dry wood and came back and they lit a fire, stripped the baby and dried the clothes, they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 wrung}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
 the clothes out and dried them as much as, so they wouldn't be noticed very much, and of course the poor baby I don't know what they was doing while all this was going on, but anyway they made it fairly pres
entable before taking it home, and then I expect they hastily undressed the baby when it got in and put on its night clothes, so they weren't found out but one of these girls she's now an old lady of 82, and she told me this story only a few years ago.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you ever have any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No. I earned my pocket money, which I told you I gave to my mother up to a certain age when I fell and bought sweets, but she never questioned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. And you mentioned that there was nothing more or less in the way of entertainment in the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Scarcely any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you remember anything at all, like a concert or a theatre or anything?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well the village concert, school concert, once a year. And Mr. S he got his friends, I remember at one point, w
hich was when I was quite young, he collected his friends from all the villages around and he knew them they were all the sort of local gentry and they got up the Shakespeare play "A Midsummer's Night's Dream" and they performed on the rectory lawn and it
 
was rather marvellous and I remember seeing that. I didn't take part, I wasn't old enough, but I remember this particular girl who threw the, dropped the baby in the river, she was Bottom, they made use of some of the village bigger children, and she was 
B
ottom, I remember that. And oh it was most romantic because it was quite a romantic garden, you know, a lawn, and a shrubbery going round where the actors and actresses could sort of dress and change and what not. Oh it was most romantic and a lovely summ
e
r's evening. I remember it now. Yes. But then there would be as I think I told you before the village, this particular club they could have a sort of feast day once a year where the grown up people would have a feast and there would be, this happened in a
ll the villages, and they would have swings and roundabouts the sort of show people would bring.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was this when the Wakes, you said...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The Wakes and the Club. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What exactly was the Wakes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well the Wakes, that happened more in the a
utumn time, but the Club, it was a club day, I think it happened sometime in June. And they'd have a band, which would come from one of the other villages, a brass band, and it would enter the village about eleven o'clock in the morning and then they woul
d
 play the band up to the rectory, you see, collect the rector who would walk in front and they would play him down to the Church they would have a church service with the band playing instead of the Church organ, and then in the school room would be prepa
r
ed a big feast for them. Only the grown ups then, and the village women would do the cooking. They would cook vast copperfuls of potatoes, and big puddings and large joints of meat. They would have a real feast. Then in the afternoon the band would be pla
y
ing and we would be playing you know on the swings and the roundabouts and then in the evening there would be a dance. If it were fine it would be on the rectory lawn, if it were wet it would be in the school room. And I remember, it just shows, one of th
e
, in the village, I remember I was quite young then but living at the rectory you see I was there on the spot, and I think they took money at the entrance to get into the garden and there were two little friends of ours whose parents were very strict and 
t
hey were rather Chapel I think, and rather strict and rather narrow, and I remember one of these little girls she was very upset about this dance and being on the rectory lawn, and I remember her saying, "My dad said, you can't serve God and man." I didn'
t know who }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 mammon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
 was, but it sounded awful. And, ooh, very disgusted that the rector should, you know, be so worldly as to allow this to happen and the band would play, you know, and there would be pints of beer and they would have many sups, but in the en
d before the evening was over they'd be all rather drunk, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. The women too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Not the women. The bandsmen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh. The bandsmen, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Mmm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 You said, I don't think you told me about this Club before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I mentioned i
t a little bit. It was the sort of, well the Club that the men paid in for, for death or, you know, any sort of disaster where they might need a little. I think they only paid a very small sum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was it the Oddfellows?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. That was it, that was the Oddfellows, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I'm awfully sorry, when you said the Club, I wasn't sure, I didn't realise you meant that Club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 A type of Masonic thing, I think, according....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 A friendly society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, a friendly society, I think it was called the Masonic, The Oddfellows
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And was it open to the whole village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well anybody who could pay the fee, but of course a lot of the poorer people couldn't afford the 1/-, whichever they had to pay, I think it was 1/- a month or something like that. I 
can't quite remember that I'm not too accurate about it. But I do know it would cover if a man died of course it would be a very big thing for a woman to have to find the funeral money as they had oak coffins in those days, you see, and it had to be paid 
for and the grave to be dug, no crematoriums of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the Wakes, they were in the autumn, you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
They were in the autumn, and I don't really know what it meant, but every village had it, and then the show people used to come to the villa
ge with their stalls of sweetmeats and little horses, you know, merry-go-rounds, swings and those things, it was a little sort of festive things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How long did they stay?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well it would be for a day and a night and then they'd clear off the next day. 'Cos people couldn't afford the time, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. And then you mentioned that about the bit of the pig?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, the bit of the pig! On thinking, it was called the chine. And it was this bit from the bit of the neck, which they stuffed. It was
 cut a sort of round. I was thinking and I think sometimes they did put in a bit of the cheek, but I didn't remember when I talked to you before about it, but it was this ring round the neck and it was quite a piece like that, and then it was rather nice 
meat, rather lean, you know. And they'd stuff it with chives and herbs. There was a very special flavour, I can think of it now, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Did people have little suppers then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. They'd invite each other in to have a bit of the chine, t
hose who could afford to do it. Yes. It was mostly, I suppose, the immediate relatives and friends. Everybody didn't do it, of course, because everybody hadn't got it. But I think I did. But I think we were more or less interested in the little frivolity 
outside, and the grown-ups would perhaps be inside eating their little thing and drinking their home made wine and home made beer. I think that would happen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Who were the relatives you had, besides your grandmother, in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well, a great uncle and aunt, that's my father's uncle and aunt, with a large family. About 12 I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 By the uncle and aunt do you mean a brother and sister or an uncle and his wife?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 An uncle and his wife they would be and they had quite a family and they w
ould be older so they were grown-up and some of them would be married, you see, and their children, and so it meant, and some of them lived in the village, so it meant there were quite a lot, it seemed a lot to me. We'd got cousins, you see, yes, whom we 
r
ealized that we could play with and be kissed by at Christmas under the mistletoe and what not, but one didn't marry cousins, you see. They were people one allowed a little affection but one didn't marry, in those days, you see, you didn't marry relatives
. There was a sort of thing about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you spend much time in each other's houses?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes one just went in it wasn't very, one just walked into houses, you know. That we were familiar with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It wasn't sort of visiting in a formal way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not in a very formal way, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And them, do you remember having them for meals or you going to them for meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well an occasional tea, but you see they were busy people and not much money. One old uncle, this old uncle he was a village carrie
r and he had a short leg and a very morose old man. You never heard him make any remark, you know, scarcely, and a long suffering wife who had lots of work to do and all these children coming along. I think she brought up twelve children. But she had many
. Well they had to have the children that came along in those days. They hadn't any ways of avoiding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No. And you mentioned how your mother had the midwife, when she had the babies but was she ever ill at any other time up to this First World War?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well she had, yes, oh yes, I remember and this must have been, although of course I didn't know as much about it. I think I'd just left school and she had a very bad time at her change of life, and I don't know what happened but we were at the rectory th
en but she was in bed for quite a time. And so, though I was only about 14 or 15, I suppose, 14, something like that, I had to more or less do quite a lot to help and we'd have a woman out of the village to come and help, she wasn't very helpful she was r
ather lazy and took advantage of my mother being upstairs, but I remember I had to know how to do things. You see I used to cook and do all sorts of things I really had a very busy and very tiring time just then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Did any relations help you? Or friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes, but not very much, everybody had enough to do they had their children, their homes and their husbands. They all had plenty to do. I suppose one got a little help occasionally but not very much. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. That's why you hired the woman, I suppose? You were too young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes, oh yes. Well we always had to have somebody to help, even when mother was well. Yes, but you see, when mother was upstairs she took advantage of not having a boss around and I had no control so things got a little bit out of hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 She was the woman your mother had got used to having around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Yes, she was one of them. I mean, at this particular time she was an older woman, who came from the village and she wasn't a very good sort I think. But at times we ha
d younger girls, you see, who I was quite free with. I was able to fool about with a little bit, more fun.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. I remember you said when your mother was having her rest you would have fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes we'd have fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What sort of things would you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh I don't know. All sorts of things. I can't remember, now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Gossiping and giggling, I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Gossiping yes, and giggling, yes. I used to giggle a tremendous lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. It's funny how young girls do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Would you say that the f
riends, you mentioned that there were some contemporaries of your parents that you would visit, would you say that they were equally their friends or were they more your mothers or more your fathers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well usually they were friends of both. And we had
 sort of, all the children were our sort of contemporaries, I mean, like this, we'd each have a friend in that family and so the mothers and fathers were friendly and oh they would see each other, but I think in the evenings, they would perhaps occasional
ly visit each other and they would sort of get together occasionally, but they were very, you know, friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
When they went and visited and, you know, got together with their friends and neighbours, do you know if they got up any sort of entertainments, like music or games together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well there was one place not, of course when we went to our parties, the children, there would be grown ups there and then they would play games, but they didn't get much chance otherwise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 What about music, did they ever...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Music, yes of course when we were at the rectory the rector was very musical, he played the piano. But you know there were a lot of people in the village who were naturally musical. I know there were two or three families who they could h
ave a little sort of band on their own. One family in particular, they were quite poor, they were, but in some way they got musical instruments. There were several of them and they could all play. One played the fiddle, one would play the harmonium, one p
l
ayed a little bit of a trumpet thing and one played the violin, and always on Sundays it was such a joy, before Church they would have a sing song with hymns and all these would be playing, all the family could play something. And several people in the vi
l
lage, you know, were like that. They had you see, needs must you see, and they couldn't go away from the village much for their entertainment and so it pressed them to make their own entertainment and to get to know things. A lot of them, you know, they c
o
uld play the piano, the organ, and they'd practice, practice enough 'til they were useful. I remember one young man, he was a little older than I was and he'd only had, they'd got a little harmonium at home and he would practice and practice, it was mostl
y hymns, and eventually he played the organ at the Church. They were very musical the young, the people in the village. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 
The parson was very musical and I think that encouraged and they would have, they belonged to the choir, all the people who could, and he
 would give the choir practice, he'd have them into the music room, where the piano was and he was very good for training. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
And then at one point, he'd get up, oh they would have competitions, you know, the choirs would compete, and go to different villages and then they'd get a banner for the best choir. And he would train our choir. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9973795\charrsid2904646 And, oh you see, in the villages, right away from everywhere you were put to use your own talent, which they did. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
And they'd very good voices, beautiful singing voices, and we had a lovely choir, though it was a small village. 'Cos everybody would belong, those who could. My first effort, I sang alto, I was quite a young girl, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Must have been very nice I should think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But we loved it. It was an event you know to get to choir practice. We didn't have to go...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Little change.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. Anything for a change.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
During the First World War, you say you went up to London because you wanted to do war work, and I wanted to learn about, how to do, not only
 to drive a car, but first I thought I'd do the job properly and I went into this engineering firm. It was Simms Motor Units, I think it was an American firm, and, I can't remember where it was now, I can't. Anyway I went into lodgings with someone my mot
h
er knew and I used to go to work at this firm, the parts would all come over from America, I suppose, all in their separate parts, in their greasy state, you know, the little springs, and what not, for the magneto. It was Simms Magneto Unit, you know, the
 
magnetos. I'd have to learn how to assemble the magneto and clean up the parts, you see they'd come in rather an oily state, so you had to clean up the parts, and then learn how to assemble but I didn't get very far with that in as much as I had a throat 
i
nfection, I've had that quite a lot of times, and I had to go back home. And be in the country. I remember Simms, himself, I had to go to see him because I was ill and not very well, he said "Why did you come to London? Did you think the pavements were ma
d
e of gold?" I said "No, I just wanted to do something different, not so much in the country." And he thought and he said "Now you're a country girl, you should go back to the country. I think it would be better for your health." So he arranged and I went 
back then. And a lot of the things are rather vague, onwards you know, for quite a few years. I can't remember very much about it. I think one was concerned with the war, and..
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, was that towards the end of it? Or nearer the beginning of the War?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh, nearer the beginning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was that after you'd given up the place at Kingham?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 It was the next step, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the hairdressing, was that after war work, or attempted war work? at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14958908\charrsid2904646 
Simms?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think that was after. Yes, I think that was after I tried that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 But it was still while the war was on do you think? That you did the hairdressing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I think so, but I'm a little vague about this you know. Its like parts of my life I can remember the early days very
 much more vivid, then came a period a few years of my life I can scarcely remember anything that happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. Sort of your late teens it was, really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Sort of early twenties? Do you remember anything about the lodgings you had in London while you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well I lodged with some people, it was an old couple, oldish, well to me they were old, I suppose they were middle aged. And they were some people that, friends of my mothers, some friends of my mothers, and they looked afte
r me, you know, like parents. And you know, saw that I had my proper food, and that sort of thing. I rather enjoyed that life, but there it was you see I had to give it up. How long do you think you did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I suppose getting on for a year. About that. I can't really give you..
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Oh no, no, it doesn't matter. I'm just interested to know, you know, I'm quite interested to know, because I'm in a way surprised you went back to London, as you'd been so unhappy there before.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes that was an amazin
g thing. But you see, I wasn't in the same, I was a more independent person. But you see, what I didn't like about London was, well of course, I was very young the first time I went, and to be so restricted, and with the older, all these old servants, who
, you know, I didn't really appreciate very much and such a very hard and dull life for a country girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you meet people then, you know, and have boyfriends and girlfriends in London your second time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 In London the second time, yes, I had a bo
yfriend there, yes. And of course, I made friends with the girls. We had a workshop where we had to clean the parts. The magnetos of the cars would come over. It was the Simms Motor Units, an American firm, I think it was, and we went to start, we had to 
clean the parts, they were all separate. A magneto contains a lot of parts you know, and we had to clean them and try to learn how to assemble a magneto. Which was interesting but I didn't get very far with it as I told you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And the couple that you lodged with. They didn't mind your going out at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I didn't go out at night much, oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The boyfriend didn't take you out at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh no. No. But on Saturdays, Saturday afternoons. Saturday would be a holiday. And Sunday. Then I would b
e invited, you know, out. But I don't remember doing anything much and of course never very much money, you see with just little earnings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Do you remember what you did earn there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I can't remember at all. I cannot remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. It doesn't really matter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 'Twasn't very much. I didn't have many luxuries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Not when you had paid your board and lodging!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I remember once going home at night. I loved chestnuts, roasted chestnuts, and they used to have them in the streets, roasting che
stnuts. And I'd only got enough for my bus fare or tram fare whatever it was, at that time. I had to go some little distance from where I was working to my lodgings. And chestnuts were being roasted in the street, over a brazier, you know, they smelt so g
ood. And so I spent my penny or tuppence, whatever it was, bus fare, and had the chestnuts and walked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 And do you remember during that period if you went home at all? Or had a holiday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Well I wasn't there long enough really, I think, to. When I 
went home I stayed. I couldn't afford, you see, the fare, and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Did you get sort of tired of domestic service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes. I hated it. I hated it. And I didn't like servants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. So you were never happy with your employees, as it were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
No. No. Because they were older, you see, and there was always a separation, a division, two sides, you see, and they were none of them, all, they were seldom all friendly together, and I was the go between and they'd, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was this the same in your other jobs too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well no, I never took another job where I was under again. No I never did that again. I stayed at home. After I left this job, I told you, I got myself into rather a bad state because I wouldn't eat. I deliberately, b
ecause I couldn't complain. Never allowed to complain, so I didn't eat my food and I got rather miserable, and not too well, you see, a little anaemic, so I went home then, and then I stayed. You see my mother was still at the rectory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Again, in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
I was anxious to get rid of, get away from domestic work, and I thought if I learned the job properly, this engineering firm, learn how all the inside of a car, and all that side, you see the magneto I started with. How to clean and I was just
 learning how to assemble a magneto, there are a lot of parts, when I had to leave because of this throat trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 How did you hear about the work in London with Simms and Co.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 I cannot remember. I've often wondered since, how I heard about it. 
But I was very happy there, but rather a country girl, you see among town girls, and you see there was a long workshop and one side were the men and the other side the girls. And the men used to play tricks by giving us electric shocks. "Oh, hold this for
 
me, oh come here a moment, would you mind holding this for me." And give me an electric shock. And of course, I was the country girl of the lot. And of course, I was really a greenhorn. And all sorts of things were said which I didn't understand at all, y
ou know. A lot of leg pulling. But they were very good to me. Rather nice to me and it was a very good firm to work for.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 The employers were good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Oh yes. It was American I think. Yes, Simms Motor Units.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were you a member of the Trade Union there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. Not in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Was there a Union at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 No. I think one had to belong. There was, one had to put stamps on a card. What was it, the panel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Insurance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Yes, insurance stamps I think. I think that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16269226 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 Were you all on the same footing, the workers there? Or were some of them...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5774122 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7276286\charrsid2904646 
Well in this workshop, I mean, there was all jokes. Oh it was so jolly everybody laughing and joking and leg pulling. And a bit of flirting went on of course with the older ones, I was rather a greenhorn but, country bumpkin, you know.
